<FIRST>r i PM-QuakeAnniversary     12-04 1060</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quake Anniversary,1096</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Year After Quake, Leninakan Mired in Mud and Memories</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINAKAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after an earthquake smashed
northwestern Armenia into rubble, the city of Leninakan is a
shantytown of mud and memories.
   The Garapetyans do laundry by boiling their clothes in a bucket
on a tiny wood stove. The stove also heats a makeshift cabin they
built from remains of their former apartment building next door.
   Far above, rain lashes the wallpaper of their old living room on
the fourth floor, which was exposed when the side of the building
sheared off.
   ``We're afraid of living in a large building again,'' Meruzhan
Garapetyan said.
   Popular songs speak of the disaster of Dec. 7, 1988, when an
earthquake measuring 6.9 on the Richter scale killed at least
25,000 people and destroyed the homes of 500,000 more.
   ``Oh earthquake, what have you done?'' one asks. ``Why did you
leave so many parents without their children? ... You covered them
with stones and dirt and left their parents in tears.''
   The Armenian relief agency Search says 20,000 people still are
missing, 2,000 of them children. Daily life is slogging through
mud, relying on relatives and wondering when normality will return.
   A quake of 7.1 magnitude in the San Francisco area on Oct. 17
killed only 66 people. Damage was estimated at $7 billion, but much
of the destruction was cleared and service restored within weeks.
   In Leninakan, Armenia's second-largest city, Vartan Oganisyan
and his family of five live in a shack made from bits of sheet
metal, wood scraps, tar paper and salvaged window frames.
   Other families crowd into half-shattered buildings, construction
huts, army tents, round Mongolian yurts, abandoned railway cars and
even gasoline tanks fitted with doors and windows. A few open
cooking fires can be seen in the twilight.
   Electrical power is intermittent as Armenia enters the bitter
Soviet winter.
   Children bundle up for classes in temporary, unheated buildings.
They wake up crying at night and run from classrooms in fright at
the slightest noise.
   After school they play ``earthquake,'' recreating the disaster
in the muddy streets.
   Hundreds of people go to the huge city cemetery after work. Many
graves are marked only by the flowers relatives leave.
   Sofik Torunyan, who lost both children, was there on what would
have been her daughter's 20th birthday, with a cake fashioned from
carnations.
   ``Oh, my young daughter! Oh, my love!'' she wailed, holding onto
a friend. ``Why didn't I die, too, so I would not have to live
without you?''
   People struggle on, helping each other. Hospitality and pride
remain.
   A dozen families share the only bathroom on their block that
still works. A boy paints the window frame in his family's shack.
Visitors are offered coffee and sweets, but often there is no
electricity to boil water.
   Maria Tumanyan, who lives in the ground floor of a severely
cracked five-story building, insists that ``we're making great
progress.'' She concentrates on the vast stretches cleared of
broken concrete and twisted metal, not the rubble remaining.
   The town of Spitak was leveled. Kirovakan and 300 villages were
shattered.
   In Leninakan, which had 235,000 residents, the quake destroyed
99 nine-story apartment buildings, 10 schools and every factory,
officials said.
   Reconstruction has lagged badly. Nikolai I. Ryzhkov, the Soviet
premier, said in November that the crash program to rebuild in two
years already was a year behind schedule, meaning virtually nothing
had been accomplished.
   Residents blame disorganization, central planning's failure to
supply enough building materials and a two-month blockade of
Armenia by ethnic enemies in neighboring Azerbaijan.
   Many foreigners building schools and hospitals went home because
supply shipments were held up on rail lines in Azerbaijan.
   By early November, only three new buildings had been completed,
all by the army for the army.
   Karlin Ambartsumyan, chairman of the city Communist Party
committee, still hopes to move 4,000 families into a vast new
suburb before year's end, but even that would be only one-fifth as
many as planned.
   For now, Ambartsumyan is concentrating on getting the remaining
homeless among the 190,000 people now living in Leninakan into
construction huts and other temporary housing, and getting heat for
them before winter.
   Svetlana Asaturyan lives in one such hut, generously called a
``little house'' in Russian but in reality a two-room insulated
packing crate.
   She and her family of five must haul water from a block away,
use nearby bushes as a toilet and travel to a relative's place for
showers. Her washing flaps over a sea of mud.
   Mrs. Asaturyan is grateful, however, because they used to be in
the remains of the towel factory where she once worked, and where
30 of her co-workers were killed.
   Her ``little house,'' like thousands of others, showed up
without a door, window glass, heater, wiring or furniture. It was
vandalized en route, apparently by Azerbaijanis, whom the Armenians
accuse of stealing or destroying relief supplies.
   When asked about the Soviet leadership's promise to rebuild in
two years, Mrs. Asaturyan said: ``I'll be glad if I get a home
within five years.''
   About 20,000 of the homeless are scheduled to receive apartments
in the new suburb as sections are completed over 18 months. A
forest of 129 cranes towers over the site, and buildings faced with
local salmon-colored stone gleam in the sun.
   Because nine-story apartment blocks shoddily built of pre-formed
concrete panels collapsed in the quake, the new buildings are made
by assembling vault-like precast rooms, foreman Gennady Pogosov
said. None is more than four stories high.
   In May, a commission of the ruling Politburo blamed most of the
deaths on shoddy construction and gave its findings to prosecutors.
No charges have been filed, said Haik Minasyan, an Armenian
government spokesman.
   Only a few projects are under way in the city itself. On the
central square, a statue of Vladimir I. Lenin looks over a scene of
devastation: a ruined school, department store, government
building, post office, shops and a sock factory.
   Cafes and movie theaters are gone. So are most food stores, and
shopping sometimes amounts to picking over piles of cabbages and
potatoes at what remains of the bus station.
   Ambartsumyan said experts had ruled out reconstruction on half
the original city lots because the ground is too unstable.
</TEXT>
