<FIRST>r a PM-ConfessionControversy     12-04 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Confession Controversy,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man at Center of Church-State Debate Pleads Guilty</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY SPRINGS, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A showdown between three
Pentecostal ministers and a prosecutor over the confidentiality of
a burglary suspect's confession in church ended when the man
pleaded guilty to grand larceny.
   Larry Yost, who was to have gone on trial today, entered the
plea Monday under an agreement reached at a hearing before Morgan
County Circuit Judge Thomas Steptoe. Yost, 35, had been charged
with the more serious crime of breaking and entering.
   ``It's over with,'' said a jubilant Rev. Shirley Hiles. ``We
don't have to testify, nor do we have to refuse to testify.''
   Yost's hearing came after Steptoe refused for the second time to
excuse Mrs. Hiles, 51; her husband, the Rev. Jack Hiles, the
58-year-old founder and pastor of the Word of Deliverance
Association; and the Rev. Wilda Maconaughey from subpoenas issued
by county Prosecutor Charles Trump IV.
   Yost, a Berkeley Springs carpenter who has been held at the
Eastern Regional Jail in lieu of $15,000 bond since January, was
sentenced to a year in the county jail, with credit for time served.
   ``I'm happy, the whole church is happy,'' Yost said in a
telephone interview from jail. ``I didn't want to see the ministers
go to jail. And I should be out in a month if everything goes
right.''
   Last December, a sobbing Yost interrupted a service at the
church, confessing that he didn't try to stop the break-in at his
uncle's building supply store.
   The ministers had said Trump wanted them to testify at Yost's
trial, and maintained authorities had crossed the boundary between
God's work and their own.
   Steptoe first refused to block the subpoenas Nov. 15, ruling
that state law does not protect confessions made to clergy. The
state Supreme Court last week refused to hear the ministers'
challenge.
   West Virginia and New Hampshire are the only states that do not
protect confessions made to ministers or priests in criminal cases,
said Richard Gay, the ministers' lawyer. West Virginia, however,
does allow statements made to clergy about divorce proceedings to
be kept secret, Gay said.
   Yost said earlier that just before Christmas he told the
congregation that he watched and did nothing as another man broke
into his uncle's store last December. He denied having a role in
the robbery.
   ``It was such a burden on my heart, I just had to go to my
church and get it off my chest,'' Yost said.
   Gay said another attorney has contacted him about drafting
legislation to protect clergy and penitents in similar situations.
   ``I was disappointed the Supreme Court didn't take this
opportunity to examine the issue,'' he said. ``It's a fundamental
issue that cries out to be heard.''
   The U.S. Constitution provides for freedom of religion. Gay also
argued that the state constitution prohibits anyone from being
subpoenaed, jailed or arrested based upon a religious belief.
   The importance of protecting confessions made to clergy has been
recognized since the days of the Roman Empire, according to the
Rev. James Burtchaell, a Roman Catholic professor of theology at
the University of Notre Dame.
   ``Society has said that it is of paramount importance that
people be able to confide in clergymen or attorneys or their
doctors without fear of it being disclosed,'' said Burtchaell, who
has taught a course preparing seminarians to hear confessions.
   However, Burtchaell added that the ministers' case may have been
weakened because Yost gave his confession publicly.
   Public confession of sins is a basic tenet of the Pentacostal
church. ``Jesus never took anyone aside and had them confess their
sins in private,'' Mrs. Hiles said.
   Hiles said the church's jail ministry had been hurt since
inmates heard of the subpoenas.
   ``They don't know if they can trust us anymore,'' Hiles said.
``They're saying `Why should I tell you anything? If I do, they
might force you to say it in court.'''
</TEXT>
