<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 2352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Eliana-Funeral     12-04 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eliana-Funeral,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young AIDS Victim Laid to Rest</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TP5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old girl whose life was cut short
by AIDS was laid to rest Monday with balloons, songs and a
procession past the federal courthouse where she won her fight go
to school.
   In a 90-minute service at a funeral home, Eliana Martinez was
eulogized as a frail, innocent child barely 3 feet tall who never
learned to speak but taught adults the language of love.
   ``Eliana taught us to hug and to kiss,'' said her mother, Rosa.
``She takes a part of me with her.''
   At Myrtle Hill Cemetery, the mentally disabled girl's small,
white casket was opened and Mrs. Martinez kissed her adopted
daughter goodbye.
   Mourners released balloons into the air, and the casket was
lowered into the ground. Friends were invited to throw of colored
beads into the grave along with the traditional handfuls of dirt.
   Strands of the colorful glass beads which Eliana liked had been
placed around her neck, and her Raggedy Ann doll laid on her chest.
She was in a white dress with blue ribbons.
   The funeral home was decorated with small balloons. Larger red
and purple balloons adorned the four white limousines that carried
relatives and friends on the 15-mile procession to the cemetery,
passing Eliana's school, school board offices and the courthouse.
   More than 125 people who gathered at the funeral home watched a
slide show that showed the wide-eyed smiling girl at home, the
beach, school, the county fair _ and the hospital.
   Playing in the background was ``Everybody's Child,'' a song
composed by family friend Linda Castellano.
   Kenneth Thomas told mourners that Eliana was ``a little girl
with a gigantic heart (who) taught us so many things _ love,
respect.''
   Speech therapist Dan McClowrey said Eliana did not learn to
speak, but ``spoke so loud to all those who were willing to hear.''
   ``She showed me that loving is all there is,'' he said, his
voice breaking. ``It was interesting to meet someone who turned the
tables on me.''
   Mrs. Martinez adopted Eliana, who died a week ago, when she was
11 months old after hearing a radio appeal for a sickly child
abandoned in a hospital in Puerto Rico.
   Four years later, the family learned that Eliana had acquired
immune deficiency syndrome. By the time she was four months old,
Eliana had received 38 transfusions, and doctors believed she
received tainted blood.
   Education officials tried to restrict Eliana's instruction to
her home, fearing she might transmit AIDS to other pupils. Mrs.
Martinez sued, saying the child needed contact with other children
to develop.
   A federal judge said the child could attend classes only if she
sat inside a specially-built glass booth until she was toilet
trained and stopped sucking her fingers. Mrs. Martinez appealed and
won after a two-year battle.
   Eliana went to school this year, but became too ill to continue
after three weeks in class.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
