<DOCNO> AP891204-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Summit-Malta     12-04 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Malta,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summit Offers Cure for Country With Identity Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before the dockside summit, this tiny
island nation suffered from an identity crisis. Maltese passports
even included a map to show doubtful foreigners that the country
exists.
   But that was before President Bush and Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev came to Malta and put this rocky Mediterranean
archipelago back on everyone's map.
   The passports will be changed shortly after the first of the
year, said a slightly embarrassed Richard Cachia Caruana, the aide
to the prime minister who was in charge of organizing Malta's part
in the summit.
   ``That was a lack of self-confidence by the previous
government,'' he said, shaking his head. ``It's degrading.''
   Any lingering doubts by the Maltese about their country's
identity seemed to have been dispelled by the superpower summit, by
the words and images beamed abroad by about 2,500 journalists
covering the George Bush-Mikhail Gorbachev talks.
   ``For Malta itself, the summit has been very positive. It has
shown Malta can cope even with the necessary organization for a
summit like this,'' Prime Minister Edward Fenech Adami said in an
interview after the summit closed Sunday.
   ``Some people were skeptical that Malta could do it. I think we
proved ourselves,'' he added.
   Not even the fierce December gale that drove the summit at sea
to the side of a pier could dampen the enthusiasm of the prime
minister.
   ``Well, I don't mind the weather at all. If anything, it has
proved I was correct when I suggested that the meetings should not
be held in Marsaxlokk but in some other bay, such as Grand Harbor,
which is more protected than Marsaxlokk Bay,'' he said.
   Cachia Caruana said the Soviets and Americans first planned to
hold the summit at sea, perhaps in Maltese territorial waters, but
that the prime minister had convinced them of the hazards of
December.
   ``Within 24 hours we made the point that this is December and
that these things can happen,'' he said.
   Still, he acknowledges the images of thunderous waves crashing
against the rocks below the 16th Century fortifications of the
capital Valletta won't help the island's winter tourism.
   ``In terms of what we had hoped to achieve overall, the tourism
objectives probably will not be met,'' said Cachia Caruana. ``But
our principal objective, especially in the United States, was name
identification.
   ``Just being at the center of the world stage for two days in a
way helped give us that anyway.''
   Cachia Caruana said Malta wants to base its growth on business,
not just tourism, and that's why the summit will help.
   ``Our greatest objective is dragging the economy into the last
decade of the 20th Century,'' he said.
   Still, in those first few hours after the departure of the
leaders of the United States and the Soviet Union, the chief
Maltese organizer of the summit was relieved that it was over.
   ``It's been a hell of an experience. We had a situation here
where the journalists outnumbered the army by two-to-one,'' said
Cachia Caruana.
   ``It's back to business as usual tomorrow. We will assume it was
a dream and forget all about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
