<FIRST>r w PM-LandInventory     12-04 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Land Inventory,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embargoed for release 10 a.m. EST; time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wind Damage to Cropland Increases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soil erosion from water runoff declined
between 1982 and 1987, but wind damage to the nation's cropland
increased slightly, an Agriculture Department report said today.
   The latest National Resources Inventory released by the
department's Soil Conservation Service said ``sheet and rill''
erosion by water dropped to an average of 3.8 tons per acre
annually from 4.3 tons during the five-year period.
   Wind erosion, however, increased 0.1 ton per acre to 3.3 tons
per acre annually. Most wind erosion of cropland is concentrated in
the Great Plains states.
   Total sheet-and-rill erosion of cropland was reported at 1.6
billion tons per year and wind erosion at nearly 1.4 billion tons
annually.
   The national summary of the NRI _ a benchmark reference used
widely by government and private conservationists and others _ will
be followed next year by a complete report, officials said.
   Wilson Scaling, chief of the Soil Conservation Service, said the
report includes information on erosion, cropland use, irrigation,
tillage and conservation needs.
   The area of rural non-federal land totals 1.4 billion acres, the
report said. Of this, 422.8 million acres are cropland; 401.7
million rangeland; 394.5 million forestland; and 59.9 million in
``minor land uses.''
   From 1982 to 1987, it said, 4 million acres of rural non-federal
land were converted to urban and transportation uses, which include
roads and airports.
   Cropland increased 1.4 million acres in the five years to 422.8
million from 421.4 million, while pastureland declined 2.3 million
acres and rangeland dropped 6 million acres.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
