<FIRST>r a PM-ThinBlueLine     12-04 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thin Blue Line,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Randall Dale Adams' First Return to Dallas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randall Dale Adams, who was freed from prison
after his case was documented in the movie ``The Thin Blue Line,''
said it felt strange to return to the city where he was convicted
of killing a policeman.
   Adams' first return to Dallas since his release from state
prison last March was because of a benefit dinner for an
organization that investigates the cases of people who may have
been wrongly convicted.
   Adams, who now in Columbus, Ohio, spent 12 years behind bars for
the 1976 shooting death of the policeman.
   ``Being back here is a little strange. You can understand that
the last time I was here I was pretty anxious to leave,'' Adams
said Saturday night at the dinner for Justice Denied Research Inc.
   ``The Thin Blue Line'' questioned the testimony of prosecution
witnesses in the case. A state appeals court later overturned the
conviction and authorities chose not to seek a retrial.
   Adams was beginning a 12-day tour of Italy this week to
correspond with the European premiere of ``The Thin Blue Line'' and
speak at an annual meeting of Amnesty International.
   Adams, accompanied by his mother, Mildred Adams, said he stopped
in Dallas to encourage the efforts of Justice Denied Research,
which is led by Jim Humphreys.
   Humphreys obtained information that was instrumental in the
release of Lenell Geter, an engineer from South Carolina who spent
two years in Texas prisons for a robbery before another suspect was
identified.
</TEXT>
