<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0873 12-04 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0873,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Tokyo, Stocks Regain Losses</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS with xx grafs to UPDATE with closing figures. Picks up
5th pvs, `Traders said ...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against the Japanese yen in Tokyo
on Monday, while the leading index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange won
back Friday's losses and rose to another record high.
   The dollar closed at 143.48 yen, up 0.40 yen from Friday's close
of 143.08 yen. It opened at 143.37, its low for the day, and ranged
as high as 143.70 yen in mixed trading.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which lost 136.11 points on Friday, rose 171.19 points, or
0.46 percent, to close at 37,303.87.
   It was the highest closing ever for the market's main barometer.
The previous record closing was set Thursday, when the Nikkei index
closed at 37,268.79.
   Traders had predicted the dollar would range between 143.40 yen
and 143.80 yen during the Tokyo trading day, saying a general lack
of interest should keep the market fairly quiet.
   Traders said the quiet holiday mood should continue during a
week which promises little fresh economic news to trade on until
Friday's report on U.S. unemployment data for November.
   The market will watch Friday's report carefully for clues on
possible easing moves by the U.S. Federal Reserve.
   ``Political developments in Europe are fairly difficult for the
Tokyo market to interpret,'' one dealer said of the weekend's U.S
-Soviet summit.
</TEXT>
