<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AMAFinances     12-04 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AMA Finances,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMA Executive Admits Errors in Financial Flap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON STATON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Medical Association's top executive
said he made mistakes in approving two money-losing internal
financial deals, but denied that the resulting controversy spurred
him to retire.
   ``I accept responsibility for the errors and the changes that
are needed to prevent their recurrence,'' AMA Executive Vice
President Dr. James H. Sammons told the opening ceremony of the
group's mid-year meeting.
   Sammons and Dr. John J. Ring, chairman of the board of trustees,
said in speeches to the AMA House of Delegates that Sammons' plans
to retire at the end of his current contract were known months ago.
   The 425 delegates are meeting through Wednesday to set AMA
policy on numerous national health-care issues, but the internal
financial controversy has captured much of their attention. The
Chicago-based AMA is the nation's largest organization for doctors,
with nearly 300,000 members.
   The controversy centers on revelations this fall that Sammons
approved a $353,000 reimbursement to a former AMA executive for
losses in a 1987 high-risk stock market fund, and a 1985 loan to
another AMA executive to buy a high-price condominium during the
latter's divorce.
   The executive involved in the stock-market loss has promised to
pay back the money with interest. The recipient of the 1985 loan
later defaulted, costing the AMA $50,000 to foreclose.
   Ring told the delegates an investigation is continuing and a
full report will be made to the House of Delegates. He said the
board would take steps so that ``this will not happen again.''
   The board on Saturday issued a report saying Sammons acted
within his authority in the two deals, but ``failed to follow the
usual fiscal policies and procedures.''
   AMA spokesman Mark Stuart said trustees declined to elaborate.
   The board also said it had accepted Sammons' plan to retire,
effective March 31, 1991.
   Stuart said it was unclear why the board had included the
retirement plans in the report on the deals. Sammons, who is widely
respected for rescuing the AMA from financial disaster when he took
the job in 1974, plans to give up day-to-day management of the AMA
at the end of next year.
   The board report also proposed a restructuring of its committees
and hiring of an outside accounting firm. It said the board would
set tighter fiscal limits on the authority of the executive vice
president, but did not elaborate.
   The House of Delegates also will consider a resolution passed
last month by the Washington State Medical Association urging
Sammons be placed on administrative leave until the investigation
is completed.
   On Sunday, Secretary of Education Lauro Cavazos asked the
physicians for help in improving and restructuring the nation's
education system. He asked the physicians to help raise public
awareness of the nation's educational shortcomings.
   During the meetings, the AMA delegates also will consider
reports and resolutions that would:
   _ Acknowledge a patient's right to basic and essential health
care;
   _ Establish policies regarding ``maternal-fetal conflict,'' such
as when an expectant mother refuses medical treatment that would
benefit her fetus;
   _ Encourage health-insurance companies to develop reduced-cost
coverage for non-smokers;
   _ Urge a lowering of the blood-alcohol level to 0.05 percent for
determination of drunken driving;.
   _ Work toward listing tobacco as a contributing factor on death
certificates.
</TEXT>
