<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BoatSunk     12-04 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat Sunk,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Die As Charter Fishing Boat Sinks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials located the wreck of a fishing
boat that sank in the main channel entrance to New York Harbor,
killing two people, and warned other boats to avoid the spot.
   The 110-foot Bronx Queen sank Saturday afternoon with 19 people
aboard. All were pulled from the water, but two men in their 50s
who were among the passengers on the chartered fishing trip died
later of hypothermia. Three people remained hospitalized today.
   Lt. Craig Lloyd of the Coast Guard operations center in Boston
said Sunday a Coast Guard helicopter had found the spot where the
Bronx Queen sank.
   ``Our concern is that it's a hazard to navigation,'' Lloyd said.
   The captain, 26-year-old Jack Chale, said the boat was in 40
feet of water ``when we hit something, hit a submerged object.
Whatever it was, I have no idea. I never saw it.''
   The boat immediately began taking on water and went down at the
harbor entrance about 15 miles southeast of the Verrazano Narrows
Bridge, which connects Staten Island and the borough of Brooklyn.
   Melissa Rivera, Chale's girlfriend, said she was inside the boat
when she heard the whistle announcing it was time to head back to
the Bronx, the boat's port.
   She went out to join her grandmother, mother and aunt on deck
and ``I saw the back of the boat was all full of water.''
   The passengers helped each other don life preservers and jumped
into the water to be rescued because Coast Guard vessels could not
get close enough to the sinking boat, Ms. Rivera said.
   They were picked up by rescue boats.
   ``We didn't even feel the cold of the water until we were out of
the water. Everything happened so fast,'' she said.
</TEXT>
