<FIRST>r a PM-Dinkins-Stock     12-04 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dinkins-Stock,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Attorney Probes Dinkins Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor-elect David Dinkins said he was not
worried by a federal probe into a stock transfer to his son, said
to be part of a larger investigation into a cable television
franchise.
   ``I'm confident this inquiry will reveal that there's nothing
with which I need to be concerned,'' Dinkins said Sunday. ``Those
of us in public life are subject to criticism and scrutiny of all
sorts over time.''
   Dinkins said the investigation stems from a suggestion by his
defeated opponent in the Nov. 7 mayoral election, Republican
Rudolph Giuliani, who said during the campaign that the stock deal
should be examined.
   Charles Stillman, an attorney for Dinkins, described the federal
investigation as ``Rudy Giuliani's last hurrah.'' Giuliani is the
former Manhattan U.S. attorney.
   The Daily News reported Sunday that Andrew Maloney, U.S.
attorney based in Brooklyn, is investigating the transaction of
stock by Dinkins to his son, David Jr.
   Investigators are trying to determine whether Dinkins
transferred Inner City Broadcasting Corp. stock to his son through
a genuine transaction in 1985, how much the stock was worth and
whether all due taxes were paid, the News reported.
   Inner City owns several radio stations and one of its
subsidiaries has a substantial interest in Queens Innerunity Cable
Systems, a cable franchise. Inner City's chairman, former Manhattan
Borough President Percy Sutton, is a longtime friend of Dinkins.
   Dinkins has said he first acquired stock in the privately held
company in 1972 and his holdings grew to 588 shares, largely
through stock splits.
   After his election as Manhattan borough president in 1985,
Dinkins said, he began transferring the stock to his son to avoid a
conflict between his position on the city Board of Estimate and the
board's role in regulating cable television.
   Ann Driscoll, a spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney, characterized
the investigation as a ``preliminary inquiry into some financial
transactions.'' She refused to elaborate.
   During the campaign, it was revealed that Dinkins had not paid a
gift tax. Dinkins released a handwritten note, dated Oct. 30, 1985,
in which his son agreed to buy the stock. But Dinkins declined to
release financial or corporate records that might further document
the transaction.
   As part of the investigation, the News said, the age of the
paper and ink are being tested to determine whether the note was
written in 1985 or during the campaign. There also are plans to
analyze the handwriting, the newspaper said.
   The city's Department of Investigation is conducting a separate,
previously disclosed probe into whether Dinkins filed misleading
financial disclosure forms pertaining to the stock.
</TEXT>
