<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WomenLawyers     12-04 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Women Lawyers,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Sexual Harassment in Large U.S. Law Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sexual harassment and limited opportunity for
advancement are part of a woman's work environment at large U.S.
law firms, a study says.
   The survey, published in today's edition of the National Law
Journal, was based on responses from 918 women lawyers who work in
large law firms in 13 cities.
   Most women said they were at a disadvantage when it came to
advancement. Sixty-four percent said men had a better chance at
gaining management positions and 49 percent said men were more
likely to be promoted.
   According to the survey, 60 percent of respondents said they had
experienced unwanted sexual attention, such as sexual teasing,
remarks or questions, from co-workers or clients. Nearly one-third
said they had experienced sexual looks or gestures.
   The lawyers who responded to the survey earned between $50,000
and $250,000 a year. Thirteen percent said they felt their male
counterparts earned higher salaries and bigger bonuses.
   The majority of the women felt they had to give up time for
family, friends or outside interests to pursue their law careers,
but they indicated that male lawyers made the same sacrifices.
   The survey participants worked in Atlanta, Boston, Chicago,
Cleveland, Dallas, Houston, Los Angeles, Miami, Philadelphia, New
York, San Francisco, Tampa and Washington, D.C.
   The survey was conducted by the National Law Journal and West
Publishing of Minneapolis, Minn., the nation's largest publisher of
legal publications.
</TEXT>
