<FIRST>r i PM-DepressedCommunists     12-04 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Depressed Communists,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Down And Out, Hoping For Reincarnation In Face of Renewed Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ONDREJ HEJMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Its monopoly on power gone, the
Communist Party is on the run, looking desperately for new strength
in the forthcoming political battle for control.
   Communists were the vanguard of reform during the ill-fated
``Prague Spring'' under Alexander Dubcek until the spontaneous
freedom movement was squelched by Soviet tanks in 1968.
   But new forces seem to be in charge this time around.
   ``The future requires giving up the monopoly of power,'' new
party leader Karel Urbanek said last week.
   A 77-year-old veteran Communist says it's ``hard to foresee any
kind of real political comeback for the party, now that the lies
and incompetence are here for everyone to see, hear and read about.
   The man, requesting anonymity, said ``only a miracle'' can save
the Communist leadership from collapse now that the 2-week-old
peaceful popular revolt has shaken it to the core.
   In a stormy party Central Commitee meeting Nov. 24, former
premier Lubomir Strougal called the demonstrations ``an expression
of civil dissatisfaction with us, our way of leadership and rule.''
   ``Let us admit our share of responsibility,'' the party daily
Rude Pravo quoted him as saying.
   Days later, the party decided to revise its stand on the 1968
Warsaw Pact invasion, part of its speedy move to jettison the
leaders and policies of the last 21 years.
   Those aging party members, who carried the torch of ``real
socialism'' from the 1948 Communist takeover until November 1989,
have been spared a younger Communist generation's worries about the
party's future.
   ``I'm of the opinion that the entire Communist Party should be
disbanded and possibly associate under a different name, if we find
the right program and people willing to do it,'' Vit Spanhel, 43, a
Communist journalist, told The Associated Press.
   That has already happened in Hungary, where the unpopular
Communist Party dissolved itself last month and christened a new
ruling party _ the Socialists _ as part of its attempt to save
itself from overwhelming defeat in free elections next year.
   With a membership of 1.7 million _ roughly one in every six
Czechoslovak adults is a Communist _ the party is still the best
organized political force in the country.
   It may be hit by massive defections now that its power is
eroded. But it still has control of thousands of offices and
factories and many of the people who run them.
   Vaclav Havel, the country's leading dissident and the unofficial
leader of the Civic Forum opposition coalition, says that by
comparison his group is composed of ``political amateurs.''
   The country's Socialist Party and People's Party, formerly
docile Communist allies, have now begun to flourish in the new
atmosphere of free speech. Membership applications are pouring in,
but both parties still remain comparatively tiny forces of less
than 50,000 members.
   A broad spectrum of several independent parties, similar to that
in Hungary, is expected to emerge before free elections take place,
probably late next year.
   Czechoslovak wits are beginning to mourn the easy target they
found in the Communists for 40 years.
   Hinting at the clumsiness of former leader Milos Jakes and the
depressing obscurity of the new communist chief, the writing on the
subway wall said last week:
   ``Milos, come back, Urbanek is no fun!''
</TEXT>
