<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     12-04 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Attorney General Seeks Lawyer For Accused U.S. Woman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Attorney General
Ramsey Clark says it will be difficult to find a competent lawyer
to defend an American woman accused of hiding weapons for leftist
guerrillas.
   Clark said Sunday that the woman, Jennifer Jean Casolo, had
decided to stand trial in the case rather than be deported.
   He said that even with a good lawyer, ``it would be extremely
difficult if not impossible'' for Ms. Casolo to get a fair trial
amid the pressure of war and the near paranoia about foreigners in
El Salvador.
   Ms. Casolo was due to be arraigned today, he said, most likely
before a military tribunal. He was not sure precisely what charges
would be filed.
   Authorities say they uncovered a huge guerrilla arms stash
buried in her yard. Clark said Ms. Casolo didn't know the munitions
and explosives were there.
   Ms. Casolo, who represents a San Antonio-based ecumenical group
called Christian Educational Seminars, is deeply committed to her
work in El Salvador, he said.
   The formeer attorney general, who has been retained by Ms.
Casolo's family but is not licensed to practice law in El Salvador,
said he had hoped Ms. Casolo would agree to be deported rather than
tried but that is not the case.
   ``Every heart has to be somewhere and her heart chose El
Salvador,'' he said. ``She doesn't want to go home.''
   Clark said Ms. Casolo has begun a ministry inside the jail where
she has been held since her arrest Nov. 26.
   Ms. Casolo, 28, a native of Thomaston, Conn., moved into the
house in May but was not at home for long periods of time,
including all of September, Clark said.
   Ms. Casolo's friends say she is being framed to justify a
government crackdown on churches and humanitarian groups that came
in reaction to a three-week-old guerrilla offensive.
   The rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, has denied
any connection with Ms. Casolo, who was known for her work guiding
visiting church groups and congressional aides.
   The rightist government has imposed a state of siege that
suspends most constitutional rights, and the National Assembly has
passed a severe new anti-terrorism law.
   The bill has not yet been signed by President Alfredo Cristiani.
   Ms. Casolo came to El Salvador in 1985 after working for two
years with Central American refugees in Seattle.
   Authorities say they found more than 20,000 rounds of ammunition
for AK-47 assault rifles, 213 blocks of TNT, detonators, 106 60mm
mortar rounds and other munitions buried in her yard.
   Ms. Casolo is being held in a cell with two other women, Clark
said.
</TEXT>
