<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0558EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pastora     12-04 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pastora,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Commander Zero' Returns, Campaigns For Small Opposition Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eden Pastora, the Sandinista
revolutionary hero turned Contra rebel leader, has ended eight
years of exile and told supporters that neither Moscow nor
Washington should influence Managua.
   The legendary fighter known as Commander Zero was mobbed on his
arrival Sunday at the airport in the Nicaraguan capital.
   A caravan of vehicles carried him and supporters to the former
National Palace, where he and about 20 fighters in 1978 held
legislators hostage until then-President Anastasio Somoza released
50 Sandinista prisoners, including Daniel Ortega and Tomas Borge,
now the president and the interior minister.
   ``I have come to take over the palace that's called Nicaragua,''
Pastora told several hundred supporters, who cheered wildly at the
reference to the bold exploit that made him known worldwide.
   Pastora said the Social Christians _ not the leftist government
or the U.S.-backed opposition coalition _ are the true followers of
Nicaraguan nationalist hero Augusto Cesar Sandino.
   ``We are anti-imperialist with Moscow and we are
anti-imperialist with Washington,'' Pastora told the crowd at the
adjacent Plaza of the Revolution.
   Pastora scoffed at Sandinista accusations that he betrayed the
revolution when he left them to fight in 1983 with the U.S.-backed
Contra rebels.
   He said the Sandinista commanders are the ``true
counterrevolutionaries'' because their standards of living now are
much higher than most Nicaraguans.
   Pastora also said that although he personally respected
opposition presidential candidate Violeta Chamorro, her 14-party
National Opposition Union was made up of opportunists and followers
of the late Somoza.
   Pastora's reception at the airport, organized by two factions of
the Social Christian Party, was the largest by far for any of the
many exiled leaders who have returned to Nicaragua this year to
join the political fight against the Sandinistas.
   On the way downtown, Pastora waved tentatively at people
standing on sidewalks waiting for buses, many of whom stared back
with blank expressions.
   Standing with Pastora were Erick Ramirez of the Social Christian
Party and Mauricio Diaz of the People's Social Christian Party.
   Two months ago Diaz threw his support behind Ramirez's
presidential candidacy after splitting from Ms. Chamorro's
coalition.
   Pastora has run a fishing cooperative in neighboring Costa Rica
since he ended three years with the Contras and quit the armed
struggle against the Sandinistas in 1986.
   When the Sandinistas came to power in 1979 in a popular revolt
that forced Somoza to flee the country, Pastora was named vice
minister of defense and enjoyed wide popularity.
   But the man who called himself a nationalist was at odds with
his more radical leftist comrades and grew disillusioned with the
Sandinista revolution. Some say he grew bitter because he was not
made defense minister.
   Pastora distanced himself from the Sandinistas in 1981, then
dropped from sight.
   He emerged in 1983 and said he would fight the Sandinistas. But
he constantly criticized his Contra colleagues, saying they
misspent money.
   The Contras welcomed the propaganda coup provided by his
defection but also eyed him suspiciously because of his independent
streak and former Sandinista ties.
   Pastora survived a 1984 bomb explosion that killed four people,
including an American journalist, during a news conference in his
jungle hideout on the Costa Rican border.
   In 1986, the CIA withdrew financial support for Pastora and soon
after he quit the fight.
</TEXT>
