<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths     12-04 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths,0352</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Tien Lui</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tien Lui, the Chinese-born inventor of
Play-Doh synthetic molding clay, died Thursday. He was believed to
be in his 80s, but there were no records of his birth.
   Lui came to the United States in 1924 to attend Cornell
University. He earned a doctorate in agricultural biology, then
taught pharmaceutical science and conducted research.
   In 1957, Lui was hired by Rainbow Crafts Inc., to develop a soft
sculpting substance that would be easy for small children to use.
Working with Joseph McVicker, whose father owned the company, Lui
formulated Play-Doh.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Joaquim Puig-Antich</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Child psychiatrist Joaquim Puig-Antich, who
helped pioneer the study of depression in children and adolescents,
died of bronchial asthma Saturday at age 45.
   Puig-Antich, who was born in Barcelona, Spain, was one of the
first researchers to recognize the existence of depression in
children and adolescents and advance its study. He also was among
the first to study the use of antidepressant medications by youths.
   Puig-Antich was chief of clinical services and chief of child
and adolescent psychiatry at Western Psychiatric Institute and
Clinic.
   He served on several national committees and on the editorial
boards of some scientific journals.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Dixon</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John W. Dixon, who transformed E-Systems from an
unprofitable electronics concern to a Fortune 500 company, died
Saturday at age 69 following a two-year battle with cancer.
   A former economist for the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics,
Dixon also taught economics at Mississippi Southern University, and
had worked as deputy controller for the Defense Department before
joining Ling Temco Vought in 1962.
   Dixon became president of E-Systems in 1969, when the company
was a subsidiary of Ling Teamco Vought, now LTV. By 1971, its
revenues soared to $168 million and in 1972 it separated from its
parent firm.
   Dixon resigned in 1987 as chairman and chief executive of
E-Systems, which produces electronics for military intelligence and
reconnaissance, electronic warfare, aircraft guidance, navigation,
communications and data systems.
</TEXT>
