<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--PetCemetery     12-04 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Pet Cemetery,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vandals Hit Pet Cemetery; Checkers' Plot OK</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WANTAGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pet cemetery was vandalized, but its most
famous grave, that of Richard Nixon's beloved Checkers, was
untouched, authorities said.
   ``Mischievous kids'' struck at the Bide-A-Wee cemetery on Long
Island early Saturday and kicked over about 200 tombstones, said
police Officer Robert Feeley. Some were broken, he said.
   The tombstone of the cocker spaniel immortalized in a speech by
Nixon when he was a vice presidential candidate was among those
spared.
   In his 1952 ``Checkers'' speech, Nixon rebutted charges that he
illegally accepted gifts from wealthy supporters. He cited the
black-and-white dog, a supporter's gift to his family, as one
contribution he would keep. The family pet died in 1964 at age 12.
   No arrests were made in the vandalism. Feeley said the vandals
were lucky.
   ``None of the animals came back to life, like in `Pet Sematary,'
'' he said of the Stephen King story. ``But it would serve them
right if they did.''
</TEXT>
