<HEAD>Cold Temperatures, Winds Lash Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the country was locked in bitter cold today with frost
as far south as Florida and snow across the Northeast with the wind
chill forecast as low as 50 degrees below zero.
   Strong northerly winds continued to usher arctic air into the
northeastern United States with gusts up to 67 mph at Johnstown,
Pa. Wind chill was expected to dip as low as 50 degrees below zero
in New York state and Vermont.
   Snow was falling in Caribou, Maine, and in Pittsburgh, early
today while gale warnings were in effect along the Maine and North
Carolina coasts.
   On Sunday, squalls left from 6 to 12 inches of snow in Lake and
Geauga counties in northeast Ohio, up to 16 inches in Ashtabula
County and up to a foot of snow over western Pennsylvania.
   Snow also fell Sunday night in the central Appalachians,
including western Maryland.
   Temperatures dipped to 32 degrees today in Jacksonville, Fla.,
and freeze warnings were in effect for northern farming areas of
Florida, but citrus growers said the cold wasn't expected to be
serious enough to cause damage to oranges.
   Frost also was reported in Georgia. Temperatures were in the
teens in central Tennessee.
   Rain in the Northwest extended from Washington to western
Montana, with freezing rain and wind gusts of up to 90 mph in some
parts of Montana. East of the Rockies temperatures in Montana
warmed above 50 degrees.
   Temperatures remained below freezing from Minnesota and northern
Iowa to the Great Lakes region. Highs on Sunday were barely above
zero in eastern Upper Michigan.
   Temperatures reached the 60s and lower 70s across Florida, in
southern Arizona and in much of California on Sunday, with readings
in the lower 80s in Southern California.
