<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Balchowsky     12-04 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Balchowsky,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Services Set for One-Armed Pianist Eddie Balchowsky</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memorial service is planned Thursday for Eddie
Balchowsky, a pianist, artist and poet who lost an arm in the
Spanish Civil War.
   Balchowsky, 73, was killed Wednesday when he either jumped or
fell in front of a train on Chicago's North Side, authorities said.
   Police said witnesses reported that Balchowsky jumped, but
several of his friends said he was under heavy medication and may
have lost his balance.
   ``To me he was Lazarus,'' said Pulitzer Prize-winning author
Studs Terkel. ``Eddie had lived about seven different lives. A
number of times we thought he had died and he'd show up again,
usually with younger and younger girls.''
   In 1937, Balchowsky sailed to Spain to fight on the Loyalist
side in the Spanish Civil War. His recordings of songs during that
time were featured as part of a television documentary, ``The Good
Fight.''
   A machine gun bullet shattered his right arm shortly after he
arrived to fight with other Americans in the Abraham Lincoln
Brigade, said his longtime friend Charles Shields. The arm
eventually had to be amputated.
   He did paintings that were almost surrealistic in nature, and
once had a one-man show at the Art Institute of Chicago, Shields
said Sunday.
   Balchowsky, who played piano accompaniment for folk singer Pete
Seeger and the late black singer and actor Paul Robeson, continued
his painting and music until his death.
   Balchowsky is survived by his two daughters, Elizabeth and
Renya, and two grandchildren.
</TEXT>
