<FIRST>u i PM-Czech-Border 1stLd-Writethru   12-04 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czech-Border, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0476,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovaks Celebrate Open Borders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with relatively light flow of travelers;
picks up 5th pvs, ``This is...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRATISLAVA, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Borders to the West opened
today and Czechs and Slovaks crossed over them by the thousands as
their country's Communist authorities allowed the first
unrestricted travel in decades.
   ``Maybe this is truly freedom,'' said Stanislaw Balaz, who drove
through the Bratislava-Berg crossing with his wife and 14-year-old
daughter en route to Vienna, 42 miles away.
   The new open-border policy took effect at midnight. Balaz's car
was among more than 100 lined up at the crossing when the
Czechoslovak and Austrian border guards shook hands, then opened
the barrier at 12:04 a.m.
   Czechoslovak border guards reported a relatively light flow of
traffic at the 20 rail and road crossings to Austria throughout the
morning _ probably a reflection of today being a regular working
day.
   Austrian border officials said about 900 Czechoslovak cars had
passed through the Bratislava-Berg crossing by noon.
   At other crossings, the number of Czechoslovaks traveling to
Austria was much smaller.
   ``Instead of a storm, just a breeze,'' the Austria Press Agency
headlined a report, referring to the unexpectedly low number of
visitors.
   The news agency said most of the Czechoslovaks were sightseeing
and few had enough convertible currency for shopping.
   However, for those who had lined up at the Bratislava-Berg
crossing, the mood was ebullient as the barrier lifted.
   ``This is an indescribable feeling,'' said Jan Spurny, 25, as he
and his brother, Dusan, drove their yellow Wartburg sedan onto
Austrian territory.
   Television lights and a small crowd of well-wishers with a sign
reading ``Welcome to Austria'' greeted the new arrivals.
   The Communist government announced Thursday that all obstacles
to travel to the West would be removed. It was among the
concessions granted after weeks of pro-democracy demonstrations by
hundreds of thousands of people.
   The move came after the East German government, spurred by
similar mass protests, announced nearly one month ago that it was
opening its Western borders, including the Berlin Wall.
   In Czechoslovakia, travel regulations introduced in 1987 had
made visits to the West easier for Czechoslovaks than for most
citizens of other Soviet-bloc countries, but there were still
formidable bureaucratic obstacles.
   Before the borders opened today, those seeking to go West needed
a passport. They also needed authorization from the police, from
their workplace or school and in some cases from local Communist
Party officials to get an exit visa. They also had to have
invitations from relatives or friends in the West.
   Now they need only to show their passports and fill out a brief
questionnaire giving their names, addresses, the country they will
visit and the duration of their stay.
   Only one Czechoslovak soldier was on duty at the Bratislava-Berg
crossing of a two-lane road when the first Austria-bound cars
arrived about 10 p.m.
   Dusan Spurney, 22, said, ``I'm just going to drive across and
then drive right back. I just want to see if it works.''
</TEXT>
