<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Foreigners 1stLd-Writethru   12-04 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Foreigners, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0486,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snipers Pin Down Hundreds of Foreigners</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th pvs, `At least...' to UPDATE with hospitals correcting
death toll; picks up 5th pvs, `Hundreds of...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OLIVER TEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anyone brave or foolish enough to
venture outside in the country's swankiest district was a target.
   Even nuns were shot at in Makati today, where fighting between
rebel and loyalist soldiers pinned down hundreds of foreigners for
a third day. Insurgent snipers had sheltered themselves in
apartment buildings and hotels.
   Canadian Ambassador Andre Simard said the rebels were using
Americans, Japanese and others as ``human shields'' in their
flagging 4-day-old coup attempt.
   At least three people were reported slain in Makati today and 15
wounded, including one American, in the fighting. Earlier,
spokesmen for the Makati Medical Center said 10 people were killed.
They said the discrepancy was due to an error in records.
   Hundreds of rebel soldiers swarmed into Makati's commercial
district Saturday, turning about 20 luxury hotels and high-rise
apartment and office complexes into snipers' dens.
   They shot at anyone venturing outside.
   ``Literally, we're in the middle,'' said Barbara Julich, a New
York businesswoman trapped in the Intercontinental Hotel. ``(We're)
now low on food. There are babies in the building, and there is no
baby food, and the mothers are hysterical.
   ``We saw were a group of nuns trying to walk where the tanks
are. They were eventually shot at and took cover.''
   Jerry Huchel, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy, estimated 210
Americans in three luxury hotels in the battle area. He said that
did not include scores of other Americans who may be living in
expensive apartments nearby.
   ``It's not a hostage situation, (but) ``they just can't leave,''
he said.
   The presence of the foreigners and residents has prevented
government forces from waging an assault to wipe out the last
pockets of resistance, and officials believe the standoff could
last for days.
   Ambassador Simard blamed the rebels for keeping the foreigners
in the area, home to the country's two stock exchanges and its most
exclusive boutiques. ``They're certainly using these people as
human shields, in my view,'' he said.
   Electricity was cut briefly today after a stray bullet knocked
out a transformer.
   The Japanese newspaper Asahi said all 600 guests at the Nikko
Manila Garden Hotel were herded into the basement Sunday when
rebels entered the building to demand food. It was not clear if
they were still there.
   Asahi said about 300 Japanese were trapped in Makati hotels and
another 300 were living in apartments in the area.
   ``My advice to them is to stay away from windows, stay in your
room and keep good courage,'' said West German Ambassador Peter
Scholz. ``We have to live out this phase.''
</TEXT>
