<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0858EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Flight103     12-04 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Identified as Suspect In Lockerbie Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UPPSALA, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swedish court today identified a
Palestinian living in Sweden as a suspect in the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 and approved the seizure of evidence during a raid on
his apartment last week.
   The District Court, granting a request by Scottish detectives to
authorize the seizure of 15 bags of clothing, said it found
Mohammed Abo Talb ``is suspected in Scotland of murder or as an
accessory to murder.''
   The court said the clothing taken one week ago from Abo Talb's
apartment ``can be presumed to carry significance for the
investigation'' and the seizure was therefore legal.
   It was believed to be the first time a suspect has faced a court
proceeding for the explosion Dec. 21, 1988 of the Pan Am flight
over Lockerbie, Scotland that killed 270 people.
   Abo Talb, 35, was in jail awaiting a verdict on separate charges
of murder and attempted murder for complicity in a series of bomb
attacks in Scandinavia and Holland in 1985 and 1986. One bomb in
Copenhagen killed one person and wounded more than 20.
   Abo Talb, a former activist in the Palestine Popular Struggle
Front group, was linked to Flight 103 when it was established that
he was in Malta two months before the explosion.
   Investigators reportedly traced clothing bought in Malta to the
suitcase which they believe also contained the bomb.
   The pressure-sensitive bomb apparently was transported in the
suitcase from Malta to Frankfurt, where it was put on board the New
York-bound flight, according to the investigators' reported theory.
   Seven Swedish policemen and three Scottish detectives raided Abo
Talb's apartment last Monday, apparently searching for clothing
that could be linked to the shreds found in Lockerbie.
   On Friday, the public prosecutor, acting on behalf of the
Scottish detectives, asked the court to sanction the seizure as
legal.
   Under Swedish law, evidence taken for a police investigation
outside Sweden must be authorized by a court. The court also must
approve its removal from the country.
   The decision, which was printed and distributed at the
courthouse by a clerk, said that any property removed from Sweden
must be returned at the end of the investigation.
   It also confirmed a previous decision to classify the court
records in the case as secret.
   Jamila Mograbi, Abo Talb's ex-wife who still lives with him,
said detectives took all the family's clothing, and she said she
had to borrow clothes from friends for herself and her two children.
   Speaking to reporters on Friday, she said the policemen
searching the apartment questioned her for one hour and that she
was called to an Uppsala police station later in the week for
further interrogation.
   According to court documents, Abo Talb was born in Lebanon,
served in the Egyptian army and underwent training in the Soviet
Union in handling anti-aircraft missiles.
   He deserted in 1970 to join the Popular Struggle Front, a
radical offshoot of the Palestine Liberation Organization. He
returned to the Soviet Union for further training in 1980.
   Abo Talb immigrated to Sweden in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891204-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0909EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Modrow     12-04 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Modrow,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reform-Minded Premier Emerging as East Germany's No. 1 Figure</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Hans Modrow, who is emerging as East
Germany's top political figure, is a reform-minded Communist long
shunned and criticized by the former hard-line leaders.
   Many see Modrow, 61, as East Germany's equivalent to Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, whose domestic programs of greater
openness and economic restructuring caught on among the East German
public.
   Modrow was elected premier, or head of government, on Nov. 14
after years of waiting as local party leader in Dresden. He was
named today to handle any Communist Party issues that arise during
the current Warsaw Pact summit in Moscow.
   It was also Modrow's duty to inform the edgy Moscow leadership
about the growing upheaval in East Germany, where the Soviets have
nearly 400,000 troops.
   Despite the clear signs of ascent, it is still too early to
predict who will finally come out on top as East Germany goes
through widespread and seemingly uncontrollable changes.
   The Communist Party, which still counts an estimated 2 million
members, is preparing for an emergency session on Dec. 15-17 that
will elect a new leadership. But even then, with party support
dropping and a greater risk of a breakup, the Communists' future is
increasingly clouded.
   Modrow himself has been among those giving a gloomy assessment
of the party's chances, saying the Communists would get no more
than 20 percent of the vote if promised free elections were held
today.
   The premier, in his inaugural speech to Parliament on Nov. 17,
appealed for more private enterprise to help rescue the country's
troubled economy.
   Modrow said East Germany is ``open for proposals on joint
ventures, investment, transfer of profits and environmental pilot
projects,'' all of which address some of the concerns of Western
businesses looking for openings in the East German market.
   He called for a ``better socialism'' with more supplies of
consumer goods for the nation's 16.5 million people. He rejected
talk of German reunification as ``dangerous and unrealistic'' while
calling for increased treaty links between the two countries.
   Long known as an anti-establishment Communist, Modrow was the
target of an inquisition led by then hard-line leader Erich
Honecker.
   The attacks temporarily derailed his career as a nationwide
leader, forcing him to stay as local party chief in his power base
of Dresden.
   In June, central authorities singled him out for rare public
criticism, saying he had failed to control ``bourgeois and enemy
views'' in Dresden after a large demonstration of citizens
demanding freedom of travel to the West.
   An engineer by trade and the holder of a university economics
degree, Modrow already has wielded far more clout as premier than
his colorless predecessor, Willi Stoph.
   Many East Germans as well as Soviet officials made plain they
would have preferred Modrow in the post of Communist Party
secretary, but the job went to Honecker protege Egon Krenz on Oct.
18.
   As 10,000 demonstrators rallied in East Berlin on Sunday, many
carried placards saying all of the top Communist leaders should
quit except Modrow.
   With Krenz now out, that leaves open the possibility for a
Modrow shot at the top party job _ if the structure stays the same.
There are already growing warnings about a possible breakup of the
troubled party, while many say a name change at least is possible.
   Married and the father of two children, Modrow began his party
career as chief of the Communist youth organization in East Berlin
from 1953 to 1961. He won election to the 163-member Central
Committee in 1967 and became Dresden party secretary in 1973.
   Modrow won massive support in Dresden, in part because he
rejected party perks and insisted on living in a normal apartment.
His wife reportedly waited in lines at stores like other local
homemakers.
   The premier stunned East Berliners by walking home, rather than
being driven, after his Nov. 17 speech in Parliament.
</TEXT>
