<HEAD>Figure in Custody Battle Remarried</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Elizabeth Morgan, who spent 25 months in
jail for refusing to allow her daughter to visit the child's
father, was married over the weekend to a federal appeals court
judge.
   Morgan married Paul R. Michel, a judge on the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia, at St. Alban's Church on the
grounds of the Washington National Cathedral on Saturday, one of
her attorneys, Adrian Roe, said today.
   Morgan was jailed in August 1987 for civil contempt of court for
refusing to produce her daughter Hilary, now 7, for an unsupervised
visit with her former husband, Dr. Eric Foretich, a northern
Virginia oral surgeon.
   Morgan, a plastic surgeon, has contended that Foretich sexually
abused the child _ an allegation he repeatedly has denied.
   Neither Morgan's parents nor Hilary were at the wedding. Her
parents have not been seen since the child disappeared.
   Robert Morgan said his sister and Michel did not reveal their
honeymoon plans, even to family members. It was the second marriage
for both.
