<FIRST>r i PM-AirportClash     12-04 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airport Clash,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airport Foes Clash With Police at Planned Construction Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a radical leftist group hurled firebombs
and stones today at riot police trying to remove huts built
illegally on the site of a proposed new runway at Tokyo's
international airport, police said.
   Police fought back with water cannons, but there were no reports
of injuries, said an offical of the Chiba Prefectural Police,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The official said Masaaki Komurasaki, a 27-year-old member of
the Battle Flag leftist group, was arrested for allegedly
constructing a tower on the construction site.
   About five people atop the tower, which was several yards high,
threw firebombs and stones as riot police moved in with bulldozers
and backhoes to get rid of about 10 huts built inside and near the
site of the planned runway, officials said.
   Local farmers and their supporters, including radicals seizing
on the issue for their anti-government activities, have been
resisting the government's plans to expropriate farmland to expand
the New Tokyo International Airport at Narita, which opened in 1978
with just one runway.
   Complaints of congestion have been growing, and the government
plans to complete construction of another 8,250-foot runway within
next year.
   Today marked the start of police action to clear the huts.
   The official said 5,000 riot police were mobilized to block off
the area.
   Another 1,500 riot police are to be mobilized to strengthen
checkpoints on roads leading to the airport, he added.
   About 230 opponents, including members of the Chukakuha, another
radical group opposed to the airport, are living in huts and other
structures there, police sources said.
   The Transport Ministry says eight farmers still live inside the
planned expansion site.
   Transport Minister Takami Eto told a news conference he had
apologized to local farmers for the government's choosing Narita as
the airport site, ministry officials said.
   Eto said his apology was contained in a letter mailed Saturday
in reply to a protest letter sent by some farmers.
   Eto, the first transport minister to make such an official
apology to farmers, said he would like to have talks with farmers
opposing the airport, the officials added.
</TEXT>
