<FIRST>r a PM-People-Who'sWho 2ndLd-Writethru a0459 12-04 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Who's Who, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0459,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Who's Hot, Who's Not _ That's the Question for Who's Who Editors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Once someone...' to add that people sometimes
are dropped from book at their request, add attribution.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMETTE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who's a Who?
   That's the question the editors of ``Who's Who in America'' must
decide as they prepare listings for the 1990-91 edition of the
reference book.
   Actor Eric Roberts will be listed in the new Who's Who. But Mr.
T, star of the canceled ``A-Team'' TV series, will not be. Baseball
slugger Jose Canseco of the Oakland A's is a Who, but National
League rookie of the year, Jerome Walton, the Chicago Cubs
centerfielder, is not.
   ``Walton was rookie of the year, true,'' explained John L.
Daniels, product manager for Who's Who In America. ``But you don't
know. What about his sophomore year? What if he fizzles?''
   Once someone is listed, it's for life, until retirement, until
someone asks to be left out or until conviction for a serious
crime, Daniels said.
   Sometimes the editors look the other way at a conviction, as in
the case of Watergate convicts John Ehrlichman, H.R. Haldeman and
Charles Colson, who continue to be listed.
   Thousands of questionnaires were mailed this fall from Who's Who
headquarters in this northern Chicago suburb to Nobel laureates,
federal judges, movie stars, Fortune 500 company officials,
newspaper editors, junior partners in major accounting firms,
up-and-coming lawyers, and others.
   Researchers at the headquarters comb through newspapers,
magazines and corporate reports for prospective listees.
   ``We try to be as objective as we can be in our standards,''
Daniels said. ``We try to quantify quality.''
   Those who return the questionnaires, providing information about
their accomplishments, memberships, education and the like, are
guaranteed a place among the 79,000 people to be listed in the new
edition, due out in September 1990.
   Daniels said the expected return rate is only 12 percent to 14
percent. Years ago, as many as 20 percent returned the
questionnaires.
   He said the rate has dropped because people are confused by the
proliferation of such books _ many of them vanity press
publications that charge for a listing.
   In contrast, ``Who's Who in America,'' a publication of
Macmillan Inc., makes clear in its preface that its entries don't
have to buy the book.
   Daniels said he receives up to 50 unsolicited nominations for
new entrants each week _ either from admirers or the would-be
personalities themselves.
   The publication has been in business since 1899. New editions
are published every two years.
   Albert Nelson Marquis, a Chicago publisher, founded the
publication after seeing a similar book in Britain. The idea was
not to confer celebrity status on certain people, but to provide a
useful reference book to businesses and libraries.
   The book does have a history of keeping a Who or two out.
   Frank Lloyd Wright was refused a listing for years because
Marquis objected to the architect's unsettled married life.
   Marquis also barred 1930s Hollywood star Mae West from the big
red book. That prompted her to respond, ``Well, the old boy who
publishes that isn't in my little black book, either.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
