<HEAD>U.S. Army Helicopter Crashes; All Aboard Safe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Army helicopter carrying 16
soldiers and a crew of three crashed into a remote mountainside
south of Seoul today, but only minor injuries were reported,
officials said.
   The CH-47D Chinook transport helicopter was on a training
mission when it crashed near Osan City, 40 miles south of Seoul, at
about 10:30 a.m., said Air Force Sgt. Wilt Baker of the 8th U.S.
Army public affairs office.
   The injured were treated at nearby hospitals, he said. Their
names were withheld.
   The helicopter was assigned to B Company, 2nd Battalion, 501st
Aviation Regiment stationed at Camp Humphreys south of Seoul.
American military officials said they were investigating the cause
of the crash.
   The Army grounded most of its CH-47D Chinook helicopters in
October because of a problem with transmission oil cooling fans.
The fleet was grounded in August as a precaution while previous fan
failures were studied.
   The helicopters were made by Boeing Helicopter Co.
