<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clash Leaves One Dead, Parliament Member and Eight Constables Hurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black man was killed and at
least 13 people, including eight policemen and a Parliament member,
were hurt when officers clashed with hundreds of blacks trying to
attend a protest meeting, police said today.
   Constables were pelted with stones and responded by using stun
grenades, rubber bullets and tear gas, policesaid.
   The clash occurred Sunday in Edendale, near the Natal Province
capital of Pietermaritzburg, after more than 2,000 blacks gathered
to attend an anti-government meeting.
   Authorities had refused to allow the meeting to be held at a
stadium, and it was moved to a meeting hall that could accommodate
only about 1,000 people.
   Police said those who could not fit inside became disorderly and
began stoning officers and their vehicles. The police report did
not specify how the death occurred.
   One of those injured was Pierre Cronje, a white Parliament
member for the anti-apartheid Democratic Party. He was hit in the
chest by a rock but not seriously hurt.
   Five other deaths were reported in political violence and
faction fighting elsewhere in Natal in the 24 hours ending at
daybreak today. More than 2,000 blacks have been killed in the
province in the past three years in a power truggle between members
of Inkatha, a relatively conservative Zulu organization, and
supporters of the United Democratic Front, a nationwide
anti-apartheid coalition.
   The meeting in Edendale was organized by supporters of the front.
