<FIRST>u w PM-HomeSales     12-04 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Sales,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Sales Down Again, But Show Improvement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new homes edged down 0.5 percent in
October, the sixth monthly decline of the year but a major
improvement over the previous month, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said new single-family homes were sold
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 649,000 units in October,
after a 10.2 percent plunge in September.
   The September decrease was revised downward from a 14 percent
fall originally reported last month.
   Fixed-rate mortgage interest rates fell to 9.82 percent by the
end of October after rising into the double digits in September.
Analysts had said the lower rates would lead to an improvement in
the housing industry.
   The National Association of Realtors reported last week that
sales of existing homes remained steady in October at their highest
level since last January and NAR chief economist John A. Tuccillo
said then that ``home financing conditions probably will stay quite
favorable in the months ahead.''
   The housing industry was among the hardest hit when the Federal
Reserve pumped up interest rates last year to slow the economy and
thus contain inflation. But as inflationary pressures cooled, the
Fed has permitted gradual decreases in rates since the beginning of
the summer.
   The Realtors association reported today that its index measuring
the ability of the typical American family to buy an existing home
rose in October to its highest level in eight months because of
stable rates and a drop in the median home price.
   The real estate group said the index rose to 106.1, from 103.5
in September and the highest since it measured 106.7 last February.
That means a family with a median income of $33,365 had 106.1
percent of the income needed to buy a median-priced existing home
costing $92,100.
   The median means that half of the families earn more and half
less, or that half the homes sell for more and half for less.
   The Commerce Department report today said the median price of a
new home was $127,900 in October, up 5.3 percent from $121,500 in
September. The average price of a new home was unchanged at
$151,900.
   New-home sales for the first nine months were down 4.4 percent
from the same period in 1988.
   Sales rose 47.8 percent in the Northeast but fell 24.7 percent
in the West. The South posted a 5.7 percent increase, while the
Midwest recorded a 3.7 percent gain.
   The Realtors, meanwhile, said a family in the Northeast earning
the median income of $37,329 had only 76.1 percent of the income
needed to buy median-priced existing home costing $143,300.
   In the West, a family earning the median income of $35,299 had
74.1 percent of the income needed to buy a home priced at $142,200.
   In the South, a family earning the median income of $30,533 had
107.4 percent of the income needed to buy an $83,400 home, while a
Midwestern family earning the median of $33,511 had 137.5 percent
of the income needed to purchase a home priced at $70,900.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891204-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Baker-Berlin     12-04 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Berlin,250</SECOND>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III will fly
to Berlin next week to visit the Berlin Wall and make a major
speech on U.S. foreign policy, State Department spokesman Margaret
D. Tutwiler said today.
   On the one-day trip next Tuesday, Baker probably will also go to
Bonn, the West German capital, for further talks with leaders of
the government, the spokeswoman said.
   Although the invitation to speak before the Berlin Press Club
was on Baker's desk for several weeks, his decision to except
represents more than a simple speaking engagement.
   The presence of the U.S. secretary of state in Berlin, which was
divided after World War II, could lend at least tacit sypport a
proposal by West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl calling for the
reunification of Germany.
   Last week, Baker endorsed a proposal by Kohl for a step-by-step
process of reunification, beginning with the confederation of East
and West Germany even while the Bonn government remains in the NATO
alliance.
   On Sunday, U.S. ambassador to West Germany, Vernon A. Walters,
predicted the reunification of Germany would take place within five
years.
   Baker's travel plan is to set out from Washington next Monday
and spend Tuesday afternoon in Berlin, including a visit to the
Berlin Wall, crumbling as East Germany joins other Eastern European
nations in veering away from orthodox communism.
   Baker then will probably stop in Bonn and then go on to Brussels
to attend a meeting of NATO foreign ministers, Ms. Tutwiler said.
</TEXT>
