<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-FemaleInmates     12-04 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Female Inmates,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Ruling on Female Inmates in Kentucky Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that women in a Kentucky prison must receive a lawyer's help with
their appeals.
   The justices, without comment, rejected an appeal by officials
at the Kentucky Correctional Institution for Women who were ordered
to provide the equivalent of at least one half-time lawyer to
assist inmates.
   One of the issues the appeal raised was whether courts, without
finding past intentional sex bias, may order prison systems to
offer female inmates the same access to courts male inmates receive.
   Inmates at the women's prison in Peewee Valley, Ky., sued over
conditions there in 1980.
   The suit alleged, among other things, that the inmates did not
have adequate access to courts because the law library was inferior
to those available to male inmates at the Kentucky State
Penitentiary and the Kentucky State Reformatory.
   After a four-week trial in 1982, U.S. District Judge Edward H.
Johnstone in Louisville ruled that the state had violated female
inmates' equal-protection rights by not providing them with the
same court access as male inmates.
   He ordered state authorities to provide a library identical to
those at the two prisons for men, to increase the hours women could
use their prison library and to provide free legal help.
   Only that part of Johnstone's order calling for legal help was
appealed. It was upheld by the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
last April 10.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the prison officials
argued that the hiring of a part-time lawyer should not be required.
   ``There is no justification,'' the appeal said. ``There is no
formula ... (to) measure the success of this part-time attorney.
There are no limits to the assistance provided by counsel.''
   The appeal was supported in a ``friend-of-the-court'' brief
submitted by 13 states. They are Arizona, Arkansas, Florida, Idaho,
Iowa, Kansas, Michigan, Missouri, New Jersey, Ohio, South Dakota,
Tennessee and Wyoming.
   The case is Wilson vs. Canterino, 89-464.
</TEXT>
