<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Parkchester     12-04 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Parkchester,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Kill Lawsuit Against Harry Helmsley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to kill a
lawsuit against billionaire hotel owner Harry Helmsley and others
accused of fraud in a major New York City condominium conversion
project.
   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that Helmsley
and the others may be sued under a federal anti-racketeering law.
   Helmsley, his business partners and an engineering firm are
being sued by tenants of the Parkchester apartment complex in the
Bronx in New York City. The lawsuit said the defendants concealed
structural defects in the buildings, the presence of asbestos in
insulation and the need to replace electrical systems and plumbing.
   They are charged with violating the Racketeer Influenced and
Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO).
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in January said the
charges against the defendants, if true, constitute a pattern of
racketeering activity as defined by the RICO statute.
   The Supreme Court last July ordered the appeals court to restudy
that decision after the justices themselves handed down a similar
ruling in a Minnesota telephone rates case.
   The high court said the RICO act can apply to even a single
fraudulent scheme that has the threat of continuing illegal
activities. The justices said the law may be invoked against
business fraud, not only traditional forms of organized crime.
   After re-examining the Parkchester case, the 2nd Circuit court
in September reaffirmed its original ruling and permitted the suit.
   The suit is separate from a federal tax evasion criminal case
that resulted in the conviction of Helmsley's wife, Leona.
   Harry Helmsley was found incompetent to stand trial on the
criminal charges in that case because of memory loss and reasoning
problems caused by several slight strokes.
   The case acted on today is Helmsley vs. Beauford, 89-572.
</TEXT>
