<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-DeKalb     12-04 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-DeKalb,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Intervene in Georgia Desegregation Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected a plea for
intervention from DeKalb County, Ga., school officials who have
been ordered to consider racial desegregation measures that include
busing.
   The court refused to block a ruling that the county's school
officials take further steps to integrate the 73,000-student school
system, the largest in Georgia.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy on Nov. 22 temporarily blocked
enforcement of a desegregation ruling by the 11th U.S. Court of
Appeals to give him more time to study the county's emergency plea.
He then referred the case to the full court.
   The county, in suburban Atlanta, has been under court order to
desegregate its schools since 1969.
   U.S. District Judge William C. O'Kelley ruled last year that the
county had done all it could to integrate its schools, agreeing
with officials that housing patterns were the primary cause of any
remaining racial segregation in public schools.
   That decision was overturned last October by the 11th Circuit
court, which said officials must consider ``pairing and
clustering'' schools in different parts of the county to attain
racial balance, a move that would require busing.
   School officials said the appeals court ruling sounded a ``death
knell'' for neighborhood schools in Georgia, Alabama and Florida,
the three states encompassed by the 11th Circuit.
   The school officials cited a 1976 Supreme Court ruling in a case
from Pasadena, Calif., which they said means a school district
already under a desegregation order may not be forced to correct
racial imbalances in student population unless found responsible
for creating those imbalances.
   The case is Freeman vs. Pitts, A-401.
</TEXT>
