<FIRST>r p PM-Celebrezze-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru a0444 12-04 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Celebrezze-Abortion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ohio Attorney General's Shift Angers Anti-Abortionists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf, `Celebrezze said ..., to include
reference to other races in which abortion played a role; pick up 4th graf,
`Celebrezze was ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Attorney General Anthony Celebrezze
Jr., a leading contender for the Democratic gubernatorial
nomination, announced a shift in his position on abortion, angering
anti-abortion activists.
   Celebrezze, who had voiced a strong anti-abortion position since
entering the state Senate in 1975, told reporters Saturday he
supports public funding of abortions for low-income women and would
veto legislation to ban abortion.
   Celebrezze said he now believes women should have the right to
choose abortion until the fetus is determined to be viable, at
which point the rights of the fetus become paramount.
   The switch comes amid growing evidence that a strong
anti-abortion stance can be a political liability. Abortion played
a prominent role in the recent gubernatorial races in Virginia and
New Jersey, and pro-choice candidates won both elections.
   Celebrezze was expected to announce his candidacy later this
month for the Democratic primary to be held in May.
   ``My own beliefs lead me to conclude that abortion is almost
always the wrong solution to the problem of unwanted pregnancy,''
he said. ``Public officials, however, have a special obligation to
explain what role the government they serve ought to play in the
abortion decision.''
   But Curt Steiner, spokesman for Republican gubernatorial
candidate George Voinovich, who opposes abortion, said Celebrezze
can't have it both ways.
   ``I think this is a shocking reversal. Here's a person who says
he wants to run on his record, then the first thing he does is run
away from his record,'' he said.
   Jill L. Spangler, executive director of the National Abortion
Rights Action League Ohio, called the announcement good news for
the Celebrezze campaign.
   ``It is perfectly valid to change one's mind, especially on
something as important as this,'' she said.
</TEXT>
