<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Air 1stLd-Writethru a0528 12-04 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Air, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Sets Stage for Significant Ruling on Power to Fine Air Polluters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 4-11, In other action, with other cases.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today set the stage for a
significant ruling on the government's power to fine air polluters.
   The court agreed to hear an appeal by General Motors, which
faces fines of up to $25,000 a day for violating federal air
quality standards at a Massachusetts car-assembly plant.
   The justices will review a ruling that the federal government's
failure to meet a deadline for approving or rejecting revised state
pollution controls does not bar it from fining GM.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Agreed to hear arguments favoring states' rights and consider
limiting the federal government's power to control water used by
hydroelectric dams.
   The court said it will hear a California appeal supported by
nearly every other state.
   _ Left intact a ruling that limits the power of states and their
citizens to block shipments of hazardous waste from other states.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Alabama
officials who failed to prevent shipments of hazardous waste from
an abandoned Texas chemical refinery to Alabama.
   _ Agreed to decide whether U.S. banks with branch offices
overseas must pay depositors after foreign governments seize or
freeze those accounts.
   The court said it will review rulings that required Citibank to
pay depositors. Lawyers for Citibank said billions of dollars are
at stake. There are more than 900 branches of U.S. banks operating
in 73 countries, with some $225 billion in deposits.
   _ Rejected a plea from DeKalb County, Ga., school officials
ordered to consider racial desegregation measures that include
busing.
   The court refused to block a ruling that the county's school
officials take further steps to integrate the 73,000-student school
system, the largest in Georgia.
   The air pollution case involves pollution from car paint at GM's
plant in Framingham, and focuses on the joint federal-state system
for cleaning up the atmosphere.
   Under the federal Clean Air Act, the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency sets national air quality standards. The states
are required to adopt plans to meet those standards, and submit the
plans to the EPA.
   The federal agency in 1980 approved a Massachusetts plan for
reducing pollution from paint at auto assembly factories.
   The plan required car makers to comply fully with the federal
rules by Dec. 31, 1985.
   But EPA officials extended the deadline for any plant switching
from lacquer paints to enamel, which emits less pollutants.
   GM initially planned to stay with lacquer at the Framingham
factory but in June 1985 announced it would convert to enamel by
the summer of 1987. The company asked that it not be required to
comply with the Dec. 31, 1985, standards until 20 months later.
   Massachusetts officials approved GM's proposal and submitted a
revised plan to the EPA on Dec. 30, 1985.
   Without waiting for federal approval, GM began building a $200
million plant in Framingham to use the enamel system while
continuing to operate its factory that uses lacquer paint.
   EPA officials went to federal court in August 1987 seeking fines
of up to $25,000 a day against GM for 20 months of air-quality
violations at the old Framingham plant.
   It was not until September 1988 that the EPA rejected the
state-approved pollution control system at the new plant.
   A federal judge barred the EPA from imposing fines against GM
for violations of the Dec. 31, 1985, standards. The judge said the
federal agency itself violated the Clean Air Act by taking more
than four months to rule on the state-approved plan submitted Dec.
30, 1985.
   But the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last June said the
EPA's failure to meet the four-month deadline does not disqualify
it from fining companies that violate previously approved pollution
control rules.
   The public should not be penalized with dirtier air because of
what often are unavoidable EPA delays, the appeals court said.
   It told the trial judge to decide how much the fines should be,
stating he should take into account whether the EPA's delay was
reasonable and what impact the delay had on GM.
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce joined GM in urging the Supreme
Court to review the air pollution dispute.
   Chamber of Commerce lawyers said the 1st Circuit court ruling is
an incentive to the EPA to treat companies unfairly. They said it
conflicts with decisions by other federal appeals courts.
   The Bush administration said the 1st Circuit court's ruling was
correct.
   The case is General Motors vs. U.S., 89-369.
</TEXT>
