<FIRST>u w PM-CatastrophicRefunds     12-04 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Catastrophic Refunds,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catastrophic-Coverage Payments Will Continue Well Into New Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retirees will have to continue paying monthly
premiums for Medicare catastrophic coverage at least until May,
even though the program is being repealed this month, federal
officials said today.
   That much time will be required to adjust and test the
government computers that now withhold the premiums from monthly
Social Security benefit checks, Social Security Commissioner
Gwendolyn King said in an interview today.
   She said the Social Security Administration hopes to stop
deducting the premiums starting with the benefit checks that arrive
in early May. Refunds of the premiums could take three or more
months beyond that date.
   The $4-a-month premium for catastrophic coverage is scheduled
under the law to rise to $5.30 on Jan. 1. Although Congress voted
last month to repeal catastrophic protection, the bill has not yet
been presented to President Bush for his signature.
   ``My concern is for those on fixed income who cannot afford to
see $5 go out of their checks,'' Ms. King said. ``That's a lot of
money for those people and it is little consolation for them to
know they will get a refund in the future.''
   The prospect of seeing retirees continue to have to pay the
premiums does not sit well either with Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark.,
chairman of the Senate Aging Committee.
   ``I fear that a lengthy delay will create a firestorm of
protest,'' Pryor said in a letter to Ms. King that was made public
today. ``We must recognize the impending firestorm and move repidly
to alleviate the problem.''
   Pryor said many retirees will need the $5.30 a month to pay the
expected increase in rates for private ``Medigap'' policies as a
result of repeal of federal coverage.
   Catastrophic coverage was enacted last year to protect people 65
and older from being bankrupted by a major illness. The program
fell into disfavor with many retirees, especially those who already
have private coverage and higher-income people who were faced with
an income surtax of up to $800 a year for catastrophic.
   As a result of loud complaints from those groups, Congress
agreed last month to kill the program.
   The monthly premiums that have been deducted from benefit checks
this year will not be refunded; they will pay for hospital and
other benefits that have been in effect all year.
   Few retirees have been paying the surtax. Those who have paid it
through quarterly estimated tax payments will get a
larger-than-expected income tax refund next year.
</TEXT>
