<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bush-Germany     12-04 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Germany,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Kohl `Comfortable' With U.S. Stand on Reunification</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Monday that West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl appeared comfortable with the U.S.
insistence that any moves to German reunfication be gradual.
   Bush said Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev voiced concern at
their summit meeting over the weekend that outside forces would try
to impose an ``artificial'' deadline for German reunification.
   At a news conference after he presented a summit briefing to
members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, Bush reiterated
the four-point U.S. position on reunification.
   _It must be pursued based on self-determination of the people of
East and West Germany, without anyone trying to dictate in advance
what form unification would take.
   _Unification must be pursued in the context of Germany's
continued commitment to NATO and the European Community.
   _Moves toward unification should be ``peaceful, gradual, and
part of a step-by-step process.''
   _The Helsinki accord respecting the borders in Europe should be
observed, and changes should be made only peacefully.
   ``I think Chancellor Kohl feels comfortable with the four things
I just said,'' Bush added.
   The first three points are similar to some of the 10 points
outlined recently by Kohl in his plan for moving toward
reunification.
   Bush was asked about his insistence that a unified Germany
remain committed to NATO. By contrast, Gorbachev contends the
division of Germany was dictated by history and that East Germany
should remain part of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   ``I think his view was one of ... caution,'' Bush said. ``I
really believe that. I think he recognized the rapidity of change.
He has very constructively talked about peaceful change.''
   ``I think he feels that if there were outside forces setting
dates that would complicate the way he is helping manage the change
in the pact,'' Bush added.
</TEXT>
