<FIRST>u w PM-EPA-Pesticide 1stLd-Writethru a0553 12-04 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EPA-Pesticide, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0553,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Calls for Curbs on EBDC Family of Pesticides</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs with crops affected by withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoicated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency today
called for sharp curbs on the widely used EBDC family of
pesticides, proposing that the chemical no longer be applied to 42
crops including apples and tomatoes because of concerns about
cancer.
   The proposed regulation, which would not become final until
early 1991, would allow the continued use of the EBDC fungicides on
10 crops including grapes, onion and cranberries.
   The EPA said the use of the EBDCs _ known as maneb, mancozeb and
metiram _ on the remaining 10 crops ``do not present an
unreasonable risk.'' The agency estimated the maximum risk of
someone getting cancer from a lifetime of exposure at three in 1
million. With the chemical's current widespread use that risk is 4
in 10,000, it said.
   EPA Administrator William Reilly applauded a decision announced
earlier this year by EBDC manufacturers to withdraw the chemical's
use on 42 crops. But he said ``we do not believe that goes far
enough'' and proposed that the ban apply as well to three
additional crops _ tomatoes, bananas and potatoes.
   The manufacturers have said they would begin their voluntary
curbs at the end of the year. EBDC use on the other three crops
would not go into effect for at least 18 months unless producers
choose to incorporate them in their voluntary curb.
   The EBDC chemicals, which began to be used in the 1930s, are
among the most widely used fungicides, with as much as 18 million
pounds manufactured annually for use on most common vegetables as
well as grains.
   But the fungicide has come under attack from environmentalists
and health specialists because a breakdown product called ETU has
been found to cause cancer in laboratory animals. Chronic exposure
also raises the risks of birth defects or thyroid disorders,
scientists said.
   The EPA said that while the health risks associated with EBDC
use on any one crop may be negligible, ``the cumulative risks
(associated with its widespread use) has been determined to be
unreasonable.''
   The health risk estimates are based on the maximum allowable
dosage of the fungicide on various crops. The EPA said those
estimates likely are greater than residue levels found in the
marketplace because the fungicide is easily washed off.
   Crop producers as well as state agriculture departments had
asked the EPA to hold off proposing restrictions on the EBDCs until
a marketbasket survey currently under way is completed to provide a
clearer picture of residue levels actually found on crops by
consumers.
   The National Association of State Departments of Agriculture
said in a letter to Reilly that several states already had reported
results of surveys and ``to date no significant residues of EBDCs
have been found.''
   Environmental groups, however, have criticized the EPA for
moving too slowely in getting the EBDCs off the market, noting that
a final regulation on the chemical will not be issued until the
spring of 1991.
   Under the EPA proposal, EBDCs would continue to be used on
grapes, wheat, cranberries, onions, sugar beets, sweet corn,
peanuts, almonds, asparagus and figs.
   The 42 crops on which EBDCs currently are used, but would no
longer be used under voluntary curbs by the chemical's
manufacturers, are:
   Apples, apricots, barley, casaba melons, crenshaw melons,
cucumbers, eggplants, endives, lettuce, pineapples, pumpkins, green
beans, dried beans, lima beans, broccoli, Brussels sprouts,
cabbage, cantaloupes, carrots, cauliflower, celery, collards, field
corn, cotton, crabapples, fennel, honeydew melons, kale, kohlrabi,
mustard greens, nectarines, oats, papayas, peaches, pears, pecans,
peppers, rhubarb, rye, squash, spinach, turnips and watermelon.
</TEXT>
