<FIRST>u a PM-MultipleTransplant 1stLd-Writethru a0430 12-04 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Multiple Transplant, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0430,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Receives World's First Heart-Liver-Kidney Transplant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with doctors' news conference
today, family background, anti-rejection drug, husband's comments. Picks
up 8th graf pvs, ``Her operation....''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 26-year-old woman has a new heart, liver,
and kidney after an almost daylong operation that doctors called
the first of its kind.
   Cindy Martin of Archbald remained in critical condition today at
Presbyterian-University Hospital, which is normal after transplant
surgery.
   At a news conference this morning, doctors said they would try
to begin weaning her off a respirator today.
   Other multiorgan transplants have been performed, but this was
the first involving the heart, liver and a kidney, said transplant
pioneer Dr. Thomas Starzl, director of the University of
Pittsburgh's transplant program.
   The procedure began at 7:35 p.m. Saturday and ended at 5 p.m.
Sunday.
   It was Ms. Martin's second heart transplant. She has familial
cardiomyopathy, an inherited heart disease, according to the
hospital.
   Mrs. Martin's family has a history of congenital heart problems.
Her father died when he was 31 and many relatives on his side of
the family also have died young, her husband, John Martin, 28, said
today.
   Mrs. Martin suffered from chronic rejection of the heart she
received in her first transplant three years ago, and had developed
hepatitis and kidney dysfunction. Kidney dysfunction can affect
patients taking the anti-rejection drug cyclosporine.
   Doctors will treat Mrs. Martin with the Japanese drug FK-506,
which is believed 50 to 100 times more effective than cyclosporine,
hospital spokeswoman Lisa Rossi said. FK-506 has been tested since
February in Pittsburgh on liver, heart, kidney, pancreas and lung
recipients.
   The new organs came from an Atlanta woman in her 20s who was
killed in a car accident, doctors said.
   When doctors called Saturday to say a donor had been found,
Martin said he had to scramble to locate his wife.
   ``We had a tough time finding her at first because she was out
shopping when the call came,'' Martin said. ``I'm nervous of
course. The first transplant sort of prepared me a little for this,
but I'm just nervous as to what the outcome might be.''
   Her operation came five days after another milestone in
transplant operations. In Chicago, 21-month-old Alyssa Smith became
the nation's first person to receive part of a liver from a living
donor. Alyssa was listed in serious condition Sunday, and is
improving steadily, said John Easton, a spokesman for the
University of Chicago's Wyler Children's Hospital. Alyssa's mother,
Teresa, was the donor.
   The world's first survivor of a heart-liver transplant was
Stormie Jones, now 12, of White Settlement, Texas. Starzl conducted
that procedure on Feb. 14, 1984, at Children's Hospital of
Pittsburgh.
   Two other heart-liver transplants were performed the next year
in Pittsburgh, but both patients died with a few days of surgery.
   Starzl also has headed multiple-organ transplant operations
involving the intestines.
   Tabatha Foster, 3, of Madisonville, Ky., survived six months
before dying in May 1988 after a multiple-organ transplant.
Rolandrea Dodge, 3, of Fruitland, N.M., died last January, six
weeks after surgery.
   Starzl also has headed multiple-organ transplants on adults with
malignant, inoperable tumors in the pancreas and liver areas.
   In those cases, surgeons have removed the patient's liver,
pancreas, most or all of the stomach, two-thirds of the colon, and
duodenum, a 10-inch-long section of the small intestine. The cavity
has been filled with a block of organs consisting of the liver,
pancreas, duodenum and jejunum, a few feet of section of the small
intestine.
</TEXT>
