<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--HospitalFire     12-04 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Hospital Fire,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Fire Leaves One Patient Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital bed mattress was set afire by the
cigarette of a patient smoking in bed, and the 77-year-old smoker
was killed, officials said.
   Nurses at Parkway Hospital discovered the fire after a smoke
alarm sounded early Sunday in the private room of Rudolph Kurtz,
who was recovering from prostrate surgery, said chief marketing
officer Daniel A. Baldwin.
   A nurse pulled Kurtz onto the floor while another staff member
fought the blaze, which was confined to Kurtz's room.
   About 40 other patients on the wing were evacuated while the
fire was being fought.
   Kurtz suffered third-degree and fourth-degree burns over 80
percent of his body. He was taken to Hermann Hospital, where he
died about two hours later.
   The incident will be reviewed to see if policy changes should be
made regarding smokers, Baldwin said.
</TEXT>
