<FIRST>r a PM-HostageGuard     12-04 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostage Guard,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prison Hostage Sues to Get Videotapes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former guard who has had emotional problems
since he was held hostage during a 1987 riot at the Atlanta federal
prison is suing to get government videotapes his psychologist says
can help him end his ordeal.
   Leon Mormann, 36, was one of about 100 hostages held by Cuban
detainees during the 11-day takeover at the penitentiary two years
ago. A number of people held hostage at the Atlanta prison and
during a related prison confrontation at Oakdale, La., have
reported serious emotional problems.
   Soon after his release, Mormann accepted a transfer to a prison
in Tucson, Ariz., where the mostly Hispanic prison population
reminded him of the Atlanta prison.
   ``I flipped out,'' he said, adding that he suffered a panic
attack that put him in a psychiatric ward for a month. His wife and
daughter left him, and he has since divorced. He returned to
Atlanta in July 1988 and lives on worker's compensation.
   The federal Bureau of Prisons confirms that tapes of the Atlanta
riot exist, but has told Mormann he was not specific enough as to
which ones he wished to see when he tried to get copies through the
Freedom of Information Act.
   He sued in federal court when that effort failed.
   ``How can we be more specific? We don't even know what's on the
tapes,'' said psychologist David Aycock of Jonesboro, who has been
treating Mormann for a year. ``It's not like there's a national
security risk here. ... We're just looking for anything that can
bring him back into the situation.''
   Aycock said the tapes could help Mormann realize what he went
through and help him get on with his life.
   ``He can watch the tapes and be anxious, cut it off and go back
to it when he calms down. Control is the key,'' Aycock said.
   Aycock said Mormann has post-traumatic stress disorder, similar
to that of some war or disaster survivors, and suffers nightmares
and flashbacks.
   On the day of the Nov. 23, 1987, takeover, Aycock was the only
guard in a dormitory of about 70 Cubans considered to be model
prisoners. He locked himself in an office, but the inmates broke
the door down with a desk.
   He was handcuffed, tied and forced at knifepoint to be a human
shield for the transfer of two wounded prisoners. He was kept
handcuffed to another guard in a cell for the duration of the
takeover.
   The Cubans detained at the Atlanta prison were among those who
came to the United States in the Mariel boatlift of 1980. Thousands
who had criminal records or got into trouble after arrival were
held pending deportation. Since the riot, 122 have been sent back
to Cuba, 789 remain in custody and 3,250 have been released to
halfway houses, relatives or other sponsors.
</TEXT>
