<FIRST>r a PM-BusCrashTrial     12-04 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Crash Trial,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fiery Accident Scene Reconstructed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police specialist took the witness
stand today at the murder and drunken driving trial of Larry
Mahoney to begin a detailed reconstruction of a fiery bus crash
that killed 27 people.
   State Trooper Henry Sonny Cease Jr., an accident reconstruction
specialist, described his investigation of the May 14, 1988,
collision between the crowded bus and a small pickup Mahoney is
alleged to have been driving the wrong way on Interstate 71 south
of Carrollton.
   Cease spent 1,880 hours investigating the wreck.
   Also testifying this morning was State Police Detective Tony
Moffett, who tried to determine where Mahoney had been on the day
of the crash. He said he could account for Mahoney's whereabouts
for all but one hour and five minutes before the crash.
   Mahoney, 36, of rural Owen County, is charged with 27 counts of
murder, 42 counts of wanton endangerment, 12 counts of assault and
a count of drunken driving.
   So far in the trial, which began with jury selection on Nov. 8,
the jury has seen the charred remains of the church bus, visited
the accident scene, heard from people who said they were nearly run
off the road by Mahoney and heard accounts from rescue workers and
police officers who went to the crash.
   Last week, 39 of the 40 survivors described in detail the panic
and horror they felt while they scrambled to escape from the
burning bus.
   Several survivors testified they tried in vain to kick out
windows. Some escaped the flames by diving over a pile of bodies at
the rear emergency exit.
   Assistant Attorney General Paul Richwalsky Jr., the special
prosecutor, said he also intends to call relatives of the 24
children and three adults killed in the crash. He said the
prosecution could rest its case later this week but was not
specific.
   Defense attorney William Summers said he hasn't decided yet
whether Mahoney will testify.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
