<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchesVandalism     12-04 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Churches Vandalism,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Churches Vandalized Over Archbishop's Anti-Condom Stance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paint was splashed on doors of four Catholic
churches, and a group claiming responsibility said the vandalism
was retaliation for Archbishop Roger Mahony's opposition to the use
of condoms to prevent AIDS.
   Members of a group calling itself Greater Religious
Responsibility! claimed Sunday they had defaced the places of
worship with bright red paint, a color they said symbolizes the
blood of AIDS patients.
   Posters of Mahony were glued to the church entrances with
paraphrased excerpts from his recent policy statement such as,
``Safe sex is both a lie and a fraud.''
   Calls seeking comment went unanswered at the archbishop's office
and residence this morning.
   At St. Ambrose Catholic Church in West Hollywood, vandals
scrawled the word ``murderer'' beneath a photo of the archbishop,
said the Rev. John A. Beattie.
   A caller to KNBC-TV who said she was a member of the activist
group said the vandalism will continue until Mahony changes his
anti-condom stance. Another caller told the Los Angeles Times the
paint also denoted the tragedy of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   ``Someone dies of AIDS every 20 minutes in this country because
(Mahony's) policy is allowing that to continue unchecked,'' the
woman caller said.
   Mahony was chairman of a committee at the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops that rejected the use of condoms as a means of
fighting the spread of AIDS.
   In presenting the policy paper to the bishops, Mahony declared
that young people should avoid ``being trapped into the `safe-sex'
myth, which is both a lie and a fraud.''
   Beattie, who said at least 30 percent of his congregation is
gay, said he was saddened by the act of vandalism and believed the
archbishop's policy has been misinterpreted.
   ``St. Ambrose has done a lot to reach out to the gay community,
and why we should be singled out is a matter of confusion,'' he
said. ``The tenor of the archbishop's statement is one of
compassion for those with AIDS and of compassion for gays and
lesbians.''
</TEXT>
