<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Algeria     12-04 0104</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Algeria,0108</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Protest Bad Roads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas to disperse
hundreds of people protesting bad road conditions in the hills
above the capital.
   No arrests or injuries were reported.
   The protesters, mostly youthful Moslem fundamentalists, had
gathered Sunday to protest the City Council's failure to undertake
repairs.
   They erected barricades across the main highways in the
Eucalyptus quarter of Algiers and rejected calls to disperse
peacefully, police said.
   Angry residents have staged similar protests, supported by
fundamentalists, almost weekly in different parts of Algeria since
the nationwide riots in October 1988 that left hundreds dead and
injured.
