<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Press     12-04 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Press,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Press to Aid Colleagues in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czechoslavak journal associated with the
democratic opposition was awarded an operating grant Monday from a
group of Western press associations that have established a new
project to assist East Bloc media.
   A $10,000 grant was awarded to the Prague journal Lidove Noviny
to assure two more months of publication, the press associations
said.
   Lidove Noviny, which is almost a century old, reappeared two
years ago as an underground journal of the Charter 77 human rights
movement and recently received official authorization to publish.
Its board of directors includes banned playwright Vaclav Havel.
   The grant was one of two announced to launch ``The East Europe
Aid Project'' of the Paris-based Fund Against Censorship.
   The Fund Against Censorship is a joint project of the Inter
American Press Association, the International Federation of
Newspaper Publishers, the International Federation of the
Periodical Press, the International Press Institute, the North
American National Broadcasters Association and the World Press
Freedom Comittee.
   A second grant of $10,000 went to the Polish newspaper Gazeta
Wyborcza to cover the cost of shipping a printing press donated
last month by the French daily Le Monde. The press will allow the
daily to expand its press run and print supplements.
</TEXT>
