<FIRST>r a PM-JournalistMissing     12-04 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Journalist Missing,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Reporter No Longer Feared Dead in El Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A correspondent for a Spanish-language radio
network who was feared dead in El Salvador last week apparently is
all right and is expected home in Dallas tonight, the network said.
   Sal Valdez, 44, operations manager and a reporter for
Dallas-based Cadena Radio Centro had been missing from San Salvador
since Nov. 28.
   A statement from network president Barrett Alley said, ``We are
extremely grateful to receive word that Sal Valdez appears to be
all right and will be returning to Dallas this evening.''
   ``Due to security reasons, we have no more information at this
time. As soon as Sal is debriefed, we will have a full release and
statement as to his disappearance.''
   Network controller Bill Cherry said he could only say that
Valdez called someone this morning.
   Hispanic groups in Dallas had planned a vigil for Valdez this
evening in City Hall Plaza.
   Valdez, a Mexican-born U.S. citizen, arrived in El Salvador Nov.
25 to report on the latest outbreak in that country's civil war and
interviewed top officials including President Alfredo Cristiani.
</TEXT>
