<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Trial     12-04 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Trial,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Melee Erupts at Trial of Dissidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of two dissidents who
illegally visited communist North Korea erupted in a melee Monday
with their supporters shouting anti-government slogans and
scuffling with courtroom guards.
   About 50 people were expelled from a courthouse after they
shouted slogans and greeted the two dissidents by showering them
with confetti and paper airplanes.
   Radical student leader Im Su-kyong and dissident Catholic priest
Moon Gyu-hyon stood impassively as screaming supporters, friends
and relatives were forced from the courtroom by guards.
   ``Repeal National Security Law!'' protesters shouted, raising
clenched fists as they were taken away. Some protesters traded
punches with guards as they were hauled from the courtroom kicking
and screaming.
   The incident began as soon as the two defendants were led into
the courtroom for the third day of hearings in their trial. About
200 supporters, many of them students, shouted slogans demanding
their release.
   Senior judge Hwang Sang-hyon adjourned the hearing and ordered
about 40 people expelled. Another 10 were ordered out when they
protested, shouting slogans and insults.
   Outside the courthouse, police arrested 21 people, mostly
college students, for either demonstrating in support of the two
dissidents or trying to carry confetti into the courtroom.
   Miss Im and Moon were charged with making illegal trips to North
Korea. If convicted, they could be sentenced to as many as 10 years
in prison under the National Security Law.
   Miss Im, a 20-year-old junior majoring in French at Seoul's
Hankook University of Foreign Studies, traveled to the North Korean
capital of Pyongyang without government authorization to attend a
July 1-8 world youth festival.
   Moon, a U.S.-educated clergyman, was sent to North Korea by a
group of dissident Catholic priests to escort Miss Im home. Both
were arrested upon returning to South Korea through the border
village of Panmunjom Aug. 15.
   Both claimed their trips were intended to help reunite the
Korean peninsula, divided in 1945.
   But prosecutors have presented evidence showing the pair making
speeches in North Korea, criticizing South Korea and the United
States. The two called South Korea ``a colony of the U.S.
imperialists.''
   In a separate trial Monday, a criminal court sentenced the Rev.
Nam Kuk-hyon, a dissident Catholic priest, to two years'
imprisonment, suspended for three years, for playing a leading role
in sending Moon to North Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
