<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     12-04 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seventh Round of Inter-Korea Red Cross Talks Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Red Cross officials from South Korea
and North Korea met Monday but failed to agree on terms for
exchanging separated family members before the end of the year,
reports said.
   Both sides agreed to continue discussing possible family visits
through a telephone hotline linking Seoul and Pyongyang, the two
Korean capitals, according to the South Korean news agency, Yonhap.
   North Korea and South Korea have been trying to arrange a
four-day exchange of families that would be only the second such
exchange in four decades.
   The Korean peninsula was divided at the end of World War II.
About 10 million family members were separated by the 1945 division
of their land and the Korean War.
   Monday's 50-minute meeting was the seventh since September and
was called by North Korea. It was the first closed-door session and
foreign press was barred. Ten Korean news reporters were invited to
cover the talks.
   The two nations initially agreed to exchange more than 500
separated family members and entertainers for a four-day visit
starting Dec. 8, but talks broke down when North Korea insisted on
broadcasting a three-hour revolutionary opera written by North
Korean leader Kim Il Sung on South Korean TV. South Korean
officials rejected the demand as a propaganda ploy.
   Yonhap quoted chief South Korean delegate Song Young-dae as
saying after Monday's meeting that both sides confirmed it would be
impossible to exchange family members before the end of this year.
   Song urged North Korea to cooperate to carry out the family
exchange early next year, Yonhap said.
   The chief North Korean delegate, Pak Yong Su, left the
conference room without answering questions by reporters, Yonhap
said.
</TEXT>
