<FIRST>r a PM-SalvadorProtest     12-04 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador Protest,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>125 Arrested in El Salvador Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 people were arrested this morning
for blockading a federal building to protest U.S. aid to the
government of El Salvador, police said.
   All 112 were given summonses for disorderly conduct and two also
were charged with resisting arrest, said Officer Janice Swinney, a
police spokeswoman.
   The protest began with an interfaith service about 7:30 a.m. in
lower Manhattan, said Michael D'Elia, a spokesman for the Emergency
Coalition for Peace in El Salvador.
   About 250 people, including Roman Catholic nuns and other clergy
members, then moved to the main entrance to the building and began
a blockade about 8 a.m., he said. The demonstration was over about
an hour later.
   ``We were protesting the violence that the U.S. government is
supporting in El Salvador by sending hundreds of millions of
dollars annually to a government that Amnesty International,
Americas Watch and other human rights organizations have repeatedly
condemned as one of the worst human rights violators in the
world,'' D'Elia said.
   El Salvadoran security forces, who are battling leftist rebels,
have in recent weeks raided several churches and were blamed by
some for last month's killing of six Jesuit priests from the
country's Central American University.
