<FIRST>u i PM-WarsawPact 3rdLd-Writethru   12-04 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Warsaw Pact, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0606,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warsaw Pact Leaders Condemn Czechoslovak Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to add more quotes from statement of condemnation.
Pickup 4th pvs, `The Soviet-led...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union and the four other Warsaw Pact
nations that invaded Czechoslovakia in 1968 to crush a reform
movement today condemned the action.
   The statement came as East bloc leaders, including the first
non-communist head of state, met for a Warsaw Pact meeting to hear
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's report on his recent talks with
President Bush.
   The leaders of the Soviet Union, Bulgaria, Hungary, East Germany
and Poland said the entrance of their troops into Czechoslovakia 21
years ago constitituted ``interference in the internal affairs of a
sovereign Czechoslovakia and must be condemned.''
   ``Interrupting the process of democratic renewal in
Czechoslovakia, these unjustified actions had long-term negative
consequences,'' added the statement, which was read on the evening
news and carried by the official Tass news agency.
   The Soviet-led invasion crushed the ``Prague Spring'' reforms of
Alexander Dubcek, who was subsequently ousted as the Communist
Party leader. He has since re-emerged as one of the spokespeople of
the pro-democracy movement sweeping Czechoslovakia.
   Meanwhile, President Bush was in Brussels briefing NATO leaders
on the summit. Dutch Foreign Minister Hans van den Broek said Bush
told the allies he and Gorbachev agreed ``to propose to their
allies ... a meeting of government leaders at the signing of an
agreement on conventional disarmament.''
   The leaders meeting in Moscow included Wojciech Jaruzelski,
Poland's Communist president, and Egon Krenz of East Germany, who
resigned as his country's Communist Party chief Sunday along with
the rest of the Politburo but retained the ceremonial post of
president.
   The East German news agency ADN said Premier Hans Modrow headed
the nation's delegation.
   Tass did not mention the arrival of Poland's Solidarity Prime
Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the first non-communist East bloc
leader to attend a Warsaw Pact meeting since the alliance was
created in 1955 in response to the formation of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
   Mazowiecki's participation highlights the radical changes that
have occurred recently in Eastern Europe.
   Tass said Gorbachev would tell the allies of his weekend talks
in Malta with Bush but it did not say when the Soviet leader would
address the meeting.
   Tass announced earlier that Western journalists would not be
accredited for the meeting and said they would have to depend on
state-run Soviet media for reports.
   The Warsaw Pact last held a meeting in July in Romania. Since
then, there have been dramatic political changes in many of the
member countries and calls for reforms within the pact itself.
   East Germay's longtime leader Erich Honecker was ousted Oct. 18
after thousands of citizens fled to the West and others staged mass
protests for reforms. Krenz replaced Honecker, and on Nov. 9 his
government bowed to continued pressure and opened East Germany's
borders to allow people to travel freely.
   It also was the first Warsaw Pact meeting for Petar Mladenov of
Bulgaria and Karel Urbanek of Czechoslovakia.
   Mladenov replaced ousted Bulgarian party chief Todor Zhivkov on
Nov. 10, and Urbanek replaced Czechoslovak leader Milos Jakes on
Nov. 24. Zhivkov and Jakes fell after similar pro-democracy
demonstrations in their countries, and their replacements pledged
reforms.
   The official Bulgarian news agency BTA said Mladenov would stay
on in Moscow after the Warsaw Pact summit on a visit at the
invitation of the Soviet Communist Party.
   In Bucharest, official Romanian media reported that President
Nicolae Ceausescu headed his nation's delegation to the meeting.
Ceausescu has rejected calls for reform.
</TEXT>
