<FIRST>r w AM-HomeSales     12-04 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>New-Home Sales Off But Analysts Predict Some Improvement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new homes fell 0.5 percent in
October, the government reported Monday. Analysts said overall
purchases were driven down by a 24.7 percent decline in the West
due to the San Francisco Bay-area earthquake and the effects of the
slowing economy.
   But economists said the sales pace should improve somewhat over
the next few months as mortgage interest rates drop to the mid-9
percent range. No analyst predicted a surge in sales.
   ``The report says that housing market activity has improved some
from the sluggish pace of March and February, but that the market
is by no means taking off,'' Thomas Holloway, senior economist for
the Mortgage Bankers Association, said.
   The Commerce Department said new single-family homes were sold
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 649,000 in October
following a revised 10.2 percent plunge in September. September
sales originally were reported down 14 percent.
   Sales in the West fell 53,000 units on an annual basis to
161,000 homes. But all other regions posted gains, prompting David
Berson, chief economist for the Federal National Mortgage
Association, to conclude ``the earthquake appeared to keep people
from buying new homes.''
   Michael Carliner, an economist with the National Association of
Home Builders, said economic sluggishness also contributed to the
lack of western sales. Part of the problem, he said, was slower
defense spending, which resulted in significant layoffs.
   Home sales had fallen dramatically earlier this year as the
Federal Reserve Board pumped up interest rates to slow the economy
and thus contain inflation. As inflationary pressures cooled,
however, the Fed has permitted gradual decreases in rates since the
beginning of the summer.
   Fixed-rate mortgage interest rates fell to an average of 9.82
percent by the end of October after rising into the double digits
in September, according to a survey by the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp.
   Despite the lower interest rates, Michael P. Niemira, an
economist with the Mitsubishi Bank in New York, said ``the new home
market appears to be hurt by the ever-widening gap between new and
existing home prices.
   ``Builders also appear to be misreading the current market,'' he
said. ``It is a market for low-priced homes and builders generally
are not building for that market.''
   The Commerce Department said the median price of a new home in
October rose 5.3 percent to $127,900. The median means half of the
homes cost more and half less. The average price of a new home was
unchanged at $151,900.
   On the other hand, the National Association of Realtors reported
Monday that the median price of an existing single-family home was
$92,100.
   New home sales in the Northeast rose 47.8 percent but Fannie
Mae's Berson said that reflected a low September sales count rather
than growing market strength in the area.
   The South posted a 5.7 percent increase, while the Midwest
recorded a 3.7 percent gain.
   New-home sales for the first nine months were down 4.4 percent
from the same period in 1988.
   In its report, the real estate trade group said that its index
measuring the ability of the typical American family to buy an
existing home rose in October to its highest level in eight months
because of stable mortgage rates and a drop in the median home
price.
   The real estate group said the index rose to 106.1, from 103.5
in September and was the highest since it was 106.7 last February.
That means a family with a median income of $33,365 had 106.1
percent of the income needed to buy a median-priced existing home
costing $92,100.
</TEXT>
