<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-VOA     12-04 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-VOA,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voice of America Opens Second Soviet Bloc Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Voice of America, the U.S.
government's broadcast service, opened its second Soviet bloc
bureau Monday and launched discussions with Polish state radio on
the exchange of programming.
   ``They were jamming us two years ago,'' said VOA Director
Richard W. Carlson.
   To mark the opening of the Poland bureau, VOA and Polish Radio
prepared a live Monday night program permitting callers in Poland
to discuss their country's economic situation with Polish-speaking
experts in Washington, Chicago, New York and Warsaw.
   ``This is unheard of given the context of our journalistic
relationship with this country so recently,'' Carlson said. ``It is
definitely amazing. We did not envision this at all.''
   VOA, which broadcasts in 43 languages to an estimated 130
million people worldwide, for years was jammed by East bloc
countries and denounced by their leaders. VOA correspondents were
denied visas to work in Eastern Europe or given only limited access.
   Jamming has ended in the Soviet bloc in recent years, Carlson
said, and VOA opened a Moscow bureau last year.
   VOA, heard by an estimated 50 percent of Poland's adults at
least once a week, was given permanent accreditation in Poland in
April, Carlson said.
   No full-time correspondent has been assigned due to budget
constraints, but the Warsaw bureau will be staffed on a rotating
basis by reporters stationed elsewhere.
   A Warsaw bureau also is being established by Radio Free Europe,
another long-time propaganda enemy for its uncensored reports to
Eastern Europe.
   The strict state control of Polish radio and TV loosened in
1988. The Solidarity-led government of Tadeusz Mazowiecki, who
became the East bloc's first non-communist leader in August, has
vowed to free the flow of information.
   On Nov. 13, Polish Radio ran a live broadcast, provided by the
VOA, of Solidarity leader Lech Walesa's speech to the U.S. Congress.
   VOA, which produces six hours of live Polish-language reports
daily from Washington headquarters, will continue talks with Polish
authorities on placing its programming on state radio, Carlson said.
   Also being discussed are exchanges of broadcasters and training
programs, Carlson said.
   VOA correspondents are being welcomed elsewhere in Eastern
Europe as well.
   Hungary offers virtually free access, and Czechoslovakia has
provided ongoing accreditaion for Czech and English-language
correspondents, said William Hill, chief of the VOA European
Division.
   Bulgaria recently allowed a VOA representative to cover an
environmental forum. And after 18 visa denials during three years,
a VOA correspondent was accredited for East Germany's 40th
anniversary events attended by Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, Hill said.
   Only Romania and Albania continue to bar the correspondents,
with Romania dening access to a party congress last month, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
