<FIRST>u w AM-Catastrophic-Premiums     12-04 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic-Premiums,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catastrophiiic Payments Continuing Beyond Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 33 million retirees will have to pay
premiums for several more months for Medicare catastrophic coverage
_ a program that will be abolished on Dec. 31.
   Gwendolyn King, commissioner of the Social Security
Administration, blamed Congress' late action in repealing the law.
She said Monday there is no way that Social Security computers can
be adjusted more quickly to halt withholding of the premiums from
monthly benefit checks.
   The premiums will be refunded in a lump sum later, Ms. King said.
   ``We have people going flat out ... but we won't be able to make
all the changes until perhaps the end of April or the beginning of
May,'' Ms. King said.
   That means the great majority of retirees _ perhaps up to 29
million _ will have to pay $5.30 a month for three or four months
for a program that will no longer exist. Some retirees pay less;
others pay more.
   ``The bottom line is that Social Security will unscramble this
egg, but we did not lay it,'' Ms. King said.
   Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., chairman of the Senate Aging
Committee, said in a letter to Ms. King that ``a lengthy delay (in
halting collection of the premiums) will create a firestorm of
protest. We must recognize the impending firestorm and move rapidly
to alleviate the problem.''
   Pryor predicted that if the Social Security Administration
continues withholding the premiums until early summer, it could
take the rest of the year for retirees to get their money back.
   Pryor estimated that would temporarily take $1 billion out of
the pockets of the elderly. In many cases, he said, they need that
money to pay private ``Medigap'' insurance policy premium increases
expected to result from repeal of federal catastrophic coverage.
   ``We knew there might be a problem but I don't think we expected
it to take this long to resolve,'' said John Rother of the American
Association of Retired Persons. ``Congress normally gives the
Social Security Administraton about a three-month lead time for
changes.''
   Since Jan. 1, most people 65 and older have been paying $4 a
month to finance part of the cost of Medicare catastrophic
coverage. The year-old program aims to prevent a retiree from being
by bankrupted by a major illness. The monthly premium is scheduled
to rise to $5.30 on Jan. 1.
   Premiums paid this year will not be refunded; they finance
extended hospital coverage and other, minor catastrophic benefits
that have been in effect since January.
   Two-thirds of the cost of the program would have been borne by
higher-income retirees through an income surtax of up to $800 a
year.
   Officials have no way of knowing whether those people have been
making periodic payments of the surtax along with their quarterly
estimated payments of income tax. Those who have, and those past 65
who are earning wages and may have paid the surtax through the
withholding system, will be able to subtract the surtax from taxes
due with they file their returns early next year.
   Congress repealed catastrophic because of protests from those
higher-income retirees and from others who have a private
catastrophic plan or coverage geared to their retirement benefits.
   The repeal vote came Nov. 22. Although Congress has adjourned
until Jan. 23, the bill has not yet been delivered to President
Bush for his signature. That could come this week.
   Ms. King, Pryor and Rother said they regret that some people
with the lowest income will be hurt by the delay in halting
collection of the premiums.
   ``My concern is for those on fixed income who cannot afford to
see $5 go out of their checks,'' Ms. King said. ``That's a lot of
money for those people and it is little consolation for them to
know they will get a refund in the future.''
</TEXT>
