<FIRST>r a AM-RomeoandJuliet     12-04 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romeo and Juliet,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchange Student and American Girlfriend Still Fighting Separation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Love has found new champions in the
battle to allow a Finnish exchange student to return to high school
here after being banished to Maine because he was spending too much
time with his American girlfriend.
   Iiro Lehtinen, 18, said he was given two hours to pack his bags
Nov. 11 before being transferred to South Portland, Maine, because
exchange program leaders said his friendship with Kelly LaPointe
was causing his grades to suffer.
   Lehtinen, in Farmington briefly Sunday, spent about an hour at
LaPointe's home with her and her family, met with a state
legislator who has taken an interest in the case and was
interviewed for two national television programs.
   His transfer prompted a walk-out last week of about 100
students, a third of Farmington's student body.
   Officials of the Education Foundation for Foreign Study, which
sponsors the exchange program, say Lehtinen was transferred because
he was spending too much time with LaPointe and not enough time
with his host family.
   The group's regional director, Meg Holliday, has denied anyone
from her organization told the youths they had to break up, but
Lehtinen said he was told by an official after he got to South
Portland that he had two weeks to break up with LaPointe.
   He said the order since has been replaced with directives
limiting him to one visit and two telephone conversations with
LaPointe a month.
   State Rep. William Tsiros said the move was an insult to
Farmington's hospitality and a violation of the boy's civil rights.
   The foundation and the host family ``are missing the point that
it is normal for an 18-year-old boy to have a romantic relationship
with a girl,'' Tsiros said.
   LaPointe, 17, said the foundation officials make it sound like
she sat around all day in front of the television waiting for
Lehtinen to come over.
   ``I'm on the honor roll, I'm a Big Sister and I play sports
year-round,'' she said. ``Whenever Iiro and I were together we were
out with other people at high school games and functions.''
   Tsiros said he has called state officials in Concord, federal
officials in Washington and the foundation headquarters in
Massachusetts to try to bring Lehtinen back.
   And the boy's father has been lobbying from Finland to reverse
the decision.
   The host family won't talk about the dispute.
</TEXT>
