<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-War     12-04 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-War,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>World War II Horror Revived in Britain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Europe is shedding the legacy of World War
II, a British libel trial has in a way resurrected it.
   The case that Britons were reading about in their Sunday
newspapers, even as President Bush and President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev were meeting to shape the post-postwar era, revived a
little-known horror in May 1945, when the British army repatriated
70,000 Cossack and Yugoslav refugees to a grisly fate at the hands
of their communist enemies.
   The trial ended last week in a record $2.6 million award, and
showed the abiding power of World War II to disrupt lives and pose
painful questions a generation later.
   The victorious plaintiff in the High Court in London was Lord
Aldington, former Conservative Party deputy chairman, business
leader and college head. In 1945 he was Brig. Toby Low, the officer
based in Allied-occupied Austria who was ordered to implement the
deportation.
   The most prominent defendant was Count Nikolai Tolstoy, a
historian who had written a pamphlet accusing Aldington of
responsibility for sending the Cossacks and Yugoslavs, men, women
and children, to the firing squads or labor camps.
   Aldington, 74, endured 30 hours of cross-examination. At one
stage he stopped answering questions and wept.
   Tolstoy and co-defendant Nigel Watts, a realtor who distributed
the pamphlet, were ordered to pay the damages plus an almost equal
sum in legal costs.
   Tolstoy said the verdict had left him financially ruined.
   For some, the case had modern-day resonances in Britain's
imminent plans to repatriate 40,000 Vietnamese boat people encamped
in Hong Kong.
   Columnist Simon Jenkins, 46, wrote in The Sunday Times that his
generation should be wary of using hindsight to judge officers
acting 44 years ago in the chaotic aftermath of a five-year war.
   But he wondered whether after the boat people were dealt with,
``after hundreds more deaths, will there be remorseful memoirs,
bitter accusations _ and yet more libel trials?''
   The Russian Cossacks and Yugoslavs who had fled the Soviet army
to safety behind British lines were anti-Communist, anti-Soviet,
and in many cases had fought for the Germans.
   Britain had agreed secretly with Soviet dictator Josef Stalin to
return all Soviet and Yugoslav prisoners. It had no illusions the
evacuees faced a rough time after repatriation, but felt bound by
the agreement in order to ensure the repatriation of its own
prisoners in Soviet hands.
   The story that unfolded over nine weeks in the packed court was
filled with anguish. It told of British authorities resorting to
subterfuge, telling the prisoners they were being sent to safety in
Italy; of prisoners killing themselves while still in British
hands; of British soldiers allowing prisoners to escape rather than
have them on their conscience; of other soldiers rifle-butting them
into the trains, despising them for having been pro-German.
   Nigel Nicolson, a young officer at the time, remembered seeing
men herded into cattle trucks and sent screaming to certain
execution.
   ``We considered it one of the most disgraceful operations any
British troops anywhere had been ordered to undertake,'' Nicolson,
now 72, testified.
   Aldington said he had only obeyed orders and had no reason to
believe executions would follow.
   ``There were many officers who were very unhappy about what we
had to do and I was amongst them, but I didn't make a fuss about
it. I just got on with my job,'' he testified.
   Aldington told his cross-examiner: ``You say I knew they were
going to be massacred. That is not what I was told. I was told that
war criminals would be tried and others would be put to work.
   ``It is terrible what happened, I know. Nobody's denying that
what happened was ghastly. I don't understand why you want to harry
me over and over again.''
   Tolstoy, the British-born grandson of a Russian Cossack, has
written several books aimed at exposing what he calls an
``inexcusable cover-up in British public life.''
   Robert Knight, a teacher of European studies who testified for
Aldington, wrote in the Guardian that Tolstoy had ``sunk into the
swamp of his own conspiracy theory.''
   In summing up, the judge said some might think the verdict would
settle the debate for good. ``It would be very nice to think it
would,'' he said. ``But it seems to me unlikely that will happen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
