<FIRST>r a PM-MusicPayola     12-04 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Music Payola,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Innocent Pleas Entered in `Payola' Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent record promoter pleaded
innocent today to charges that he provided cash and cocaine to get
songs played on several radio stations.
   Joseph Isgro, who appeared before U.S. Magistrate Volney V.
Brown Jr., pleaded innocent to 51 counts of making illegal payoffs,
distributing cocaine, racketeering, conspiracy, obstruction of
justice, tax fraud and mail fraud.
   A Jan. 23 trial was scheduled before U.S. District Judge James
M. Ideman.
   A second defendant, Jeffrey Monka, pleaded innocent to
money-laundering charges today. Prosecutors say Monka set up a sham
company to help Isgro launder the cash used for ``payola'' to
employees of several radio stations.
   Payoffs allegedly were made at stations in Los Angeles, Fresno
and El Paso, Texas.
   Former Columbia Records executive Raymond Anderson was to be
arraigned next week. Prosecutors say Anderson took kickbacks from
Isgro.
   Isgro is free on $300,000 bail and Anderson is free on $50,000
bail. Bail was set at $100,000 for Monka, whose attorney, William
Pitman, said his client has remained in jail because of a clerical
error.
