<FIRST>u i AM-Czech-Mood Bjt   12-04 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Mood, Bjt,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heady Revolution Pervades Every Corner of Prague</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defiant liberty bell stands on a
hill above Prague, but many now notice revolutionaries failed to
add a clapper to their makeshift symbol. They're still building the
revolution.
   ``The Communists are playing for time, and we can't rest a
minute,'' said Lenka Ressova, a young technician, before joining
more than 150,000 people Monday on Wenceslas Square.
   The crowd, chanting, ``Resign! Resign!'' delivered its verdict
on a new Communist-dominated Cabinet meant to shape a new
Czechoslovakia. In thundering unison, people added, ``Free
elections!''
   But at opposition headquarters, Civic Forum leaders wrestled
with a problem now familiar as the Iron Curtain tatters: Where to
find popular, experienced leaders in societies ruled 40 years by a
single ideology.
   ``They're fighting over every line,'' reported a Civic Forum
member, emerging from strategy talks over how to protest a new
government of Communist Party holdovers and only five little-known
outsiders. ``This will not be easy.''
   He asked anonymity, no longer afraid of secret police but wanted
to stay clear of internal politics.
   The overall mood is confident, even ebullient, as Czechoslovaks
try out new freedoms few dreamed were possible only weeks ago. But
cold, hard realism has replaced the first warm rush.
   A clear strain of anxiety that marked faces at Monday's mass
rally was reflected all over town. Politics penetrated every
crevice of Prague.
   ``No one talks of anything else,'' said Hana Lingerova, slinging
plates of roast pork at the Old Synagogue cafe. She amused
customers by making folds in a banknote to turn a pictured
Communist hero into the movie alien from ``E.T. _ The
Extra-Terrestrial.''
   In downtown metro stops, huge crowds mobbed public TV sets. In
the outskirts, people rose at 3:30 a.m. to get the morning papers
before they sold out.
   At the Charles University Faculty of Medicine and Physics,
frazzled students watched TV, nibbled at stale sandwiches and
churned out leaflets on their prehistoric computers.
   Milan Horak, 21, studied a visiting reporter's passport with
more care than the immigration officer at Prague Airport.
   ``Infiltrators are trying to sneak in, to divide us and change
our minds,'' he said. A revolutionary guard was comprised of four
sleepy students armed with a guitar.
   Horak acknowledged that although people demand that the
Communists hand over power, no alternate leaders were emerging.
``Our leaders are compromised, and the people who could lead were
driven off,'' he said.
   Asked about Alexander Dubcek, Horak gave the awkward shrug which
often greets that name. Dubcek, a powerful symbol, led
Czechoslovakia to the ``Prague Spring'' that was crushed by Warsaw
Pact tanks 21 years ago. But for most young people, he has been a
Communist for too long.
   Vaclav Havel, the playwright whose life-long insistence on human
freedoms shaped the script for the revolution, rejects any
prolonged role in the politics of what comes next.
   In the vacuum of power, untested names rise in moments of glory.
There are insistent calls for Valtr Komarek, a reform-minded
economist, but critics say he is blemished by his close ties to the
failing system.
   ``Now comes the hard part, the pressure of the mind,'' said
Jaroslav Nesetril, a professor who dropped in to check on the
students. ``The Communists are more experienced, more organized. It
is in nature that everything is reversible.''
   In the bowels of the ABC Theater, people who helped bring off
the revolution harbor few illusions about the next act. They admire
Havel and the intellectuals around him, but most agree it is time
for others to move in.
   ``That is the question, where to find the leaders,'' said Ivo
Niederle, a popular actor. ``We must find them.''
   Havel has offered to play some sort of transitional role, but
has made it plain he is not eager to be the missing clapper in
Czechoslovakia's liberty bell.
   Late Saturday night, he emerged from a dinner, haggard.
   ``Are you going into politics?'' he was asked.
   ``I'm going to bed,'' he replied.
</TEXT>
