<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-NewEurope     12-04 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Europe,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Endorsing European Change Easier Than Keeping Pace with It</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev are finding it easier to endorse political change
in Europe than to deal with the consequences.
   After a summit meeting in which both leaders envisioned an end
to East-West rivalry, they face the considerably more difficult
task of redefining their respective military alliances without
upsetting a balance of power established through 40 years of Cold
War.
   For Gorbachev, the assignment is especially tricky. He seeks to
preserve his Warsaw Pact alliance at the same time that its
hard-line communist regimes are being swept aside. During the
post-summit news conference, a Czechoslovakian journalist pointedly
asked whether he had renounced the Brezhnev doctrine used to
justify the 1968 Soviet invasion of that country as it began to tip
Westward.
   ``Every nation is an independent entity in world politics and
every people has the right to choose its own destiny, the destiny
of its own state,'' the Soviet leader replied.
   Gorbachev's response underscored the diminishing role _ and
perhaps ability _ of the Kremlin to control the political avalanche
in Eastern Europe.
   ``No one can avoid this evolutionary process,'' he said.
   Bush, following Gorbachev in response to the Czechoslovakian
question, praised the Soviet leader for the reforms he has started
in the Soviet Union and its allies.
   However, the president is not as eager to claim, as the Soviet
leader had at the joint news conference, that the ``epoch of the
cold war'' is over.
   On Monday, after he briefed NATO allies in Brussels, Bush said:
``Is the Cold War raging like it was before, in the times of the
Berlin blockade? Absolutely not. But if I signal to you there's no
Cold War, then they'll say, `Well, what are you doing with troops
in Europe?'''
   Both leaders say they want to preserve the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and the Warsaw Pact to maintain stability, but want to
conclude an agreement by late 1990 to cut troops in Central Europe,
withdrawing 30,000 U.S. and 325,000 Soviet soldiers.
   The memory of Nazi Germany, which invaded many NATO and Warsaw
Pact members during World War II, still looms large in the European
equation.
   Gorbachev has expressed concern about a proposal last week by
West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl for a confederation of East and
West Germany. Soviet officials say West Germany has never renounced
its claims to the pre-war German borders, which included parts of
Poland.
   Bush sought to assuage those Soviet fears by reaffirming U.S.
support for the 1975 Helsinki Accords, which were signed by the
United States, Soviet Union and 33 other nations and ``spells out a
concept of permanent borders.''
   The Helsinki accords, said Gorbachev, ``summed up the results of
the Second World War and consolidated the results of the war. ...
And the reality is such that we have today's Europe with two German
states.''
   Bush reiterated the U.S. position that any move toward the
reunification of Germany will have to be gradual and respect the
rights of people on both sides of the present border to
self-determination.
   At the same time, Bush made it clear that the United States will
keep its troops in Europe as long as NATO allies want them there.
   ``The United States will remain a European power, and that means
that the United States will stay engaged in the future of Europe
and in our common defense,'' Bush said.
   To cope with Soviet concerns about Germany unified outside the
postwar alliance strucure and to keep pace with the changes in
Eastern Europe, Gorbachev has accepted Polish proposals to
restructure the Warsaw Pact. NATO should do the same, he said.
   ``They should not remain military alliances, but rather
military-political alliances and later on, just political
alliances, so that their nature would change in accordance with the
changes on the continent,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Bryan Brumley, a Washington based writer, covers
national security issues for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
