<FIRST>r a AM-HospitalShooting     12-04 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Shooting,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Killing Father in Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERVILLE, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing his
77-year-old father in his hospital bed was in stable condition
Monday recovering from two self-inflicted gunshot wounds, officials
said.
   Leonide L. Michaud Jr., 47, was under police guard at Waterville
Osteopathic Hospital, said hospital spokeswoman Bonnie Lantz.
   Michaud was charged with murder after he allegedly shot and
killed his father, Leonide L. Michaud Sr., also of Waterville, at
the Thayer Unit of Mid-Maine Medical Center.
   Spokesman Stephen McCausland of the Maine Public Safety
Department said the younger Michaud went to his father's hospital
room Saturday night, pulled out a handgun and held two nurses, an
unarmed security guard and another patient at gunpoint before
several shots were fired.
   The elder Michaud was dead and his son suffered two ``minor''
self-inflicted wounds to the head, McCausland said. The others were
not hurt, police said.
   Michaud Jr. was given emergency medical treatment and then taken
to the Waterville police station, where he was charged with murder,
McCausland said. While in a holding cell, Michaud complained of
chest pains and was rushed to Waterville Osteopathic Hospital.
   McCausland would not comment on a motive.
   McCausland said the Michaud family had been told by doctors that
his illnesses were probably terminal. Michaud suffered ``a variety
of ailents associated with old age,'' McCausland added.
</TEXT>
