<DOCNO> AP891204-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Jordan     12-04 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jordan,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Appoints Islamic Sympathizer Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Zeid Bin Shaker resigned
Monday and was replaced by Mudar Badran, who has held the office
twice before and is sympathetic to Islamic fundamentalists.
   King Hussein told Badran to concentrate on improving Jordan's
dismal economy situation and to support the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Bin Shaker's resignation had been expected following
parliamentary elections last month, the first nationwide balloting
in 22 years. He took office in April after the resignation of Zaid
Rifai and formed a transitional government for the purpose of
preparing for the elections.
   The king assigned the outgoing Cabinet to continue its duties
until Badran forms a new one.
   ``I ask you to work with the PLO and to support the
steadfastness of our brothers, the Palestinians in their occupied
territories,'' Hussein said in a letter to Badran, the former chief
of the royal court.
   The monarch stressed the importance of increasing the kingdom's
foreign currency reserves and maintaining the Jordanian dinar's
purchasing power.
   Since late last year, the dinar's value against other currencies
has fallen sharply under the pressure of foreign debts of more than
$8.3 billion.
   Riots triggered by price increases of 10 percent to 50 percent
for food and fuel led to riots that killed nine people in April and
led to Rifai's resignation.
   Royal palace officials said naming of a new Cabinet might be
delayed because of disputes among potential new ministers over the
assignment of portfolios.
   The palace officials said the new Cabinet would include some
former ministers, some members of the royally appointed senate and
some deputies elected Nov. 8.
   According to one royal palace source, the disputes stem from
three Moslem Brotherhood deputies who were assigned portfolios
``which they did not accept.''
   The source did not explain what chairs they were assigned but he
said they were seeking the portfolios of education, higher
education and Islamic religious affairs.
   The Moslem Brotherhood, which won 25 seats in Parliament,
campaigned to impose stricter Islamic laws and improve social
welfare benefits. There are nearly three dozen deputies in the
80-seat Parliament with Islamic leanings.
   Badran is known to sympathize with extremist Moslem factions,
including the Moslem Brotherhood.
   The November elections were the first nationwide poll since 1967
when Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan. Hussein last year
renounced Jordan's claim to the West Bank in favor of the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   Badran, who graduated from the University of Damscus in 1957
with a law degree, served as prime minister as well as defense and
foreign affairs minister in 1976-79 and 1980-84.
   During both of Badran's terms, Jordanian relations with Syria
deteriorated, first because Syrian alleged Jordan was supporting
Moslem Brotherhood activists seeking to topple Syrian President
Hafez Assad.
   The countries reconciled in 1979 after Arabs joined together to
oppose the Camp David peace treaty between Egypt and Israel.
   A year later, relations were severed again when Syria sided with
Iran in its war against Iraq. Jordan was Iraq's main backer.
   When Hussein patched up his relations with Assad in 1985, he
apologized for Jordanian backing of the Brotherhood and claimed it
had been carried out without his knowledge by previous governments,
including Badran's.
   Jordan's relations with its powerful northern neighbor are
lukewarm, mainly because it opposes Syrian's military presence in
Lebanon.
   As royal court chief, Badran was responsible for palace
operations and served as a key political adviser to Hussein. The
post has often been a stepping stone to the prime minister's office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
