<FIRST>u i AM-NATO-Reax     12-04 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO-Reax,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-NATO Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>American Allies Relieved U.S. Keeping Strong Ties to Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's NATO allies Monday welcomed
President Bush's determination to keep strong military links to
Western Europe despite the diminishing security threat posed by the
Soviet Union.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, though, appeared to
have qualms about some of the president's remarks, in which Bush
raised the possibility of greater arms cuts in Europe and even
closer ties among the European Community nations.
   She said that Bush's speech to leaders of the 16-nation North
Atlantic Treaty Organization ``was so full of meat that we really
should consider it very carefully before we reply to it.''
   Others were not so hesitant.
   Dutch Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers said he was impressed by the
United States' ``extraordinarily positive attitude'' toward events
in Europe.
   ``It has nothing to do with a `we are pulling out' attitude,''
he told reporters. ``On the contrary, they are again promising a
meaningful presence (in Europe).''
   Belgian officials said it was obvious that the president took
Europe seriously.
   Just last week, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney was at NATO
headquarters trying to dispel fears that the United States would
unilaterally pull its troops out of Europe because of budget
deficit pressures and reduced East-West tensions.
   Bush, too, went out of his way to reassure the allies after
giving them an account of his weekend talks with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev in Malta.
   ``I pledge today that the United States will maintain
significant military forces in Europe as long as our allies desire
our presence as part of a common security effort,'' Bush told the
allies during a closed-door meeting. His remarks were later
released by the White House.
   ``The U.S. will remain a European power,'' he said. ``That means
the U.S. will stay engaged in the future of Europe, and in our
common defense.''
   Mrs. Thatcher said his reassurance was a key outcome of the
meeting.
   Reports of American plans to slash military spending in coming
years have raised concern about the United States' future ties to
its European allies.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney said there was no
question of withdrawing his country's forces from Europe. NATO
provides a security link between the two North American nations and
those in Western Europe.
   The officials stressed NATO's importance during the dizzying
pace of political and economic reforms in some of the countries of
the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact, the East bloc's military alliance.
   Mulroney said NATO was ``more relevant now than ever.''
   ``It offers both security and stability,'' said Mrs. Thatcher.
   Belgian Prime Minister Wilfried Martens agreed it has an
essential role to play at a time of change.
   In his speech, Bush put special emphasis on negotiations between
NATO and the Warsaw Pact to slash conventional, or non-nuclear,
arms in Europe. Last May, Bush offered a sweeping plan to reduce
those weapons and set a one-year deadline for negotiating a treaty.
   ``We have made good progress since then,'' he said, ``but too
little and too slowly to take full advantage of the opportunity
before us: the chance to ease the Soviet army out of Eastern Europe
and substantially reduce the risk of surprise attack and
aggression.''
   He warned the other leaders that the arms bargaining ``could be
overrun by events. That could be dangerous and we must avoid it.''
   He said he was ``prepared to look with an open mind at ways in
which we can together achieve even lower levels of conventional and
nuclear forces in Europe as part of a negotiated agreement.''
   The president urged the 12 nations of the European Community
trading bloc to press ahead, maybe even intensify, efforts to
become more closely bound. The nations are trying to dismantle
trade barriers to create a single, European-wide market by the end
of 1992.
   Bush said the community also should play a role ``as a magnet
that draws the forces of reform forward in Eastern Europe.''
   His remarks touched on sensitive topics for Mrs. Thatcher.
   She has urged a more cautious attitude than some of the allies
toward the events unfolding in Eastern Europe.
   She also has been isolated from other Common Market members over
plans for a tight economic and monetary union that would lead to a
common currency and European-wide central bank system. The
community holds a summit later this week in Strasbourg, France, to
thrash out these issues.
   Mrs. Thatcher insisted she did not feel left out of the NATO
talks. ``Time after time, the word caution came (up),'' she said.
   ``Turmoil can be very disturbing,'' she said, ``and we don't
know what may happen.''
   She said the reform paths embarked on by the East European
governments were difficult. ``It's easier to demand freedom than it
is to set a structure of freedom in place,'' she said.
   Lubbers said the Bush administration was ``not at all fearful of
the possibilities of rapprochement in Europe and of the European
healing process.''
   ``They obviously see it as a very positive adventure,'' he said.
</TEXT>
