<FIRST>r w AM-Soviet-Nicaragua     12-04 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Nicaragua,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Soviets Sending New Helicopters To Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-NATO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just days before the Soviet-American summit
meeting, a Soviet vessel left Leningrad for Nicaragua carrying four
helicopters with potential military use, Bush administration
sources said Monday.
   The reported shipment, due to arrive in Corinto, Nicaragua, on
Dec. 18, comes as the Sandinista Army is staging a substantial
buildup in northern Nicaragua not far from base camps of the Contra
rebels in southern Honduras.
   While some officials expressed concern about the potential
military impact of the MI-17 helicopters, they said the Soviets are
likely to contend the aircraft are for commercial purposes.
   Because such aircraft normally are sent to Nicaragua without
weapons mounted on them, the delivery would not appear to
contradict the reaffirmation Sunday by Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev that his country has ceased arms deliveries to Central
America.
   But the sources, who asked not to be identified, said the MI-17
has been used extensively by the Sandinista armed forces for
carrying troops and as gunships. In the past, they said, MI-17's
have been converted on arrival in Nicaragua for military use
against the Contras.
   President Bush has said he does not challenge Gorbachev's
assertions but has expressed concern about what he has descibed as
a continuing flow of Soviet bloc weaponry through Nicaragua to
leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   At his news conference in Brussels on Monday, Bush acknowldged
that he and Gorbachev have ``big differences'' on Central America.
He said he would like Gorbachev to use his influence to
``facilitate democratic change'' in the Western Hemisphere.
   The sources said the Sandinistas now have about 38 MI-17's in
their inventory. The MI-17 is an advanced version of the MI-8
helicopter and is more easily adaptable than the MI-8 for use as a
gunship.
   Since there are already many MI-17's in Nicaragua, one official
said the new shipment could not necessarily be considered a
provocation. The official said the Sandinistas already have enough
MI-17's and described the additional helicopters as unnecessary.
   He added that the delivery probably had been in the planning
stage for months and that it may have been a coincidence that the
ship carrying the helicopters left Leningrad just before the
Mediterranean summit.
   The U.S. officials, citing intelligence reports, said the
shipment left Leningrad aboard the vessel Vladimir Ilyich.
   The MI-17 delivery to Nicaragua, as U.S. officials see it,
appears to be more closely related to the internal situation in
that country than to El Salvador.
   National elections are set for Feb. 25 and the Sandinista
government is angry that the Contra rebels continue to operate not
only inside Nicaragua but also remain deployed at base camps in
Honduras.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega and four other Central
American presidents called in August for the demobilization of the
rebels by this Tuesday, but that deadline will pass with the
resistance forces still intact.
   The Contras, backed by the Bush administration, have pointed out
that the Central American presidents specified that the
demobilization must be ``voluntary'' and carried out only if the
rebels can return safely to their homeland.
   Five weeks ago, Ortega suspended a truce that had been in effect
for 19 months, accusing the rebels of engaging in terrorist
activities. The Contras, who continue to receive non-lethal U.S.
aid, said the only offensive action during the truce period had
been carried out by the Sandinista Army.
   Aggravating the situation was the collapse on Nov. 21 of
cease-fire talks in Washington between the Sandinistas and the
Contras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
