<DOCNO> AP891204-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1657EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FireDiscrimination     12-04 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire Discrimination,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minority, Female Promotions Upheld</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Monday upheld
San Francisco's agreement to hire and promote women and minorities
in the white male-dominated Fire Department.
   In a 3-0 ruling, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected
a union claim that the plan violated the rights of white men by
setting numerical goals for minority and female employment and by
requiring the promotion of 33 minority firefighters.
   The agreement, approved in a consent decree by U.S. District
Judge Marilyn Hall Patel in June 1988, ``is fundamentally fair,
adequate and reasonable,'' said the opinion by Judge David Thompson.
   The court noted the department had no blacks until 1955 and no
women until 1987, and the city's hiring and promotional tests for
firefighters had repeatedly been found discriminatory from 1970 to
1987.
   Thompson said the decree met the standards for race- and
sex-based remedies set by the Supreme Court: a ``manifest
imbalance'' between representation of groups in the Fire Department
and the population, and the fashioning of a plan that does not
unnecessarily hurt whites and males.
   The decree, which ended 18 years of lawsuits by minorities and
women, was challenged by Firefighters Union Local 798, with the
support of the Reagan administration.
   As the litigation neared a climax, a swastika was found in the
office of two minority firefighters in December 1987. Patel
pronounced the department ``out of control'' and ordered top
officials to enforce rules against racial and sexual harassment
under threat of contempt of court. Shortly afterward, Fire Chief Ed
Phipps resigned.
   The appeals court upheld Patel's order in Monday's ruling,
saying there was ``ample evidence of foot-dragging'' by the
department in enforcing its rules against harassment.
   When the decree on hiring and promotions was signed, the
department had 225 minorities and seven women on its staff of 1,100.
   The plan sets long-term goals of 40 percent minorities and 10
percent women in the department, and goals of 55 percent minority
hiring and 10 percent female hiring through 1994.
   The appeals court ordered the plan modified to eliminate the
hiring standards before 1994 if the long-term goals were met by
then.
   The plan also requires the city to prepare new, unbiased
examinations for hiring and promotion, and to promote 33 minority
firefighters to the rank of lieutenant. An additional 48 promotions
are optional, of which 12 must be minorities.
   Thompson rejected the union's argument that the plan was
discriminatory by requiring the promotion of minorities but not of
whites. No evidence was presented of past discrimination against
whites, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
