<FIRST>r a AM-Helmsley     12-04 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotel Queen Loses Bid to Overturn Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last obstacle between Leona Helmsley and
sentencing was lifted Monday when a judge refused to set aside her
tax evasion conviction.
   Mrs. Helmsley, who is portrayed in advertisements as the queen
of her luxury hotels, was convicted Aug. 30 of evading $1.2 million
in federal taxes by charging personal expenses to her business
empire.
   By denying a request to overturn the conviction and dismiss the
charges, U.S. District Judge John Walker cleared the way for her
Dec. 12 sentencing.
   The judge ruled that prosecutors did not use tainted evidence
against Mrs. Helmsley. Mrs. Helmsley's lawyers based their request
on allegations that prosecutors improperly used the testimony she
gave to grand juries in 1985.
   At the time, the state was investigating possible sales tax
evasion by jewelers, furriers and other retailers. Because Mrs.
Helmsley was granted immunity, prosecutors were legally barred from
using the testimony in the later income tax case.
   ``The court is satisfied that the government's evidence used in
the federal grand jury and at trial was derived from sources
independent of Mrs. Helmsley's immunized testimony on unrelated
matters,'' Walker said in a written decision.
   Her attorney, Gerald Feffer, said he had not seen Walker's
decision and could not comment.
   At sentencing, the 69-year-old Mrs. Helmsley could receive
punishment ranging from community service to 127 years in prison if
Walker imposes consecutive sentences on 33 tax-related counts. She
also could face more than $7 million in fines.
   Mrs. Helmsley's 80-year-old husband, Harry, heads a $5 billion
real estate and hotel empire. He was charged with his wife and the
others but was found incompetent to stand trial.
</TEXT>
