<FIRST>u i AM-East-Glance     12-04 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-Glance,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monday's East Bloc Developments at a Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Monday's East bloc developments:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150,000 demonstrators filled Wenceslas Square,
rejecting the new Communist-dominated government and demanding free
elections. The opposition called for a second general strike on
Dec. 11 if there is no new government by Sunday. Thousands of
tourists from Czechoslovakia freely visited the West for the first
time in decades after the government lifted most travel
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EAST GERMANY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   East Germans outraged by the corruption of ex-leaders tried to
storm secret police offices to make sure the evidence was
protected. Prosecutors blocked access by the ousted officials to
the evidence. Premier Hans Modrow emerged as the leading political
figure one day after the Communist Party leadership resigned. He
led a three-member delegation to the Warsaw Pact summit in Moscow.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POLAND</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Voice of America opened a bureau in Warsaw, its second in
the Soviet bloc, and launched discussions with Polish state radio
on exchanging programming. The National Bank of Poland devalued the
zloty by 9.5 percent, continuing a drive to create a convertible
currency that would encourage Western investment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ELSEWHERE:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _ The Soviet Union, Bulgaria, Hungary, East Germany and Poland
for the first time jointly condemned the 1968 Soviet-led invasion
of Czechoslovakia that crushed the ``Prague Spring'' reforms. The
Warsaw Pact nations, meeting in Moscow, said the invasion
constitituted ``interference in the internal affairs of a sovereign
Czechoslovakia.''
   _ President Bush, in Brussels, said it's too early to proclaim
an end to the Cold War, but added that Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
acceptance of sweeping reform in Eastern Europe ``absolutely
mandates new thinking'' by the West. He also endorsed a cautious
and measured approach to reunifying Germany.
   _ Bush said his weekend meeting with Gorbachev gave the two
leaders a chance to cement a personal relationship, although ``it
wasn't all sweetness and light.''
   _ The Czechoslavak journal Lidove Noviny, which is associated
with the democratic opposition, was awarded a $10,000 grant from a
group of Western press associations that have established a new
project to assist East bloc media.
</TEXT>
