<FIRST>r i AM-CentamSummit     12-04 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Centam Summit,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central America Summit to be Held in Costa Rica</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next summit meeting of five
Central American presidents will be held in Costa Rica Dec. 10-12,
sources close to President Oscar Arias said Monday.
   The meeting, which had been scheduled for Nicaragua, probably
will be in Heredia, nine miles from the capital of San Jose,
according to the sources who spoke on condition they not be
identified.
   Plans to hold the summit in Managua were canceled because
Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani refused to go to Nicaragua.
   Cristiani suspended relations with Managua last week after two
planes, allegedly smuggling arms from Nicaragua to leftist rebels
in El Salvador, were found in Salvadoran territory. One crashed and
the four crewmen perished, and the other was burned by its crew at
a landing strip because the craft was out of fuel, according to
Salvadoran officials.
   The presidents of Costa Rica, Honduras, Guatemala, Nicaragua and
El Salvador, at their meeting last August in Tela, Honduras, agreed
to demobilize the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, by Dec. 5.
Next week's meeting is supposed to review the relocation of the
Contras, thousands of whom live in camps across the border in
Honduras.
   Most of the Contras, who have been fighting the Sandinista
government for eight years, refuse to disband and be relocated
until after Nicaragua's elections, scheduled for February.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega, who had insisted that the
meeting be held in his country, relented over the weekend and
agreed to meet in Costa Rica, the sources reported.
   They said there were offers to hold the summit in Argentina, but
Arias insisted it be held in the region. Arias has said all the
presidents except Ortega agreed on Guatemala as a replacement site
for Managua.
   ``All the Central American foreign ministers are pressuring that
the summit be held in a hotel with conveniences, not only for the
presidents, but also for the press,'' said a Nicaraguan diplomat
who asked not to be identified.
   The Costa Rican location most frequently mentioned is the
Central American Insitute for Business Administration in Heredia.
   Also attending the meeting will be Joao Baena Soares,
secretary-general of the Organization of American States, and
representatives of U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar,
the Nicaraguan diplomat said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
