<FIRST>r a AM-StLouisNewspapers     12-04 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-St Louis Newspapers,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Everyone's Happy in St. Louis Newspaper Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The St. Louis Sun has grabbed more than
100,000 readers a day in its first two months of publication, but
hasn't drawn readers away from the established St. Louis
Post-Dispatch, executives of the two newspapers said Monday.
   In fact, Post-Dispatch officials sounded almost grateful to the
upstart Sun, which is the newest newspaper in the country.
   ``I do firmly believe that the Post-Dispatch is a much better
newspaper today than it was a year ago,'' Nicholas Penniman IV,
publisher of the Post-Dispatch and vice president of the Pulitzer
Publishing Co., said at an annual editors meeting.
   David Lipman, managing editor of the Post-Dispatch, said the new
competition has accelerated changes that were in the works at the
111-year-old newspaper and given it a jolt of adrenalin.
   ``The Post-Dispatch feels 10 years younger. And we're going to
continue feeling young and being useful and still be a lot of
fun,'' he said.
   The Sun, which debuted Sept. 25, has been averaging about
107,000 circulation for its first two months, while the
Post-Dispatch's circulation has remained steady at 378,000 daily
and 565,000 on Sunday.
   The Post-Dispatch's Saturday newspaper has increased its
circulation about 3 percent to 348,000 since the Sun began
appearing with an expanded Saturday paper that costs $1 compared to
25 cents for the Saturday Post-Dispatch.
   Ralph Ingersoll II, the Sun's editor-in-chief and chairman of
its parent company, Ingersoll Publications Co., said he expected
the Sun to turn a profit by the end of 1990.
   However, he said profits won't be as high as originally
projected because the newspaper is attracting more home subscribers
and fewer newsstand buyers than expected. Home subscribers pay less.
   Ingersoll brushed aside talk of a ``newspaper war'' in St. Louis.
   ``We look on it as a competition, which is something different
than a war,'' he said.
   Before the debut of the Sun, the Post-Dispatch had been without
competition since the St. Louis Globe-Democrat folded in Oct. 1986.
</TEXT>
