<FIRST>u w AM-Skinner-Drugs     12-04 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinner-Drugs,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner Sees High Drug Use In Transportation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner
predicted Monday that random drug testing will reveal an ``alarming
amount of drug usage'' among people responsible for the safety of
land, air and sea transportation.
   Rules begin going into effect in two weeks that require random
and other drug tests for millions of airline, railroad, mass
transit, bus company, boat, trucking company and pipeline employees.
   Skinner said that where court orders do not stop the testing,
companies must comply with the new rule. Several suits have been
filed by workers to stop the federally imposed program. Startup
dates for the testing vary by modes of transportation.
   The secretary said he has set up a group in his office to
monitor progress of the testing, while agencies dealing with
aviation, railroads and other modes would each oversee industries
they cover.
   ``Once they begin the testing, I think we'll see an alarming
amount of drug use and positive testing in safety-related jobs,''
said Skinner at a session with reporters.
   He said he expects the results to justify the high priority the
administration has given the program.
   Random drug tests in the military showed high drug use in the
first few months, he said. Ten percent of tested Coast Guard
personnel showed positive, but the incidence has since dropped to 2
percent because of the testing, he said.
   Skinner said the government would not be lenient with companies
that do not make an effort to begin drug-testing programs.
   ``I don't want to be unfair,'' he said, but ``the time has come
where we've got to move forward on this testing. We're not going to
sit here and tell somebody who is required by law or regulation to
conduct the test that they can just wait until they are ready.''
   Possible action against employers, including civil penalties or
withholding of federal funds, varies by transportation modes.
   Skinner said that ``with rare exception'' airlines have
submitted drug-testing plans that have been approved. The Federal
Aviation Administration extended the August deadline after several
smaller airlines failed to submit their programs.
   The secretary said he had been told by more than one mass
transit operator to expect high rates of drug usage when the
testing begins, possibly significantly higher than the 10 percent
found in the Coast Guard.
   Results should vary in different parts of the country and in
different modes of transportation, Skinner said, but added, ``I
know it's a major problem all over this country.''
   Asked what effect high drug use might have on the continuation
of transportation services, Skinner said, ``If the percentages were
40 percent, it would be devastating. If it were 5 percent, they
could probably work their way through it.''
</TEXT>
