<FIRST>r w AM-Poland-Agriculture     12-04 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Agriculture,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twenty Poles To Recieve Agricultural Training In U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty Polish agriculturalists will be trained
in the United States next year through a fellowship program
designed to educate foreign farm program administrators in American
methods, said Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter on Monday.
   Yeutter said $90,000 has been set aside through the Cochran
Middle Income Country Fellowship Program for Polish participants.
   ```We look forward not only to increasing trade opportunities
for U.S. commodities in Poland through this program, but also to
increasing goodwill between the people of both countries,'' said
Yeutter, as he returned from a four-day economic mission in Poland.
   Thirty-nine participants from Poland received agriculture and
agribusiness training in the United States last April. It was the
largest group among the 16 countries that participated this year.
   The program, named for Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., is
administered through the Agriculture Department's office of
international cooperation and development.
   Yeutter said sales of breeding stock and animals, grains, seeds
and high-value products have resulted from past fellowships.
</TEXT>
