<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Unrest     12-04 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Unrest,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Leaders Escape Trial for Security Reasons</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Uprising Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security considerations convinced the
government not to investigate and try two prominent Palestinians
identified as uprising leaders by an Israeli legislator and court
documents, officials said Monday.
   Tzahi Hanegbi, the legislator, alleged in a Supreme Court appeal
that philosophy professor Sari Nusseibeh and the head of the Arab
Journalists Association, Radwan Abu Ayyash, handled uprising funds
and wrote leaflets urging escalation of the 2-year-old rebellion.
   Hanegbi, of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's conservative Likud
bloc, quoted documents submitted to a military court at Lod in May
that called Nusseibeh a paymaster of the uprising in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, responsible for distributing PLO funds
and publishing uprising literature.
   He claimed Abu Ayyash represented Fatah, the guerrilla group of
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinie Liberation Organization chief, in the
underground Unified National Leadership of the Uprising and was
responsible for several leaflets, army radio reported.
   Neither has been charged and Hanegbi demanded both men be tried,
the national news agency Itim reported.
   Nili Arad of the state attorney's office attributed the decision
not to investigate Nusseibeh and Abu Ayyash to ``professional
considerations,'' Itim and the radio reported.
   She said Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, Police Minister Chaim
Bar-Lev and other officials bore those considerations in mind,
according to the reports.
   Army radio said the security reasons remained secret but might
be revealed if the court requested it.
   Abu Ayyash said in a telephone interview: ``I would love to know
and understand what these considerations are, but I'm not involved
directly in these things, so I don't see I should worry.''
   He said Hanegbi's appeal contained ``false and fake
allegations,'' and the journalist declared: ``I think that, if the
legal system in Israel possesses information on security
violations, they won't hesitate to ask us for interrogation. I have
been interrogated many times, whenever they suspect something
against security.''
   Nusseibeh characterized Hanegbi's allegations as ``vague and
circumstantial.'' He denied committing offenses or having knowledge
of what the Israeli considerations were.
   ``Regarding secret security reasons, one is always at a loss
concerning secret files of prosecutors,'' he said. ``One can never
really tell what they have or do not have.
   ``I'm glad ... of not being investigated or put on trial. On the
other hand, I'm also quite prepared to face trial and to put
forward my case and to defend myself using all the legal methods at
my disposal.''
   Some Arab observers have speculated Israel saw the two as
possible candidates in its plan for Palestinians in the territories
to elect delegates to negotiate interim autonomy, and therefore was
hesistant to investigate them.
   Both the West Bank and Gaza were paralyzed Monday by the second
day of a general strike called because of an Israeli army attack on
a Palestinian gang in the West Bank city of Nablus.
   On Friday, Israeli soldiers killed four members of a group
calling itself the Black Panthers. Israel claims the group has
killed 16 Palestinians as alleged informers.
   The number of alleged collaborators slain by other Palestinians
since the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987, rose to 155 on Monday with
the death of Mabrouka al-Akra in a Gaza Strip hospital. Masked
assailants stabbed the 55-year-old woman to death, according to
Arab reports.
   In Gaza City, at least nine Palestinians were reported shot and
wounded by Israeli troops in the Sheik Radwan neighborhood,
hospital officials said.
   An Arab journalist said protests began after residents learned
Jamal Abdul Atti, 25, committed suicide in a Gaza prison Monday. He
was arrested Oct. 10 on suspicion of trying to run over an Israeli
soldier and a civilian.
   At Mukassed Hospital in Arab east Jerusalem, 17-year-old Hussam
Abu Zant died of a gunshot wound to the eye suffered in a clash
with soldiers Nov. 7 in Nablus, doctors reported.
   His death brought to 625 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israelis in the uprising. Forty-three Israelis have died.
</TEXT>
