<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Dubcek     12-04 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Dubcek,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dubcek: `You Cannot Suppress an Idea'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, ousted in disgrace as
Czechoslovakia's Communist Party leader after the Soviet-led
invasion in 1968, praised his countrymen's struggle for democracy
and said, ``You cannot suppress an idea.''
   Independent Television News broadcast on Monday an interview
with Dubcek in Bratislava. The 67-year-old leader of the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms said, ``An idea is going to survive within
people's conscience.''
   He spoke of the 17 years he lived in forced obscurity after
being removed from office in 1969 and stripped of party membership
in 1970.
   ``They wanted to totally isolate me. I was followed
everywhere,'' he said. ``I had to keep my circle of friends small
to protect them. Maybe they thought I couldn't take it
psychologically but I could. It's been a hard life but we are still
here.''
   Dubcek was relegated to work as a minor forestry official in the
Slovak capital of Bratislava and barred from travel. The
restrictions were relaxed after Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev visited Czechoslovakia in April 1987.
   Reforms instituted by Gorbachev in the Soviet Union have surged
like a tidal wave through the East bloc and on Nov. 24
Czechoslovakia's hard-line Communist government resigned under
public pressure. Tens of thousands of people cheered Dubcek in
Prague's Wenceslas Square on his triumphant return to the capital.
   ``To speak in Prague gave me a deep sense of satisfaction,'' he
said Monday. ``Twenty years ago their parents cheered me. Now these
children are doing the same and supporting the same ideas.''
   He said many of the democratic reforms being demanded now were
part of his 1968 plans.
   ``There was no internal power willing to stop the `Prague
Spring,' we were suppressed by external force,'' he said, speaking
through an interpreter. ``The basic idea is the same now. You
cannot suppress an idea. An idea is going to survive within
people's conscience.''
   Thousands of Czechoslovaks demonstrated Monday, protesting the
composition of the new Communist-dominated government.
   Dubcek was asked if he might become president and he said, ``For
the presidency it's up to the people to decide.''
   Dubcek received virtually complete vindication Monday when a
Warsaw Pact summit meeting in Moscow condemned the 1968 invasion as
``interference in the internal affairs of a sovereign''
Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
