<FIRST>r i AM-UN-PLO     12-04 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-PLO,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Efforts to Upgrade its U.N. Status Collapse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO's campaign to win recognition in
the General Assembly as the provisional government of Palestine
broke down Monday and negotiations shifted to finding a face-saving
retreat, diplomats said.
   They attributed the failure to upgrade the PLO to
observer-nation status in the General Assembly to shallow support,
divisions within the Palestine Liberation Organization and a U.S.
threat to stop contributing to the United Nations.
   A vote on the resolution was postponed until Wednesday.
   ``The climate is not right now,'' said a senior Palestinian
diplomat, speaking privately. He said the PLO might try to revive
the idea next year.
   The PLO is recognized by the United Nations as an observer
organization. It was seeking to gain recognition as a non-voting
observer state, such as North and South Korea, Switzerland, San
Marino, Monaco and the Vatican.
   Washington said it would cut off all U.S. funds for the United
Nations if the PLO's status was upgraded. The United States is
assessed $216 million annually, one-fourth of the U.N. budget.
   One Western diplomat, speaking on the condition he not be
identified, said a rift had developed between PLO chairman Yasser
Arafat, at the organization's headquarters in Tunisia, and Farouk
Khaddoumi, the PLO foreign secretary who heads the group's U.N.
delegation.
   Khaddoumi was ``the guiding force'' behind the General Assembly
resolution to upgrade the PLO's status, while Arafat believed the
effort was counterproductive and last week ordered a halt, the
diplomat said.
   European and U.S. diplomats worked with Arab and non-aligned
movement officials through the weekend to avoid a showdown.
   Negotiations on a discrete way for the PLO and Arab group to
postpone consideration of the resolution were not complete when the
time arrived Monday afternoon for a vote and formal action was
deferred until Wednesday.
   The diplomatic sources said the resolution will be suspended
Wednesday.
   As a member of the 102-member non-aligned movement, the PLO
supposedly had enough support to prevail on a simple majority vote
in the 159-member General Assembly.
   But Western diplomats said the vote could have been very close
because many non-aligned Nations did not feel the issue was worth
losing U.S. funds.
   Egypt and Morocco in the Arab group did not support the
resolution and the Soviet Union and its allies also were opposed.
   The resolution draft states the PLO ``has the powers and
responsibilities of the Provisional Government of the State of
Palestine'' and ``shall be construed, within the United Nations, as
the State of Palestine.''
   Last year, the PLO declared the existence of a state of
Palestine without specifying exact borders in the Israeli-occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip and has said more than 80 nations formally
recognized the state.
   The United States and many Western governments have not
recognized the move, saying the declared state lacks the basic
attributes of a state, such as a functioning government and
defensible boundaries.
</TEXT>
