<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 2041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Pastora     12-04 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Pastora,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commander Zero Claims Opposition Did Not Want Him Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eden Pastora, a former Sandinista hero
who switched sides and fought with the Contras, said Monday that
opposition groups in Nicaragua did not want him to return from
exile.
   Pastora, also know as Commander Zero, is a former Sandinista
vice minister of defense who fought with the Contras from 1983-86
and then retired to private life. He returned Sunday to support the
Social Christian Party.
   Repeating what he said at a rally immediately after his arrival,
Pastora called the Social Christians an alternative to the ruling
Sandinista National Liberation Front and the U.S.-backed National
Opposition Union, known as UNO, in the Feb. 25 national elections.
   The Social Christian Party and its presidential candidate Erick
Ramirez persuaded Pastora to return to Nicaragua and support them.
Few believe Pastora can add many more followers to the Social
Christians.
   The controversy surrounding Commander Zero already has attracted
the kind of news media attention the Social Christians, a minority
party, had sought unsuccessfully. About 25 journalists crowded a
small conference room Monday morning at party headquarters, but
ignored Ramirez, who sat next to Pastora.
   Many questions revolved around Pastora's past.
   Pastora said that he had spoken with some UNO members. ``They
left me with the impression that they did not want me to return to
Nicaragua.''
   ``Sectors of the CIA in alliance with the Contras'' were
responsible for the bombing at his southern Nicaragua jungle
hideout in 1984, where four journalists were killed, he said.
Pastora alleged that the attempt was made ``because I never wanted
to accept anti-popular postures'' adopted by the Contras. He did
not elaborate.
   Pastora said he intends to settle in Nicaragua if he can
continue the fishing business he runs in neighboring Costa Rica.
   Commander Zero, as he is still known, gained world attention
Aug. 20, 1978, when he led 20 Sandinista rebels in a takeover of
the National Palace.
   The rebels held dozens of legislators hostage and succeeded in
freeing from prison 50 Sandinista leaders, among them Daniel Ortega
and Tomas Borge, who are now president and interior minister.
   Eleven months later, the Sandinista came to power in a popular
revolt that forced President Anastasio Somoza to flee.
   After the Sandinista victory in 1979, Pastora became vice
minister of defense and of interior but grew disillusioned with the
Sandinistas and left the country in 1981. It is said he was
embittered when he was denied the post of defense minister, which
went to and is still held by Ortega's brother, Humberto.
   In 1983 Pastora joined the Contras, fighting in the southern
front, but his outspoken criticism and independence soon led him
into strong differences with the Contras. In 1986 he quit fighting
and left for Costa Rica.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
