<FIRST>r a AM-VaGOP-Abortion     12-04 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Va GOP-Abortion,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Committee Refuses to Tackle Abortion Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginia's Republican Party emerged from a
weekend meeting with no clearcut policy on abortion, an issue many
GOP members believe cost them the election for governor.
   The Republican State Central Committee refused Sunday to vote on
a resolution stating that there is room for abortion supporters as
well as opponents in the GOP.
   ``This issue has got to come out,'' Don Moseley, a district GOP
chairman, said after the committee voted 40-27 to table his
resolution. ``It has to be settled.''
   Moseley said J. Marshall Coleman, the Republican candidate for
governor, lost the Nov. 7 election to Democrat L. Douglas Wilder
because of the abortion issue.
   Wilder, who will become the nation's first elected black
governor if his narrow election victory withstands a recount,
campaigned in favor of abortion rights. Coleman opposes abortion
except to save the life of the mother.
   Moseley's resolution said state Republicans ``must support any
candidate nominated by the party, regardless of that candidate's
position on the issue of abortion.''
   Hugh Mulligan, the state party's first vice chairman, said the
party already allows differing views on the issues.
   He said debating the resolution would provide ``a catalyst for
the press,'' which he said has tried to portray the party as
divided on the abortion issue.
   Moseley said the party's inaction at its three-day meeting in
Roanoke leaves the impression that the GOP remains captive to
abortion opponents. He said he'd resubmit his resolution when the
committee meets in Richmond Feb. 24.
</TEXT>
