<FIRST>r a AM-MontoyaTrial     12-04 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Montoya Trial,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Goes on Trial; Refuses To Talk To Reporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Sen. Joseph Montoya went on
trial Monday on federal corruption charges that could result in a
220-year prison sentence and more than $3 million in fines.
   Montoya, chairman of the Senate's Business and Professions
Committee, refused to answer reporters' questions as he entered the
courthouse accompanied by his wife, Pilar, and two of his daughters.
   As U.S. District Court Judge Milton Schwartz questioned
potential jurors, Montoya sat between his two lawyers at the
defense table and occasionally made notes on a pad.
   Montoya, 50, a Democrat from the Los Angeles suburb of El Monte,
has pleaded innocent to a dozen felony counts that accuse him of
bribery, extortion, racketeering and money laundering.
   He faces a maximum penalty of more than $3 million in fines and
220 years in prison if convicted on all counts.
   He is the first person to be tried as a result of the FBI's
4-year-old investigation of alleged corruption at the state
Capitol. He is accused of obtaining or attempting to obtain money
in exchange for votes.
   Among other things, the charges include allegations that Montoya
accepted a $3,000 ``honorarium'' from an undercover agent in
exchange for help in getting a special-interest bill through the
Senate.
   The FBI probe came to light after about 30 federal agents raided
the Capitol on the night of Aug. 24-25, 1988 and searched the
offices of Montoya, three other lawmakers and their aides.
   In their investigation, FBI agents set up dummy companies and
claimed they were seeking legislation to help them set up a shrimp
importing operation in Northern California.
   Charges also have been filed against an Assembly aide, a former
Montoya aide, a former Yolo County sheriff and a former
undersheriff. The aide and the former undersheriff have agreed to
cooperate with prosecutors.
   U.S. Attorney David Levi, who is heading a three-member team
that is prosecuting the case, filed a list of 63 potential
prosecution witnesses, including Gene Upshaw, head of the National
Football League Players' Association; actor Ed Asner; and several
Capitol lobbyists.
   According to a prosecutors' memorandum, in May 1985 Montoya
asked Asner, then president of the Screen Actors Guild, for a
financial contribution in exchange for his support of guild
legislative aims.
   The memorandum also said that Montoya demanded money from the
NFL Players Association in exchange for siding with the association
on legislation dealing with the relationship between professional
athletes and their agents.
</TEXT>
