<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Philippines 1stLd-Writethru a0744 12-04 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0744,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Calls Aquino</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS graf 5: ``Despite claims,'' with three grafs to update
with details on situation in Manila, material from a0743</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush called Philippines President
Corazon Aquino Monday night to express concern for the lives of
Americans in hotels occupied by rebel soldiers and to pay tribute
to her courage in seeking to quell the rebellion, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   Bush had just completed a 9-hour journey from Brussels, where he
briefed the NATO allies on his weekend summit with Mikhail
Gorbachev, when he called the Philippine leader.
   ``The president tried to call Mrs. Aquino earlier in the day and
was unable to get through. So when we got home tonight ... he went
immediately up to the residence and re-placed the call,'' Fitzwater
said.
   The rebellion broke out Friday before dawn Philippine time, just
before Bush embarked on his journey to Malta.
   Vice President Dan Quayle presided over an all-night meeting of
the National Security Council in the White House, and Bush later
approved overflights by U.S. fighter jets based in the Philippines
to keep rebel aircraft on the ground.
   Despite claims by the Aquino government that it had quashed the
rebellion, fighting continued in Manila for a fifth day Tuesday,
with 2,000 foreign tourists and business people trapped in the
embattled Makati financial district. Some 215 Americans were holed
up at three hotels in the district, according to the U.S. embassy.
   The Aquino government said Tuesday it had arranged bus
transportation to evacuate the foreigners to the airport, and a
rebel spokesman telephoned news agencies to say the foreigners
would be released.
   At least 70 people have been killed and more than 500 wounded
since mutineers seized several military installations and bombed
the presidential palace Friday.
   Fitzwater quoted Bush as telling Aquino: ```I understand some
Americans are in the hotels. ... Can we get those people out? I'm
very concerned about their lives and their safety.'''
   ``She assured him they were doing everything possible to protect
American lives,'' Fitzwater said. ``Then the president ended the
conversation by saying, `I appreciate your concern for the
civilians. We're proud of you for standing up with great courage.
We want to see you succeed.'''
   Asked if Bush was considering sending in U.S. troops to rescue
the Americans, Fitzwater said, ``We don't think that will be
necessary.''
   He said Bush called Aquino because ``he just wanted to register
his concern for the lives of Americans who were trapped in these
hotels. ... He just wanted to ask that she make every attempt to
protect their lives.''
   National security adviser Brent Scowcroft, who had accompanied
Bush on Air Force One on the journey back from Europe, was with the
president as he made the call from his personal quarters.
</TEXT>
