<FIRST>r a AM-Duke-Senate 1stLd-Writethru a0711 12-04 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Duke-Senate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0711,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Klan Leader Planning to Run for U.S. Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Johnson, who ..., with 2 grafs comment from
Johnston.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Rep. David Duke, the former Ku Klux
Klan leader who won election to the Louisiana House earlier this
year, announced plans Monday to challenge Sen. J. Bennett Johnston,
D-La.
   ``I think it's time we had a conservative Republican in the U.S.
Senate to represent the true issues and wishes of the people of
Louisiana,'' he said.
   However, Duke, 39, refused to rule out the possibility that he
might challenge U.S. Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., instead.
   Duke gave out copies of a letter and petitions calling for
President Bush and Republican National Committee Chairman Lee
Atwater to support him against Johnston. Atwater repudiated Duke in
the state legislative race, and Bush endorsed his opponent, fellow
Republican John Treen.
   The letter and petition are being sent to every GOP household in
the state, Duke said.
   Johnston, who has held the seat 18 years, said Duke's entry into
the race will make it more interesting.
   ``Oh, it ups the ante. There will be some national attention
here, and it will make it more fun also,'' Johnston said during a
visit to Shreveport on Monday. The election will be Oct. 6, 1990.
   Duke said he thought his past as imperial wizard of the Knights
of the Ku Klux Klan would help his candidacy.
   ``I think it says to a lot of people that I will stand up for my
principals and ideals. ... I won't compromise my ideals,'' he said.
   Duke said he has raised $60,000 in cash and $224,000 in pledges
for the Senate campaign.
   He said his platform would be the same as it was in his campaign
for the state House, when he called for eliminating affirmative
action and busing to achieve school desegregation, among other
things.
   Duke said his official announcement probably would be made in
January.
