<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0650 12-04 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Kosovo Party Leader Says His Trial is Human Rights Violation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 11 grafs at end on developments in Slovenia-Serbia confrontation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TITOVA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main defendant in
Yugoslavia's largest political trial in decades accused Serbia's
leadership Monday of staging the trial as part of its policy of
repressing ethnic Albanians.
   Azem Vlasi, a former Communist Party chief in Kosovo, told the
court on the first day of his defense that ``the trial represents
the worst possible violation of ... human rights.''
   Vlasi and 14 other ethnic Albanians are accused of engaging in
counterrevolutionary activities and of inciting unrest last winter
in which at least 25 people died.
   At the time, ethnic Albanians, who make up almost 90 percent of
the province's 1.9 million people, were angered by constitutional
amendments that gave Serbia greater control over the affairs of the
province.
   Kosovo is a part of Serbia, the nation's largest republic, and
had previously enjoyed a measure of autonomy.
   Vlasi denied the charge that he was responsible for the deaths,
which occurred during clashes between protesters and security
forces.
   He said his trial was organized by Slobodan Milosevic, the
republic's leader, and Rahman Morina, Kosovo's current party chief.
   District public prosecutor Spasoje Zamfirovic demanded several
times that Vlasi be prevented from giving what he said was a
political speech, but judge Ismet Emra overruled the objections.
   Vlasi denied he had visited a nearby mine, where workers staged
an eight-day sit-in in February to ``incite the strikers,'' as
claimed in the indictment.
   ``I went there exclusively for humane reasons,'' he said, adding
that he had reported his activities to Milosevic and to Morina.
   ``A political trial has been staged on behalf of a policy which
advocated repression in Kosovo so that (the province) may be ruled
through a state of emergency instead of democratic methods,'' Vlasi
said.
   Milosevic led the drive earlier this year for constitutional
amendments he said were necessary to protect Kosovo's Slav minority
from harassment by ethnic Albanians.
   Vlasi, 42, faces the death sentence if found guilty.
   He is being held in the Titova Mitrovica prison during the
trial, which began Oct. 30.
   Vlasi said prison conditions were ``brutal'' but that he would
not be broken. ``I can disappear physically but I will not
submit,'' he said.
   The trial continues Tuesday and Vlasi's defense presentation is
expected to last five days.
   The federal leadership meanwhile said Monday that a clash
between Slovenia and Serbia, two of its constituent republics,
seriously threatens Yugoslav unity.
   The statement from the nation's eight-member state presidency
was carried by the official Tanjug news agency.
   Serbia cut all political and business contacts with Slovenia
last Wednesday after authorities there banned a rally by Serbs.
   The presidency said without elaborating it will take all steps
necessary to solve the worst political crisis in Communist
Yugoslavia's 46 years of existence.
   It said the federation's political situation ``has dangerously
deteriorated'' because of the clash, ``which seriously threatens
Yugoslavia's integrity.''
   The Yugoslav federation consists of six republics and two
autonomous provinces, encompassing varied ethnic groups and
religions. The latest row brought to a head a long series of bitter
disputes between Slovenia and Serbia.
   Slovenia's liberal-oriented leadership advocates regional
autonomy and has legalized opposition parties that are to contest
the first-ever free multiparty elections in post-World War II
Yugoslavia, scheduled for next March.
   Serbia's leadership favors a centralized federation and opposes
Western-style political pluralism.
   Several Serbian firms said Monday they are severing all economic
ties with Slovenian firms and closing down branch offices there.
   Economists say cutting business ties will backfire, since Serbia
is economically much weaker than Slovenia.
   Yugoslavia's political, economic and social problems have
mushroomed since the death in 1980 of President Josip Broz Tito,
who founded the modern Yugoslav federation in 1943.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
