<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Military     12-04 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Military,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Curfew Eased, Arraignment of U.S. Woman Postponed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces eased a
dusk-to-dawn curfew Monday, claiming it had 90 percent of El
Salvador under control after a three-week rebel offensive.
   San Salvador, hit hard for the first time in the 10-year-old
civil war, began enjoying a sustained calm over the weekend. The
armed forces press office said the curfew now will be from 11 p.m.
to 6 a.m. instead of 6 p.m to 6 a.m.
   Although an armed forces spokesman said reports of only ``small,
routine'' combat emerged Monday, an ABC news crew said they saw
heavy fighting 25 miles south of the capital in Zacatecoluca.
   A U.S. Embassy source said the guerrillas used two more recently
acquired anti-aircraft missiles. The source, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said both missed their targets, O-2 observation
planes.
   The guerrillas used the weapon for the first time last week,
firing two missiles at A-37 jet fighters but missing their mark.
   El Salvador suspended relations with Nicaragua Nov. 26, saying
planes from Nicaragua flew in the missiles.
   Meanwhile, the arraignment of a Connecticut woman accused of
hiding rebel arms was postponed.
   Guillermo Romero Hernandez, the judge of the military tribunal
where Jennifer Jean Casolo was to appear, said he expected strict
new anti-terrorist measures would be applied retroactively,
affecting her case.
   The measures have not yet been signed into law by rightist
President Alfredo Cristiani.
   Ms. Casolo, 28, a native of Thomaston, Conn., and a former
resident of Seattle, worked for an ecumenical group that acted as
liaison for visiting church groups and congressional aides.
   Authorities say they unearthed a huge munitions cache in her
yard Nov. 26, including more than 20,000 rounds of ammunition for
AK-47 assault rifles.
   Former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark, here to advise Ms.
Casolo, said she does not want to leave, even it if means spending
time in prison.
   He said she will plead innocent when charges are filed.
   The judge said her arraignment was postponed because of
confusion about jurisdiction and procedure.
   Scott Wright, a Roman Catholic lay missionary from San Antonio,
Texas, was freed Monday after spending the weekend in a 10-by-16
foot cell with 15 other people.
   Wright, a slender, soft-spoken Nebraska native, was picked up
Thursday night in a parish house in a San Salvador slum along with
a Spanish priest and three Salvadoran lay workers.
   He said he spent most of the first night and part of the first
day blindfolded and handcuffed, standing against a wall.
   Wright, who has spent three years working among the poor and
those displaced by the war, said police administered a paraffin
test to see if he had fired a gun and accused him of being involved
with the leftist Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, or FMLN.
   He was freed on the condition he leave El Salvador; no charges
were filed.
   Wright said he leaves reluctantly.
   ``Through the years, I've come to know the Salvadoran people,
particularly the poor, and the Salvadoran Church quite well,'' he
said. ``I know what they are living through, what they are
suffering.''
   The FMLN launched an urban offensive Nov. 11 that paralyzed the
capital for more than a week and led to imposition of the curfew.
   The Cristiani government also imposed a state of siege that
suspends many constitutional guarantees, including freedom of the
press and the right of assembly.
   In another development, a summit of Cristiani and four other
Central American presidents was scheduled for Dec. 10-12 in Costa
Rica, sources close to President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica said
Monday. The meeting is to deal with relocation of Nicaraguan rebels
from camps in Honduras.
</TEXT>
