<FIRST>r i AM-GermanFugitive     12-04 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-German Fugitive,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Fugitive East German Trade Official May be in West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive East German trade official
wanted in his country for suspected illegal currency and weapons
deals might be in West Germany, government spokesman Dieter Vogel
said Monday.
   But he said East Germany has not sent a request for the
apprehension of Alexander Schalck-Golodkowski and even if it did it
was uncertain if he could be sent back.
   The East German government said Sunday that Schalck-Golodkowski,
a state secretary in the foreign trade ministry, fled the country
after an investigation was ordered into a secret operation to ship
weapons to the Middle East, Africa and South America.
   It said a warrant was issued Sunday for his arrest and the
government was enlisting its embassies in an international search
for him.
   Vogel said Schalck-Golodkowski and other East German finance
officials were in Bonn last Wednesday holding talks with West
German authorities.
   ``We don't know where he is now,'' Vogel told The Associated
Press.
   He was asked if Schalck-Golodkowski might still be in West
Germany and he said, ``That's something we can't exclude. But we
are not looking for him.''
   Vogel and Juergen Schmid, a Justice Ministry spokesman, said
there were no indications Schalck-Golodkowski has committed any
illegal acts in West Germany.
   Vogel noted there is no extradition treaty between the two
Germanys and said he did not know what could be done if East
Germany asked that the suspect be seized and returned.
   Wolfgang Vogel, East Germany's most prominent lawyer, said
Schalck-Golodkowski had asked that he represent him. He said
Schalck-Golodkowski was ``at an unknown location'' outside East
Germany.
   East Germany's state news agency ADN said Schalck-Golodkowski
had returned to East Berlin after the meeting last week in Bonn and
disappeared during the weekend.
   On Saturday investigators found a secret warehouse in Kavelstorf
that contained weapons to be sold abroad, according to ADN.
   It said foreign exchange proceeds from the sales were paid into
the Foreign Trade Bank of East Germany addressed to
Schalck-Golodkowski.
</TEXT>
