<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 2120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Purdon     12-04 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Purdon,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eric Purdon, Who Helped Desegregate Navy, Dead At 76</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARWOOD, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Navy Cmdr. Eric S. Purdon, who
commanded one of the ships that helped integrate blacks into the
Navy's regular ranks, has died of prostate cancer at age 76.
   Purdon died at his home near Annapolis on Saturday.
   Blacks were usually restricted to being mess attendants before
the experiments in desegregation during World War II on ships such
as Purdon's submarine chaser, the PC1264, said Purdon's wife, Mary.
   The PC1264 was commissioned to demonstrate whether blacks could
be capable seamen.
   One of the crewmen on the ship was Samuel Lee Gravely Jr., who
became the first American black admiral.
   After World War II, Purdon was an intelligence analyst for
Central Intelligence Group, the forerunner of the Central
Intelligence Agency, until 1948, when he was recalled to active
duty in the Navy.
   After retiring in 1963, he was a spokesman for the Commerce
Department and the Office for Economic Opportunity and a special
aide to the director of the Job Corps.
   His book, ``Black Company, The Story of Subchaser 1264,''
detailing the mission, was published in 1972.
   He was born in the Philippines, and educated in England and
Ireland. He was a graduate of Trinty College in Hartford, Conn.,
and earned a master's degree from Boston Univeristy.
   He returned to the Philippines, working as a night manager on a
sugar plantation before joining an expedition to Mongolia to
collect stories and legends about Ghenghis Khan and the Mongols of
the 13th century. The material provided background for his first
book, ``The Valley of the Larks.''
   During World War II, he commanded two ships in the Atlantic and
the Caribbean, including the subchaser.
   Purdon also was co-author of ``Battle Report: The Middle
Phase,'' an account of naval operations in the Pacific during the
war. He also wrote articles and short stories.
   Survivors include his wife; two sons, a daughter and one
grandson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
