<FIRST>u i AM-India-Carbide 1stLd-Writethru a0612 12-04 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Carbide, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0612,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Tribunal Planned on Chemical Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 3, Sunday was ... to make gas isocyanate, sted isocynate.
Picks up graf 4, At least ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental coalition plans
an international tribunal on the Union Carbide Corp. chemical leak
in Bhopal, India, that killed more than 3,500 people, the
organizers said Monday.
   The tribunal, which will have no binding powers, will be held
next fall by the International Coalition for Justice in Bhopal, a
group of concerned citizens and environmentalists in Western
Europe, the United States and India, said spokeswoman Ruth Waterman.
   Sunday was the fifth anniversary of the world's worst industrial
accident, in which thousands of people were killed when methyl
isocyanate gas leaked from a Union Carbide pesticide plant in
Bhopal, a central Indian city about 360 miles south of New Delhi.
   At least 3,598 people have died from effects of the gas, and
relief workers say victims continue to die at a rate of at least
one a day. Most of the 20,000 survivors suffer from eye and lung
ailments and are unable to work.
   Ms. Waterman said the major purpose of the tribunal will be to
devise an international framework to protect victims of such
catastrophes.
   ``We want to present an outline of international legislation on
fixing liability in such disasters,'' she said.
   Union Carbide gave $470 million to the Indian government in
April in final compensation for the accident, which it claimed was
the result of sabotage by a disgruntled employee.
   ``It's a ridiculous amount,'' Ms. Waterman said at a
presentation of the environmental coalition's plans for the
tribunal.
   The Indian government originally had sued the U.S.-based
multinational company for $3 billion, alleging negligence.
   The tribunal is to convene in October and take testimony from
victims in Bhopal. The proceedings are to end in London in
December, Ms. Waterman said.
   She said the composition of the tribunal had not been decided.
</TEXT>
