<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF-EastGermany-Planes     12-04 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF-East Germany-Planes,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leadership's Jetliner Fleet to be Converted to Passenger Use</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen Soviet-built jetliners once reserved
for use by top East German Communist officials will be put into
passenger service, the state news agency ADN said Monday.
   Klaus Henkes, general director of the national airline
Interflug, told ADN about half the planes were ready for immediate
use on charter flights and the rest would be converted for
passenger use.
   The jetliners will remain based at army airfields because
civilian East German airports currently do not have enough hangar
space and maintenance capacity, ADN quoted Henkes as saying.
   Use of the previously official fleet of planes will allow
Interflug to sell off noisy, fuel-guzzling older Soviet models and
expand capacity to meet passenger demand in East Germany.
   Henkes said experts estimate the number of East Germans flying
annually will double to 6 million by the year 2000.
   The fleet reserved for East German statesmen included
Soviet-built Tu-134, Tu-154 and Il-62 models, ADN said.
</TEXT>
