<FIRST>u a AM-Comaneci-Florida     12-04 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comaneci-Florida,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nadia Comaneci Arrives in Florida</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian gymnast Nadia Comaneci, who fled her
Communist homeland for freedom in the West, arrived here Monday
night and said she would be settling in south Florida.
   Comaneci, 28, escaped from Romania on Tuesday, reportedly
enduring a muddy, 6-hour nighttime trek through rough terrain
before reaching the Hungarian border.
   ``I came here a few years ago and I liked it,'' Comaneci told
the Associated Press after arriving on Pan Am Flight 2077 on the
arm of Constantin Panit of Hallandale, a fellow Romanian exile who
helped her defect.
   Representatives from the State Department greeted them at Miami
International Airport and escorted them to a car waiting to take
them to an undisclosed hotel in Miami.
   The State Department officials told Comaneci that Panit's house
was surrounded by reporters and that Panit's wife, Maria, was upset
by the barrage of news media, before taking them to an undisclosed
hotel in Miami.
   Panit said the two were friends from Romania, but did not
elaborate on their relationship.
   Officials of the U.S. Gymnastics Federation had flown to New
York in hopes of contacting Comaneci and setting up a meeting
between the former Olympic champion and her former coach Bela
Karolyi, who now lives in Houston.
   Comaneci said she would not be involved with the U.S Gymnastics
Federation. She also told the Associated Press she would not be
working with her former coach Bela Karolyi. ``I have no business
with my former coach,'' she said.
   Some news reports said her destination was Indianapolis, Houston
or Orlando, Fla. But Comaneci said had no immediate plans to visit
Disney World and just wanted to relax for a while.
   Comaneci, wearing a grey cashmere sweater, blue jeans and
high-top tennis shoes, was unwilling to discuss anything about her
homeland. ``I don't know what is happening there,'' she said.
   Comaneci had arrived Friday in New York City after fleeing
Romania through Hungary and Austria, and held a brief news
conference but since has kept out of public sight.
</TEXT>
