<DOCNO> AP891204-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 2156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     12-04 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Up Against It,' A New Musical, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There isn't a messier musical in town than ``Up
Against It,'' an apt title for this chaotic song and dance
adaptation of an unproduced screenplay originally written by Joe
Orton for the Beatles.
   The musical, which opened Monday at the New York Shakespeare
Festival Public Theater, defeats a lot of people _ particularly a
slew of talented performers such as Alison Fraser, Philip Casnoff
and Toni Dibuono, director Kenneth Elliott and Orton himself.
   Only hints of Orton's wicked humor show through in this
flat-footed and tuneless version of his story adapted for the stage
by Tom Ross with music and lyrics by rock star Todd Rundgren.
   Orton, the iconoclastic English playwright who was murdered by
his lover in 1967, apparently fashioned a satiric tale about the
adventures of two British scamps and a subsequent war between the
sexes. In the musical, the battle takes place after a group of
radical men have assassinated the female prime minister. She is
replaced by another, even tougher woman, played with relentless
assurance by the booming Dibuono.
   Ross' scattershot book takes on religion, the rich, right-wing
politicians, sexual stereotyping, the military and all points in
between.
   The low point of the musical occurs when the men dress up as
women to infiltrate a political rally held by the prime minister.
The number is called _ what else _ ``Life Is a Drag'' and it is as
hard to watch as it is to listen to.
   Most of Rundgren's score is a disappointment. Except for a fine
ballad entitled ``Parallel Lines,'' it is remarkably conventional,
blandly at odds with the outrageousness of the story being told on
stage.
   Elliott has directed the show at a furious pace, and Jennifer
Muller's choreography is equally athletic. Nothing stops for very
long, although the musical numbers have a way of numbing the story
line rather than advancing the plot.
   What Orton and the Beatles would have done with ``Up Against
It'' is a tantalizing question. There are hints of such Beatle
movies as ``A Hard Day's Night'' and ``Help!'' in some of the
musical's more frantic posturings. But you would be better off to
rent videos of those classics than sit through ``Up Against It.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891204-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 2235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites SUB a0670 12-04 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites, SUB, a0670,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS the NEW UNDERWOOD, S.D.-dated item to DELETE reference
to the 13th always falling on Friday in months beginning on Monday, and
to Christmas always falling on Monday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW UNDERWOOD, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rancher Gabriel Raba figures the
present calendar switches around too much on the number of days in
a month, so he's drawn up a new plan where there'd be 28 days each
month _ all 13 of them.
   ``I haven't had hardly anybody that didn't agree with me'' said
Raba, 78. ``But I might not live long enough to see the change.''
   His calendar would be easy to understand and remember, Raba
says. Thirteen 28-day months equals 364 days. Making up for the
365th day is simple. Just create a 48-hour New Year's Day.
   Leap Year every four years also would have an extra 48-hour day,
wiping out the current Feb. 29.
   The current calendar, adopted in 1582, has 12 months with either
28, 29, 30 or 31 days.
   The Raba calendar would mean fixed-date holidays would always be
on the same day of the week. Every month would start on Monday,
which is the first day of Raba's weeks.
   The current names of months and days would remain, but the 13th
month would need a name.
   Raba said he has suggested the calendar to President Bush,
former Gov. Bill Janklow, current Gov. George Mickelson, the United
Nations, Canadian officials and others.
   ``All the answers I got, they thought it made sense and was
good,'' he said. ``But most didn't know if we was quite ready for
it yet. ... They all agreed that we're due for a change somehow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
