<FIRST>u a AM-BankRobbery     12-04 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Robbery,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Robbery Suspect Keeps Police, FBI at Bay</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KV2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank robbery suspect holed up inside a
house Monday wounded a policeman, then threatened suicide an
automatic pointed at his chest before a sharpshooter shot it out of
his hand, ending a nearly three-hour standoff, police said.
   A man and a woman also were arrested in the holdup, spokesman
Foster Arnett said.
   The gunman kept police and FBI agents at bay with random shots
fired from inside the house with a .45-caliber automatic, Arnett
said.
   The man emerged from the house in this eastern Tennessee city
around 2:30 p.m. after police filled it with tear gas, Arnett said.
He then lay down on the porch, pointed his pistol at his chest and
flashed a ``peace'' sign.
   A SWAT team member shot the gun out of the man's hand, and
officers captured him, Arnett said. The man was not seriously
wounded.
   Shots fired from inside the house hit Officer Richard Giammarino
three times in the arm and once in the chest. He was in stable
condition at the University of Tennessee Medical Center, Arnett
said.
   ``His bulletproof vest probably saved his life,'' the spokesman
said.
   The incident began around 9:50 a.m., when the gunman and the
other two suspects were seen fleeing the robbery of a First
Tennessee Bank branch.
   An unidentified motorist followed their car, saw them switch
vehicles, followed them to the house and called authorities, Arnett
said.
   The woman and the other man emerged from the house a short time
later and surrendered, Arnett said.
   All three suspects were being held at the Knoxville police
department. Their identities were withheld pending formal charges,
Arnett said.
   Authorities recovered an unspecified amount of money from the
holdup.
</TEXT>
