<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Ashley Adv05   12-04 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Ashley, Adv 05,0873</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday PMs, Dec. 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Elizabeth Ashley: Free Spirit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Mary C Brown,' with no period, is CQ in 12th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talking with Elizabeth Ashley is a grand
adventure. She has fierce energy and a jumpy, bawdy sense of humor.
Her sentences go every which way but loose, full of digressions,
asides and hard sayings. Such as:
   ``Football is an absolute metaphor for life. If you want nice,
clean, let's-pretend sports, watch tennis.''
   Technically, that has nothing to do with her latest venture. But
it's the thought that counts.
   Her latest venture, on cable TV Thursday, is an Arts &amp;
Entertainment version of Eugene O'Neill's ``The Rope.'' She, her
fellow Tony-award winners Jose Ferrer and Len Cariou, and Brad
Davis co-star in it.
   One of four adaptations of one-act plays by Pulitzer
Prize-winning playwrights, Thursday's one-hour drama is, in the
O'Neill custom, a poetic, bitter tale _ in this case one about a
family torn by despair.
   She has known that world of well-scrivened gloom before. But it
proved a particularly good deal in 1974. Then, several years after
a string of so-so TV movies and a busted marriage to actor George
Peppard, whom she refers to only as ``the husband,'' she went back
to theater.
   It was part of a process of starting all over again, says
Ashley, who'd been hailed as an actress of great promise when she
won Broadway's Tony award in 1962 as the bouncy, nubile daughter in
``Take Her, She's Mine.''
   Twelve years later, she says, ``the American Shakesepeare
Festival and Tennessee Williams saved me from being a third-rate
television actress today with `Cat on a Hot Tin Roof.'''
   In that New York revival, she was acclaimed for her
interpretation of Maggie, the Southern beauty married to an
alcoholic.
   Herself a Southern beauty to whom time has been tender, Ashley,
50, was born in Ocala, Fla., and raised in Baton Rouge, La. She is
a veteran, she says, of one semester at Louisiana State University.
   She came to New York at 18 to model and appear in commercials.
Then she studied acting at the Neighborhood Playhouse, paying the
way by waiting tables and playing guitar, ``plunking a few chords
and singing your odd songs.''
   Possessed of a husky, well-modulated voice, she is not thought
of as a singer. Still, she once appeared in a Los Angeles
production of a short-lived musical by her friend Dory Previn,
``Mary C Brown and the Hollywood Sign.''
   Her own assessment: ``I'm not your best singer of show tunes.
I'm a pretty good country singer, though, and I was a great rock
'n' roll screamer.''
   She said all this and more when interviewed in her favorite
bistro, where she periodically lit a cigarette and cheerfully
denounced both yuppies and no-smoking fiends who've ruined most
bistros.
   Her life, which includes a son, Christian Peppard, now 21, has
taken a goodly measure of ups and downs. Ten years ago, after she'd
taken a few years off to go sailing and ponder the cosmos and such,
it was down time.
   She had all the goodies, she says _ a house in Santa Monica, two
lofts in New York, a couple of costly foreign cars. But there was
only $83 in the till. She rented out the house, sold the cars, and
awaited developments.
   She got a call for a Broadway part. It was as the chain-smoking
psychiatrist in what proved a hit, ``Agnes of God.''
   ``That was God kissing me on the cheek,'' she says. ``The second
time around.''
   Ashley, who this year filmed an NBC movie, ``Orleans,'' and
starts off-Broadway rehearsals next month on ``When She Danced,''
about dancer Isadora Duncan, spent 14 months on Broadway in ``Agnes
of God.''
   Then, she says, she spent 40 more weeks on the road, touring in
the play. More than a few actors hate touring. Not Ashley.
   ``I like the road,'' she says. ``It's great to be in a Broadway
hit and a long run. But they know where you are then, and people
start calling you and asking you to do things like'' _ she laughed
and winced _ ``lunch.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   SAME TIME, THIS YEAR _ Morton Downey Jr., whose syndicated shout
show got axed last summer due to fleeing sponsors and declining
ratings, returned to TV Monday. He's back bellowing on cable,
CBNC's ``Showdown,'' where his co-host, who also is a co-bellower,
is Richard G. Carter, a New York Daily News columnist.
   Monday's scheduled premiere threatened a discussion with a
Boston city councilman of suspects' and victims' rights. But it
often degenerated into hostile co-host babble, with Carter twice
calling Downey ``sick.'' Downey in turn accused his black colleague
of being hung up on racial issues, then sneered that ``I even get
my makeup put on darker so we'll match.''
   For the record, the new show has a studio audience and Downey
now wears a gold ring in his left ear lobe.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tuesday PMs, Dec. 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
