<DOCNO> AP891204-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--EuropeanCommentary Adv17   12-04 0979</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--European Commentary, Adv 17,0996</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 3 35mm slides.)</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The changes sweeping Eastern Europe are
reshaping the Continent. Suddenly the old bipolar equation _
Western Europe vs. Eastern Europe _ has been overturned by the
rebirth of an older geographical entity called Central Europe.
   The script is having to be rewritten almost every week. Will
Poland, Hungary, East Germany and Czechoslovakia become Western
democracies? Will the Germanys be united? And if united, will the
German colossus once again threaten Europe's stability? To try to
answer some of these questions, The Associated Press asked five
West European commentators to contribute their thoughts.
   The following overview, the first of five articles, was written
by Adrian G.V. Hyde-Price, a research fellow on the International
Security Program at the Royal Institute of International Affairs in
London, specializing in East-West relations and European security.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ADRIAN G.V. HYDE-PRICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thursday, Nov. 9, the day the East German
authorities allowed their citizens to travel freely to the West,
marks the simultaneous end of the Cold War and the emergence of the
``German question'' as the decisive issue of European politics.
   The lifting of the Iron Curtain is cause for celebration and
euphoria. At the same time the strategic and political
ramifications are enormous, and therefore it is also cause for
sober reflection and what the Dutch foreign minister has called
``constructive alertness.''
   The bipolar structures of the Cold War effectively displaced
deep-seated national and ethnic rivalries in Europe, and replaced
them with a security system which was, for all its many faults,
relatively stable and predictable. One of the crucial features of
this security order was the division of Germany, which provided a
degree of reassurance to many of Germany's traditional opponents.
   Today, however, the old certainties and assumptions of the
postwar period are disintegrating under the combined impact of the
changes _ associated above all with perestroika in the East, and
the 1992 abolition of internal tariff barriers in the European
Economic Community. This is nowhere more apparent than in Central
Europe where, as the Cold War divisions fade away, older patterns
of cooperation and conflict are re-emerging. Changes in this
sensitive region, however, inevitably open the Pandora's box of the
``German question,'' which is now the central issue of European
politics.
   The ``German question'' predates the division of Germany and
stems from the difficulty of integrating German power into the
European interstate system. Germany has traditionally been the
fulcrum of the European balance of power, and this is why the
recent assertion of ``people power'' in the German Democratic
Republic has led to so much discussion about the future of Europe.
   The reform process in East Germany will inevitably entail a
qualitative change in inner-German relations, and therefore a
substantial shift in the balance of power in continental Europe.
   The worries are twofold:
   First, there is the immediate concern about West Germany's
growing economic, political and military weight in Europe. This has
already been felt within the EEC and NATO, where the West Germans
have shown themselves willing and able to assert their national
interests, on economic and financial matters as well as over the
issue of modernizing Short-range Nuclear Forces.
   In Eastern Europe, West German economic and political influence
has been expanding as the military and political dominance of the
Soviet Union has declined. West Germany is now well placed,
geographically, economically and culturally, to benefit from the
new markets and investment opportunities opened up by the reform
movements in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe. At the same time,
the ``renewal'' movement in East Germany will inevitably bring the
two German states closer together, particularly in the economic
sphere, thereby facilitating West German penetration of the rest of
Eastern Europe. Bonn is thus set to become both an economic and a
political giant in European politics.
   Second, there is the fear that in the long term a reunified,
centralized German nation-state (a ``Fourth Reich'') could emerge.
Its precondition would be the collapse of East Germany as a viable
political and economic entity.
   This gives rise to two possible scenarios. First, West Germany
simply expanding to absorb East Germany, while remaining a member
of both the EEC and NATO. This would be unacceptable to the Soviet
Union and might unbalance economic and political relations within
the Western alliance. The second possibility is that the Soviet
Union, faced with a disintegrating East German state, might decide
to make the best of a bad deal, and allow Germany to unite and
remain a member of NATO, provided it became fully denuclearized and
all foreign troops withdrew from German soil.
   This might be acceptable to the Germans, but it would spell the
end of NATO as an effective military alliance.
   In order to assuage fears of a reunited and resurgent ``Fourth
Reich,'' therefore, it is essential that the West collectively
formulate a strategy for managing the changes in East-Central
Europe and in inner-German relations. Above all, a broader European
framework must be forged within which the ``German question'' can
be successfully managed.
   This involves recognizing that the self-determination of the
German people does not necessarily entail reunification, and that
the central issue in Germany at the moment is the democratization
of East Germany.
   Also, a unified or confederated Germany would only be acceptable
to Germany's neighbors in the context of a European Community that
is both well advanced along the path toward economic and political
union, and that is open to new forms of cooperation and association
with other democracies in Europe. Within this broader European
framework, German power could be diffused upward to the
supranational institutions of the EEC and downward to its own
regional governments.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891204-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--EuropeanCommentary-Ludlow Adv17   12-04 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--European Commentary-Ludlow, Adv 17,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Peter W. Ludlow is director of the Center for
European Policy in Brussels, Belgium, and has written extensively
on the European Economic Community.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PETER W. LUDLOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Initial comment on the extraordinary
events that culminated in the breach of the Berlin Wall tended to
dwell on the damage these developments might inflict on the
European Community.
   The Federal Republic, it has been suggested, would now be much
more interested in reunification than in Western European
integration. Every mark spent in Leipzig was one less mark
available for Lisbon. Encouraged perhaps by calculations of this
kind, those who were opposed anyway to speeding up the EC
integration process by, for example, the convening of an
intergovernmental conference on economic and monetary union seized
the occasion offered by the events in Germany and elsewhere to
counsel caution.
   Now was not the time, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Great
Britain and her allies proclaimed, for the EEC to dwell on its own
internal problems when so much was happening beyond its frontiers.
   These early reactions are beginning to appear rather
superficial. None of us, it should be stressed, has much idea of
how events will develop in the East. They are beyond our control.
They also seem to be beyond the control of either government or
opposition leaders.
   The reunification issue is an example. Sober reflection a few
days after the Wall came down suggested that speculation about
prospects for German unity was largely a Western phenomenon. A few
days later, banners in Leipzig proclaiming unification as a highly
desirable objective complicated the picture yet again. Where the
East is going and how quickly remains uncertain.
   These uncertainties have not, however, prevented the emergence
of a fairly widespread consensus among Western European leaders
themselves that in the new circumstances the EC, far from being
redundant, is the indispensable cornerstone of any new European
system. This consensus, manifested at the highest levels at the
Paris dinner party for the heads of government and state of the 12
EC member countries in November rests on various assumptions:
   _That the European Community is the surest framework within
which the Germans themselves can pursue an active policy toward the
East and eventually perhaps achieve reunification.
   _That in a period in which the emphasis in East-West relations
is bound to rest on economic and non-military matters, the European
Community is best placed to coordinate and channel Western aid and
technical assistance.
   _That in a broader perspective, the Community can and should be
seen not only as the most appropriate basis for the European pillar
of the Atlantic alliance, but also as the indispensable Western
pillar in a new European security system in which the Soviet Union
will remain a military superpower regardless of what happens to the
Warsaw Pact.
   Against this background, it is now possible to see the Eastern
developments as a catalyst of Western integration. In the new
circumstances, European Community leaders are almost sure to
demonstrate their determination to continue with their own progress
toward union: Economic and Monetary Union is the obvious practical
initiative, for which highly developed plans already exist.
   In any case, it is already obvious that the Community will be at
the center of a number of high profile efforts to assist the East
directly. These economic and technical means will furthermore be
backed up by even more conspicuous political initiatives involving,
as President Francois Mitterrand of France implied after the Paris
summit, visits to Eastern Europe at the highest level.
   Finally, the acceleration of events and the obvious intention of
European Community leaders to play an active role can only
strengthen those elements in the Bush administration who already
see the Community collectively as the ideal long-term partner with
whom to discuss not only economic issues, but also political and
security questions.
   For those committed to the further development of European
union, these prospects can only be highly gratifying. There are,
however, serious dangers that the West European themselves should
be the first to recognize and deal with:
   _A stronger Western Europe organized through the European
Community can and should be a major asset to the Western Alliance.
It is not, however, as currently organized, in any practical sense
linked to the alliance machinery.
   _More important, a stronger Western Europe that is a magnet to
the East almost certainly will be seen in the Soviet Union as a
potential threat, ready in the worst case to gobble up dissident
members of the Warsaw Pact. However unfounded these fears may be,
the Community should take active steps to reassure the Soviet Union
and to cooperate with it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891204-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--EuropeanCommentary-Mommsen Adv17   12-04 0812</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--European Commentary-Mommsen, Adv 17,0822</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Wolfgang J. Mommsen, a professor of modern
history at Duesseldorf University, has written several books about
the age of European colonial imperialism. He is chairman of West
Germany's Association of Historians and from 1977 to 1985 he was on
loan as head of the German Historial Institute in London, a think
tank supported by the West German government.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By WOLFGANG J. MOMMSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last Nov. 9, 1989, East German
authorities decided to open their borders with West Germany. By now
almost half the population in East Germany has traveled to West
Berlin or to the Federal Republic to see for themselves what this
capitalist society really is like.
   More important, this mass migration westward turned into an
emotional get-together of the Germans, not just for those who had
not seen their relatives for many years, but for everybody.
   Undoubtedly, the opening of the border, symbolized spectacularly
by the instantaneous scrapping of large sections of the hideous
Wall, was a tactical move of the Communist authorities intended to
open a safety valve and head off the constant stream of
demonstrations in almost all major cities in the German Democratic
Republic.
   This strategy may perhaps still succeed in part, but all the
same the situation has changed fundamentally. The peaceful mass
demonstrations have above all achieved one thing: Suddenly the
fear, instilled by an oppressive police state for so many years,
has given way to a new self-confidence.
   The momentous events not only in the GDR, but in East-Central
Europe may perhaps be called the beginning of a Third Democratic
Revolution (the first was the age from 1760 to 1800 highlighted by
the American and French revolutions, and the second by the gradual,
though not continuous advance of democratic government in the West
since the beginning of the 20th century).
   For one, Marxist-Leninist ideology is discredited. The highly
bureaucratic and oppressive system of a centrally directed
socialist economy, which had been established in East Germany
perhaps more effectively than anywhere else, has failed
disastrously. Just a few people on the top, so it emerges, were
capable of making far-reaching decisions affecting the economic
performance of a whole country without any effective control and
almost wholly on ideological grounds. Now democratization has
become unavoidable by any standards.
   Besides, the crumbling of the Wall will imply that the East
German economy can no longer be run in isolation. Between the two
German states, economic cooperation on the governmental and private
levels as well as much economic help will be needed to forestall a
complete breakdown of the economy and mass deprivation in East
Germany, something that would be in nobody's interest. This may
require establishing special links between the Federal Republic,
West Berlin and East Germany. It remains to be seen whether in the
medium term these will devolve into a sort of German confederation,
as seems likely, or whether they will be kept on an informal level
that does not affect the statehood of either of the two Germanys.
   Right now the people from both Germanys are reluctant to go any
further. The West Germans do not want to weaken the close political
and economic ties they have established with the West. Neither are
they prepared to abandon the alliances with the West, even though
the danger of an aggression from the Soviet Union may become
remote. Instead they hope that all steps regarding the
intensification of the relations with East Germany, as well as with
the other East-Central European countries, will be done in full
cooperation with their Western partners.
   The time may be ripe for a second Marshall Plan, this time to be
organized on an international level, with the active participation
not only of the United States and the European Economic Community,
but possibly also Japan. It all depends, however, on what happens
in the Soviet Union itself. West Germans are now perhaps more than
ever interested in making things easier for Mikhail Gorbachev, in
order to see his reform policies succeed. For they are fully aware
that all depends upon whether the Soviet Union will tolerate the
process of democratization in East Central Europe, and in
particular in East Germany.
   Come what may, the democratic revolution under way in Poland,
Hungary, and now East Germany and Czechoslovakia, will change the
course of history. A return to the old ways of a bureaucratic
socialism seems unlikely. The national idea, long believed to be
gradually supplanted by the European idea, seems to have a
remarkable revival. However, it may no longer be quite the
dangerous creature to which we have grown accustomed in the 1920s
and 1930s. Rather it is a nationalism that believes in a Europe of
free nations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891204-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--EuropeanCommentary-Bogdanor Adv17   12-04 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--European Commentary-Bogdanor, Adv 17,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Vernon Bogdanor is a Fellow of Brasenose
College, Oxford, and a lecturer in politics at Oxford University.
He writes extensively on constitutional and European Community
affairs.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By VERNON BOGDANOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain is in, but not of, Europe. She
did not share the psychology of the original six who founded the
European Community in 1958 _France, the Federal Republic of
Germany, Italy, Belgium, Holland and Luxembourg, all of whom
suffered from fascism and enemy occupation.
   For them, World War II showed that the nation-state had to be
overcome through the creation of supranational institutions. For
Britain, the war meant the triumph of the nation-state _ her finest
hour. Not feeling ashamed of her past, she felt assured of her
future as a global superpower, the center of a worldwide empire
rather than a middle-ranking European country.
   She has always known that sooner or later she will have to put
aside her ambivalence and decide whether to join the Continent or
stand aside. The cataclysmic changes in central and eastern Europe
ought to bring this moment of truth closer.
   Although the late French president Charles de Gaulle did his
best to keep Britain out of the European Community, the British
approach to Europe has always been Gaullist. Britain favors a
Europe of cooperating but sovereign independent nations, rather
than any pooling of sovereignty. Entering the Community in 1973,
she thought she was joining merely a customs union rather than a
dynamic organization whose purpose was European union. Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher has given forceful expression to this
conception of Europe.
   Superficially, the changes in central and eastern Europe make
the British government's case for a loosely organized Community
more plausible. For if Central Europe is being unraveled, what is
the sense in continuing with the creation of a closed Community in
the West?
   Instead, so the British argument goes, new forms of association
need to be created that can bridge the ever-narrowing ideological
gap between West and East. It would be parochial to concentrate on
the machinery of integration _exchange rates, monetary union and
the like _ when the solid scaffolding of the Europe we knew is
disintegrating before our eyes.
   This conception, in the view of most of the other governments in
the Community, ignores the vastly increased danger of instability
in Central Europe. The withdrawal of Communism is likely to bring
to the surface all kinds of national conflicts, submerged since the
war through the might of the Soviet Empire. In particular, a
reunited Germany, which now looks a distinct possibility, could
threaten the balance of power in Europe.
   It especially frightens the Poles, whose frontiers, in the
absence of a peace treaty, have still to be finally agreed; and the
French, invaded three times by Germany in the past 120 years. The
French, therefore, are in the vanguard of those arguing that German
reunification can only be safely attempted if Germany becomes fully
integrated into the European Community.
   Britain does not share this fear of Germany. Less traumatized by
World War II, she was more willing to forgive and forget. Less
scarred by history, she finds it difficult to imagine a reunited
Germany as anything other than benign. Traditionally, Britain's
role in Europe has been to stand apart, preserving the balance of
power against the attempt of any single power to dominate the
Continent. That remains the instinct of many leading British
Conservatives.
   The opposition Labor Party has recently taken a distinctly more
pro-European stance. Yet this transformation of attitudes _ it was
the Conservatives who took Britain into the Community, while as
recently as 1983 Labor was promising withdrawal from it _ owes as
much to hostility toward Mrs. Thatcher as to genuine European
conviction.
   There are signs that attitudes are changing. Survey evidence
earlier this year suggested that 55 percent of the British
electorate regarded the Community as a ``good thing,'' the highest
figure since Britain joined. The Euro-elections, which were
catastrophic for Mrs. Thatcher, showed that there is no longer a
strong anti-European constituency in Britain.
   It remains to be seen whether the convulsions in Central Europe
will finally convince the public that Britain is essentially a
European power. Eventually, Britain will have to make a decision of
principle _ whether she wishes to be part of the new political
entity being created in Western Europe, or remain an offshore
island devoid of both power and influence.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
