<DOCNO> AP891204-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1404EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv17   12-04 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 17,0872</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``I rather specialize in old men.''
   So confesses author John Mortimer, whose fifth ``Rumpole of the
Bailey'' series, starring Leo McKern, is running on PBS'
``Mystery,'' and who has a four-part play starring 86-year-old John
Gielgud running on British TV.
   The six Rumpole episodes, each a separate story, began Dec. 7.
``Summer's Lease,'' starring Gielgud, will come to America in the
spring.
   Mortimer retired from practicing law six years ago and doesn't
miss it. Now 66, he continues his other career as a writer. With
six more Rumpole tales ready to be filmed next April, he has
written more about Rumpole than any other character.
   ``I think my writing has got funnier,'' Mortimer says. ``The
last three Rumpole series were written when I wasn't a barrister
any more. I can see the law as funnier when I'm not doing it all
the time.''
   Rumpole is a favorite of ``Mystery'' viewers.
   He calls himself an Old Bailey hack. He takes cases that start
fairly grungy and descend to fairly hopeless. He drinks Chateau
Thames Embankment at Pommeroy's Wine Bar, spouts literary
quotations and witticisms, duels verbally with a wife he calls She
Who Must Be Obeyed, and thinks.
   Everybody from the head of his law chambers to the clerk takes a
dim view of Rumpole's chances in court. Though he usually makes a
brilliant deduction that wins the day, Rumpole is perceived as
muddling through.
   Rumpole is real to Mortimer but not necessarily the most real of
his creations.
   ``The man in `Summer's Lease,' Dodds, the old father, does have
a life of his own. He comes bopping in and does his stuff. It's
what good characters do,'' Mortimer says.
   ``He's played by Gielgud in the TV version of it. It's going to
come to America in April or May on `Masterpiece Theater.' Its four
episodes are a huge success in England.
   ``Dodds had to be played by a great big star. Gielgud
immediately wanted to do it. He's bright as a bee. He has had the
most marvelous notices with this part.''
   In the Rumpole stories, Mortimer says, ``There are always three
plots: the plot of the case, which is the least important one; his
life at home; and his life in chambers. I've always found if you do
an hour's TV, what makes it rich is having a lot of stories going
on at the same time. And it's more interesting to do.
   ``Usually I write the TV scripts first. They don't come out for
nine months. During that time I write the book, so that the book
can come out at the time of the TV show.''
   The paperback ``Rumpole and the Age of Miracles'' contains
Rumpole's adventures in the present series.
   ``I do take a lot of trouble not to make the stories look as if
they were novelizations of scripts,'' Mortimer says. ``I don't just
put `he said' and `she said' into it. I try to write it as though
it's a work of prose fiction to begin with.''
   Mortimer wrote ``Charade,'' his first novel, in 1946, putting in
his experiences in a World War II film unit.
   ``I wrote six novels. `The Narrowing Stream' was about 1954.
Then I wrote `Dock Brief,' which was a radio play.
   ``I gave up writing novels partly because I got into the theater
and partly because I was married to a novelist, Penelope Mortimer,
who wrote `The Pumpkin Eater.' It didn't seem to be right to have
two novelists in the family. I'm not married to her anymore.''
   Three of those early novels have recently been reprinted.
   Mortimer's ``Paradise Postponed'' was seen on TV in America in
1986. It's the result of his being asked to write a 13-part TV
series about England since World War II.
   ``I thought I'd write the novel at the same time,'' he says. ``I
was writing like it was a lot of TV scripts. I had to start again.
I hadn't written a novel in 30 years. In novels you have to write
scenes.''
   Mortimer has just finished a sequel called ``Titmuss Regained,''
which will be published as a book next spring.
   ``It's about the concreting over of the south of England,
building a new town and destroying the countryside,'' he says.
   Britain's politics bemuses Mortimer.
   He says Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's great achievement is
``to have taken the Conservative Party away from the upper class
and given it to the up-and-thrusting lower middle class. It's much
more ruthless than the old upper-class conservatism. Old country
gents were quite keen on looking after the people on the estate,
bringing them blankets and boxes of tea. The new type of
conservatism is just everybody for themselves.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891204-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1407EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv17   12-04 1001</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 17,1033</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.
ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Geraldine James had doubts about acting in ``The
Merchant of Venice'' until she learned that her co-star was Dustin
Hoffman.
   ``When I knew who was playing Shylock, I became rather keen to
do it, unsurprisingly,'' says the 39-year-old English actress,
fresh from a sellout London run as Portia to Hoffman's Jewish
moneylender in Shakespeare's dark comedy of caskets, the law and
revenge.
   The production, directed by Sir Peter Hall, marked Hoffman's
British and Shakespearean stage debut and packed London's Phoenix
Theater for 18 weeks.
   The play is now on view at Broadway's 46th St. Theater for a
limited engagement through Feb. 24. It gives Americans the
opportunity to see a two-time Oscar-winner tackle Shakespeare in a
performance which, James says, changed nightly in London.
   ``To do the trial scene, I used to walk on every day not knowing
what was going to happen,'' she says, referring to Portia's
fourth-act encounter with Shylock, the beleaguered and vengeful
moneylender who meets his match in the heiress, Portia.
   ``When Dustin was truthful, even if he took choices that were
wrong, he was always brilliant _ so riveting and unexpected,'' she
says.
   ``I felt very protective of him ... The whole company as a
company was so proud to be working with him. He was so generous,
spiritually and literally. He wouldn't have his name over the
title, and insisted on me having the last curtain call.''
   James used a six-week break before New York rehearsals to
regather her artistic strength.
   ``We don't ask opera singers to do Wagner eight times a week,
and honestly, I am exhausted,'' she says. ``Portia is a very big,
quite tiring part.''
   The blonde, big-boned actress is best-known to American
audiences for her portrayal of Mirabehn, Mahatma Gandhi's acolyte
in the Oscar-winning movie about the Indian leader's life, and as
Sarah Layton, the India-born daughter of a British colonel, in the
1984 TV miniseries ``The Jewel in the Crown.''
   James' first experience in ``Merchant'' came while playing
Jessica, Shylock's daughter, in a provincial production 10 years
ago in the English midlands city of Coventry.
   Then, she recalls, Portia struck her as ``a bit of a know-all.''
Now, she finds her ``a miraculous character,'' and attributes her
shift in perceptions to Hall's direction.
   ``With Shakespeare, he is the master, he can tell you how to do
it,'' James says. ``If I was going to see Shakespeare for the first
time, I would choose a Peter Hall production. He may not go for
innovation, but he does the play.''
   Hall says he admired James's ``natural musicality and sense of
rhythm ... She'sa very intelligent, feisty actress.''
   James says the director encouraged her to explore the
contradictions of a character who can seem dismissive and even
racist one minute, ripe with ``the quality of mercy'' _ in
Shakespeare's celebrated phrase _ the next.
   ``It's tempting to iron those contradictions out so that
characters become one-dimensional in order to become
recognizable,'' James says. ``As actors we always want to be liked;
it's much braver to dare to be disliked.''
   She says Portia's complexities ``are part of her interest.''
   ``People say, `How can someone be as nice and as nasty as
Portia?' But we're very often like that,'' James says. ``It's much
too simple to say Portia's any one thing, because she's all of them.
   ``It's important to win an audience around through convincing
them of the truth of the character.''
   ``Merchant'' reunited James with Hall, who directed her as
Imogen in Shakespeare's ``Cymbeline'' last year at the National
Theater. She replaced Sarah Miles just three weeks before the first
preview of Shakespeare's sprawling, rarely performed late romance.
   ``It was wonderful doing `Cymbeline' knowing people didn't know
it at all,'' she says. ``Those who came discovered the play.''
   She also starred in Hall's first film in 15 years, ``She's Been
Away,'' as the self-destructive banker's wife. She and co-star Dame
Peggy Ashcroft shared the best actress prize at the Venice Film
Festival in September.
   ``I had worked with Peter; Peggy had worked with Peter; I had
worked with Peggy,'' James says. ``A lot of things about it made
sense.''
   She and the legendary Ashcroft, now 81, co-starred in ``The
Jewel in the Crown,'' about the end of British rule in India.
   And the afterglow lingers on: ``I get letters still from
America. They have `Jewel in the Crown' evenings, watching it on
video, eating curries and wearing saris.''
   Her training, typical of many English performers, was in the
theater. She studied at the Drama Center and did a stint as a
dresser with the Royal Shakespeare Company, which was then
presenting Ashcroft in Edward Albee's ``A Delicate Balance.''
   Years in regional repertory theaters led to the London
``fringe'' and on to the commercial West End, where she starred
opposite Julie Walters in ``When I Was a Girl, I Used To Scream and
Shout.''
   Her first major screen part was in ``Gandhi.'' Earlier this
year, she appeared with Jeff Goldblum in a new film comedy, ``The
Tall Guy.'' Neither that film nor ``She's Been Away'' has yet been
released in the United States.
   James will be seen later this year on-screen in ``The Wolves of
Willoughby Chase,'' starring Stephanie Beacham from ``The Colbys''
and ``Dynasty.''
   Next year, she and Ben Kingsley, her ``Gandhi'' co-star, re-team
for a two-character play, Lanford Wilson's ``A Betrothal,'' which
they first performed above a London pub three years ago.
   James was born in Berkshire, west of London, one of three
children and the daughter of a cardiologist. The product of ``a
typical middle-class family,'' she says she became an actress more
or less against the wishes of her parents.
   ``But if the spirits want you to be something, you be it,'' she
says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
