<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   12-04 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: `She-Devil'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``She-Devil'' is a revenge movie without Sly, Clint, Arnold or
Chuck. This time it's Roseanne Barr who shows those vengeful gents
the kind of hell that a scorned woman can administer.
   Barr is the dull, slovenly, accident-prone wife of Ed Begley
Jr., an ambitious New York accountant with amazing tolerance for
her many failings. They include running their suburban home like a
city slum and mismanaging their two overbearing children.
   When the couple attends a gallery opening in Manhattan, he falls
into the clutches of a man-hungry, self-adoring writer of romance
novels, Meryl Streep. Weary of her live-in gigolo, she decides to
give the accountant her business and her love.
   Barr slowly realizes her husband has been led astray. She boils
with Mephistophelean wrath, vowing to rob him of everything he
holds dear: his family life, his career, his new love, his freedom.
Her methods are as far-fetched as they are hilarious.
   Full-out farce such as ``She-Devil'' requires a feathery
directorial touch and the most delicate of playing. Susan
Seidelman's direction is on target most of the way, maintaining a
whirlwind pace that forestalls suspension of belief. The script by
Mark R. Burns and Barry Strugatz is cleverly constructed, though
some of the comedy is misdirected (example: the spoofing of
senility in a retirement sanitarium).
   The movie is based on the novel, ``The Life and Loves of a
She-Devil,'' by Fay Weldon. Set in Britain, the novel was made into
a critically acclaimed TV miniseries telecast by PBS.
   The big news in ``She-Devil'' is Streep's emergence as a
world-class comedy actress. She attacks the role of the vain,
foolish novelist with a skilled gusto that invites comparison to
the great Lucille Ball. Streep is delicious in her cunning
calculation and convulsively funny when her champagne world loses
its fizz.
   Another revelation is Ed Begley Jr., heretofore known for expert
character roles in films (``The Accidental Tourist'' and ``Scenes
From the Class Struggle in Beverly Hills'') and as the
self-centered doctor of television's ``St. Elsewhere.'' Tall and
clunky with unruly straw-colored hair, he is the ideal foil for the
marvelous Streep.
   ``She-Devil'' marks Barr's film debut following her rapid rise
as a standup comedian and television star. It would be nice to
report that she scores another triumph. Alas, she seems uneasy and
tentative in her role as the vindictive wife, as if wondering where
the jokes are. With more expert handling, she can undoubtedly
register on the big screen. Next time, Roseanne.
   The Orion release is rated PG-13, for mild swearing and
suggestive situations. Running time: 99 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
