<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   12-04 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``How I Got Into College'' (CBS-Fox Video. VHS-Beta, $89.98.
Rated PG-13.)
   
   Marlon Brown, a rather dim high school student who bombs out on
his SATs, nevertheless sets his sights on getting into selective
Ramsey College to be near the girl he loves from afar, Jessica
Kailo _ scholar, cheerleader and class president.
   Will Marlon (Corey Parker) get into Ramsey? Will he win the girl
of his dreams? Will Jessica (Lara Flynn Boyle) get into Ramsey?
   A high school guidance counselor might call ``How I Got Into
College'' an underachiever.
   Consider the potential for a movie about getting into college _
the terror of taking the SATs, confusion over where to apply, the
dreaded college interview, the agonizing wait for word of whether
you've been admitted or rejected. ``How I Got Into College,'' a
comedy, tries to take on all this, but does it with little humor,
drama or insight.
   It has some clever spots _ a shady SAT coaching service; a
mailman bringing a letter with a demonic grin; students phoning
home frantically to find out whether they've received a fat letter
(an acceptance) or a thin one (a rejection).
   But the movie often substitutes offbeat camera angles for humor,
and the odd-couple romance isn't particularly compelling. By the
end, it's clear Marlon has more to offer than we thought. But not
much more.
   Send ``How I Got Into College'' a thin letter.
   _ By Pete Brown, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Badge of the Assassin'' (Vidmark. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated R.)
   
   Why would anyone want to spend $90 for a made-for-television
movie that has had its share of reruns since 1985? Video companies
seem to think consumers are either dumb or so hungry for movies
they'll buy anything.
   ``Badge of the Assassin'' is actually a fairly good cop and
court room drama about the conviction of Black Liberation Army
members who murdered two police officers in New York City in the
early 1970s. It stars Yaphet Kotto as the investigating detective
who must walk a thin line, and James Woods as the young and
crusading assistant district attorney who prosecutes the black
radicals.
   But despite excellent acting, the pacing is slow and the overall
feel of the movie is television tepid. The hard edge that could and
should be there is missing.
   ``Under the Biltmore Clock,'' from Nelson for $79.98, is another
leftover from television. This time it's the jazz age as seen
through Sean Young. You can miss it.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
