<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 2123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   12-04 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Lute Suites, by Johann Sebastian Bach (London) _ Eduardo
Fernandez, guitar
   Compact disc enemies now have some new ammunition. This
recording not only reproduces Fernandez's sound in crystal, it also
captures to a distracting degree the clicking, zinging sounds of
the mechanics of playing his instrument.
   Aside from the the suites, this two-disc set offers
transcriptions of assorted Bach works for violin and harpsichord,
confined to a second disc timed at a pitiful 44.59.
   Fernandez is also a little ungenerous musically. His techically
fine playing sounds not especially sensitive, on this recording at
least. Lines are not well shaped and don't always emerge
independently, and the phrasing sometimes sounds rushed.
   _ By Daniel J. Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Deaf, Dumb, and Blonde'' (Sire) _ Deborah Harry
   
   ``Deaf, Dumb and Blonde'' is Deborah Harry's third solo effort
since the breakup of the punk bastion Blondie.
   Unfortunately, Harry has locked into today's pop format and the
album lacks her snarling early 1980s cleverness.
   Two of the tracks, including the lead single, ``I Want That
Man,'' were written by Allanah Currie and Tom Bailey of the
Thompson Twins, and their influence permeates most of the record in
the form of snappy beats and almost mundane lyrics.
   On the few songs Harry wrote with ex-boyfriend Chris Stein, the
dark, brooding punk attitudes return. Harry's self-confident lyrics
and Stein's menacing guitar combine on several notable tracks.
   ``Lovelight,'' a duet with Ian Astbury of The Cult, mixes
paradoxical imagery with Indian rhythms to tell of love in a
cryptic, mystical setting. ``Calmarie,'' which Harry sings partly
in Spanish, is a lovely showcase for the higher register of her
voice.
   ``Brite Side'' produces a more tender side. She is confident,
but not arrogant; loving, but not worshiping.
   You have to wait for most of the record for a real knockout.
That comes with the last track, the gorgeously arranged ``End of
the Run.'' It is a partly spoken song-poem that tells of Harry's
beginnings: ``when a torn T-shirt made it all dangerous.'' In it,
she says she ``doesn't like flashbacks in movies ... I like the
story to proceed.''
   Harry's story has proceeded, but into what's threatening to look
like pop dribble. She's called her new music ``simpler and more
aggressive.'' Simpler, yes. More agressive, no.
   By Kira L. Billik, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
