<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Chase Takes Charge of His Career</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1 of Dec. 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a dozen years in movies, Chevy Chase
can still take a tumble to get a laugh, but he is learning not to
risk career falls because of bad advice.
   The lesson hasn't come easily for the tall, preppie-looking
comedian. After creating a falling-down sensation on ``Saturday
Night Live,'' he made an impressive film debut in ``Foul Play'' and
followed with big-money hits such as ``Caddyshack,'' ``National
Lampoon's Vacation'' and ``Fletch.'' But along the way he
encountered films that might have submerged a less durable
performer: ``Under the Rainbow,'' ``Oh! Heavenly Dog,'' ``Modern
Problems,'' ``The Deal of the Century.''
   Despite such disasters, Chase has survived and reportedly draws
$5 million per movie. His latest is ``National Lampoon's Christmas
Vacation,'' which reunites him with ``Vacation'' buddies Beverly
D'Angelo and Randy Quaid.
   Chase has finally reached a point where he decided he had to
take charge of his own career.
   ``I don't think there's a star around who doesn't feel that
way,'' he reflected. ``The problem with that is that it can become
too egotistical, too warped by your own lack of introspection and
perspective.
   ``The world is different (when you're a star). It behaves
differently towards you. You're no longer just like anybody else
around you. You have to remember there's such a thing as compromise
and collaboration. On top of that, of all the arts that I'm
familiar with, film is the most collaborative.
   ``I was reading an article about Bill Friedkin (`The Exorcist')
the other day. He said, `I don't consider myself any more or less
important than a crew member.' We all know that's not true of Bill.
We know that he would like to think that and that he means it. The
fact is that his ego takes over, and he gets crazy. He's also a
brilliant director.''
   Chase cited last year's ``Fletch Lives'' as evidence of why he
needs to make his own decisions.
   ``Quite frankly, I had a lot of trepidation about the `Fletch'
sequel. It was in the middle of the writers' strike. I was the only
one who kept saying, `No, it's not gonna work, it's not happening.'
... Everybody at Universal: `It's going to be great, don't worry.'
Me: `No, it's not working.
   ``I hate that. And yet I go along with it. It ends up with me
putting on a lot of funny faces and trying to mug my way through a
picture. It worked for what it was. But I didn't think it was a
good picture. Then I have to go out on a junket and promote it, the
whole time feeling bad about it.''
   Chase doesn't feel that way about ``Christmas Vacation.''
   ``I think it can stand on its own as a picture,'' he said.
``It's got a lot of the richness of the first `Vacation,' if you
can call that stuff rich. It's written by John Hughes, as the first
one was. ... It's directed by a very talented young director named
Jeremiah Chechik, who's got a great eye and a lot of warmth.
   ``And it's very physical, more physical in the Buster Keaton
tradition than I've ever done before. I love that stuff.''
   Chase said he participated in all the production decisions, from
the first meeting with executives from Warner Bros. until the final
print. If he is so gung-ho on control, why doesn't he direct his
own films, like Clint Eastwood and Eddie Murphy?
   ``Clint's children are grown up; Eddie doesn't have any,'' he
pointed out. ``I'm not prepared to take myself away from my family
for the amount of time (needed to direct a film). I try to be as
much a part of the directing process as I can, without being away
from my family.
   ``It's hard enough to be the star and see your family during
that three-month production period. If you direct a movie, you're
looking at a year. This is a very important, precious period in my
kids' lives,'' he said.
   Chase has three children. ``They are from one to six years old,
and a five-year-old. They need the accessibility of their dad, as
well as their mom. The fact is, I need it, too.''
   His resolve may stem from his own childhood: ``I came from a
divorced family, and that was very tough. I think it has affected
me all my life. I think it affects anyone whose parents are
divorced. I don't like it, I don't like to see it happen. It's hard
on the kids.''
   He was born into a wealthy New York family on Oct. 8, 1943, and
named Cornelius Crane Chase (his grandmother provided the Chevy,
perhaps after the Washington suburb). An expensive education
provided a bachelor of arts degree in English and a determination
to perform. After writing for Mad magazine and the Smothers
Brothers, he fell in with the National Lampoon people and ended up
in the first cast of ``Saturday Night Live.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 15-17</NOTE>
