<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 15-17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Canadian Band Makes Movie Debut</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5 of Dec. 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian rockers Blue Rodeo are used to stealing
shows on their own, but in their recent movie debut they played
backup band to country and western singer Meryl Streep.
   Meryl Streep?
   That's right. And, according to Blue Rodeo vocalist Greg Keelor,
the band has the Academy Award-winning actress' chauffeur to thank
for the gig.
   Platinum-selling artists in their native Canada, the five
members of Blue Rodeo hope their cameo with Streep in next year's
release of ``Postcards From the Edge'' and their new album,
``Diamond Mine,'' will propel them to similar status in the United
States.
   ``She's very good,'' group member Jim Cuddy said of Streep's
performance on ``Checking Out of the Heartbreak Hotel.''
   ``She can sing very well. She's probably kind of a boundless
entertainer.''
   Filmmaker Mike Nichols wanted a group that sounded like an early
version of The Band. Blue Rodeo, who performed with former Band
members Robbie Robertson, Rick Danko and Garth Hudson on the
Canadian Juno Awards show earlier this year, was one of five bands
asked to submit tapes.
   Streep was listening to the tapes while being driven into New
York City when her chauffeur raved about Blue Rodeo's 1987 debut,
``Outskirts,'' Keelor said. Soon after, Blue Rodeo auditioned and
won the movie role.
   ``It was a very normal kind of experience,'' said Cuddy, whose
band rehearsed Patsy Cline songs with Streep before shooting the
scene. ``I'm sure that's not the typical Hollywood experience. This
was one of the first times we've stayed in separate rooms.''
   Blue Rodeo traces its roots to the late 1970s, when Toronto
natives Keelor and Cuddy rather violently crossed paths for the
first time. Cuddy was a football linebacker who slammed quarterback
Keelor to the ground in a scrimmage. Nevertheless, they soon became
friends and began writing songs together.
   Keelor and Cuddy moved to New York City in the early '80s
looking to succeed with Fly to France, a rock band they admit now
was unfocused. Fly to France shared rehearsal space with Toronto
friends who formed the Cowboy Junkies.
   Trying to make it in New York proved unsatisfying, typified by
the disappointment the pair heard from musicians who responded to
their newspaper ad and found they wouldn't be flown to France for
auditions, Cuddy said.
   They moved back to Toronto in 1984 and ditched Fly to France.
They formed Blue Rodeo, adding acoustic guitars to their collection
and aiming for a country-rock hybrid inspired by the Everly
Brothers and the Beatles.
   ``It was the music to do,'' said the 33-year-old Cuddy. ``It
gives an artist a certain longevity, a certain respectability that
is not always evident in pop music. To just chase pop music and
chase an audience that's half your age is a little ridiculous. .. .
It's especially embarrassing if you get rejected by 11-year-olds.''
   Despite a twang in their sound, Blue Rodeo doesn't feel
comfortable in the world of country music. And, frankly, country
music probably wouldn't feel comfortable with a band whose keyboard
player occasionally solos by standing barefoot on his organ.
   ``I like the harmonies and I like the mournfulness of it,''
Cuddy said of country music. ``I've always liked the details in the
lyrics, the focus on small details, but I've never wanted to be a
full-fledged member of country music. It's just not something that
appeals to me. I think we're rock musicians borrowing from
country.''
   Like a certain famed British songwriting duo they admired, Cuddy
and Keelor's styles are often a contrast between the sinister and
the sweet.
   Cuddy's smooth voice highlights country ballads like ``Try,''
which won a Juno Award for Canadian song of the year in 1988, and
new songs ``Now and Forever'' and ``House of Dreams.''
   Keelor's vocal phrasing is a dead ringer for early Elvis
Costello on ``The Ballad of the Dime Store Greaser and the Blonde
Mona Lisa'' and, with keyboard player Bob Wiseman, he creates an
eerie, Doors-like sound on the new album's title cut.
   The contrast can be jarring on record but makes more sense
onstage when the pair harmonize, said Keelor, 35.
   ``It's certainly an advantage in that you can cover a lot of
ground in songwriting,'' Cuddy said. ``We can approach things from
a couple of different ways. And just from a physical standpoint,
it's nice not to have to sing all night.''
   Blue Rodeo's sound, for lack of a more appropriate word, has
been described as quintessentially American. They're not afraid to
sing about their southern neighbors; ``God and Country'' is about
Oliver North.
   ``There's also a sort of Canadian tradition in the band, like
Neil Young and Joni Mitchell, of writing a lot about America,''
Keelor said. ``But it's with a different perspective, it's like
with a distance.
   ``The modern world has a fascination with the United States. But
for us, it's even more tangible. We speak the language. We can
cross the borders and work down here as legal aliens. I did that
for years.''
   But Blue Rodeo's own success points out differences between the
two countries.
   In Canada, ``Outskirts'' was the country's equivalent of a
double-platinum album (more than 200,000 sold) and the band plays
in concert halls. In the United States, they're critical favorites
but are largely unknown. In the United States, a double-platinum LP
would mean that more than 2 million copies were sold.
   At a recent Blue Rodeo performance in New York, dozens of
Canadians packed the Lone Star Roadhouse. A cardboard cutout of a
Canadian Mountie hung over the stage. Such questions as ``what
province are you from?'' replaced typical New York small talk.
   ``The success we have in Canada is pretty good for us,'' Keelor
said. ``We'd like to do the same thing here. A large part of it is
just to keep playing and have people see us. We're fairly confident
that when people see us, they'll like it. It's a good show.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 15-17</NOTE>
