<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Monroe Adv15-17   12-04 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Monroe, Adv 15-17,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 15-17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Year of Milestones for Bill Monroe</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NS2 of Dec. 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been a year of milestones for Bill
Monroe, ``the father of bluegrass music.''
   In October, the stately 78-year-old celebrated his 50th
anniversary on the Grand Ole Opry, the live country music show he
helped transform into an American institution. In February, he won
a Grammy Award in a newly added category: best bluegrass recording.
   And he ended the decade the way he began it: chatting with the
president at the White House. In 1980, he played his beloved
mandolin on the White House lawn for President Carter. This
November, he was invited to 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue to meet
President Bush.
   When the celebrations and awards and White House visits subside,
Monroe can sit at his office desk and read a sticker pasted on the
wall: ``Bluegrass: finger picking good.''
   This music, developed by Monroe in the 1930s, has been mighty
good indeed to this legendary performer.
   Millions have heard him on the Grand Ole Opry or in live
performances. He's entertained in every state and in several
foreign countries. He's sold more than 50 million records.
   In 1986, the U.S. Senate adopted a resolution honoring him for
``many contributions to American culture and music.''
   He says he's lasted so long because he took care of himself and
enjoyed singing and playing.
   ``I've always liked work and I've been stout,'' he said in an
interview. ``I've taken care of myself and never did smoke or
drink. Work is something I've always liked to do. I like to do
something every day.
   ``I love to play music and hear it. I love to put the sounds and
notes in there that I want to hear. I want to do the best I can for
my friends and fans sitting out there in the audience.''
   Monroe, a descendant of the fifth president of the United
States, is best known for his songs ``Blue Moon of Kentucky,''
``Uncle Pen'' and ``Mule Skinner Blues.'' ``Blue Moon of
Kentucky,'' which he wrote in 1946, was recorded some 10 years
later by Elvis Presley.
   ``I knew he was coming with another style of music,'' Monroe
recalled. ``One Saturday night, they had him on the Grand Ole Opry.
He came around to me and apologized for singing the way he did.''
   ``I told him if it gave him a good start with his music and
everything, I was for him 100 percent. So our friendship stood good
all the way.''
   Born near Rosine, Ky., Monroe was the youngest of eight children
and was orphaned by age 11. He was raised by an uncle who was an
excellent fiddler and mandolinist. By age 12, Monroe was playing
music at dances with his uncle and perfecting his tenor voice that
was to enthrall millions for years to come.
   Down through the years, he taught bluegrass music _ the string
music of guitars, banjos, fiddles and mandolins _ to disciples such
as Lester Flatt and Earl Scruggs, who played in his band, the
Bluegrass Boys.
   Monroe has recorded for MCA Records for nearly 40 years, a
rarity in the music industry where performers often change labels
every few years.
   ``They've been a big help to me and we work together good,'' he
said. His most recent album is ``Bill Monroe and the Bluegrass Boys
Live at the Opry.''
   He still performs 100 times a year at bluegrass festivals,
country music shows and the like. In his office is a lined white
sheet of paper with a place on each line for the date and the city
he's booked in. Even after more than 50 years on the road, he still
finds travel inspirational.
   ``I like to see the hills and mountains and valleys and how they
take care of the land and everything,'' Monroe said.
   He's been blessed with good health and a steely determination to
keep his music alive. When he was diagnosed with colon cancer in
the early 1980s, he fought it with the spirit he shows as his
nimble fingers dance along the neck of his mandolin.
   ``The doctor said I whipped the cancer out,'' Monroe said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 15-17</NOTE>
