<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:WyomingCentennial     12-04 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Wyoming Centennial,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Wyoming Centennial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY700, NY701</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wyoming is inviting one and all to take a
step into its rollicking, rowdy past during the state's year-long
centennial celebration in 1990.
   Settled by rugged mountain men who revered the Rocky Mountains'
beaver pelts as highly as gold and later by cowboys tending cattle
herds that once made Cheyenne the richest town per capita in the
world, Wyoming's heritage is woven of the stuff that made the West
wild.
   Justice once was dispensed with a short rope and a long drop,
and outlaws like Butch Cassidy, the Sundance Kid and the rest of
``the Wild Bunch'' often high-tailed it to the ``Hole in the Wall''
west of Kaycee in central Wyoming to avoid the gallows between bank
heists and train holdups.
   The outlaws, the range wars between cattlemen and sheep
ranchers, and the lonely lives of cowboys riding the desolate
plains in search of strays all combined to give Wyoming an image as
a wild place for the rough-and-ready.
   During 1990 travelers will be able to sample this life, be it by
viewing the state's open expanses from atop a Conestoga wagon, by
taking in the world's largest rodeo at the 94th annual Cheyenne
Frontier Days in late July, or by walking through the barracks at
Fort Laramie, where the cavalry once protected emigrants passing
along the Overland Trail.
   ``There will be plenty of western-oriented activities for people
to participate in,'' says Becky Evans, community service consultant
for the Wyoming Centennial Commission.
   And the activities will be found in just about every corner of
the state as communities from Cody to Cheyenne, Spotted Horse to
Smoot, and Mule Creek Junction to Moose celebrate the centennial.
   While the state that boasts of being ``What America Once Was''
won't actually turn 100 until July 10, the partying begins on Jan.
1 and runs through the end of the year.
   Montana's centennial party this year gained nationwide attention
with a massive, and dusty, cattle drive reminiscent of those run
from Texas to Wyoming and Montana in the late 1800s, but in Wyoming
there's really no single eye-grabbing, headline-catching event.
   Instead the Wyoming Centennial Commission is urging the state's
communities to mark the birthday in ways fitting to their
particular heritage.
   With that in mind, for those tourists who want to step into the
past there will be wagon trains and trail rides, shootouts and
rodeos, ice cream socials and elaborate balls.
   Those who prefer to mix the present with the past will be able
to take in an international centennial celebration in Worland
featuring Chinese ice sculptures, cheer on cyclists in the Casper
Classic International Bike Race in Casper, or take in the Grand
Teton Music Festival with 13,766-foot-tall Grand Teton serving as a
backdrop.
   A look at the mountain men who wandered the state's rocky ranges
in search of furs will be possible in Pinedale in early July, when
the 54th reenactment of the 1840 mountain man rendezvous on the
Green River is staged.
   The biggest individual birthday party will be held in early July
in Cheyenne, the state capital tucked away in Wyoming's
southeastern corner. The celebration July 7-10 will include a
reenactment of the arrival of the original telegram declaring
Wyoming's statehood, an ethnic festival recognizing the diverse
cultures that call the state home, and a fireworks extravaganza.
   Evans said 10,000-15,000 people a day are expected to join the
revelry in Cheyenne, which in the late 1800s was known as ``Hell on
Wheels'' because of the hard-drinking, gun-toting men who passed
through the frontier town.
   Wyoming's geography is just as diverse as the centennial
celebrations. Although the eastern half of the state is mostly
high, desolate plains cut here and there by long, narrow strips of
mountain ranges, the western half is internationally renowned for
its grandeur.
   Secretary of State James Baker brought Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze to Jackson Hole in September to conduct
ministerial meetings in the shadows of the craggy, snow-capped
Tetons. Just to the north of the valley is the world's first
national park, Yellowstone, and its vast bison and elk herds and
thousands of thermal features.
   ``There's plenty for people to participate in 1990,'' Evans
says. ``All they have to is contact us and we'll let them know.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Additional information on Wyoming's centennial may be obtained
by writing the Wyoming Centennial Commission, Herschler Building,
Cheyenne, Wyo., 82002, or the Wyoming Travel Commission, Frank
Norris Jr. Travel Center, Cheyenne, Wyo., 82002.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891204-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:IdahoCentennial     12-04 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Idaho Centennial,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Travel: Idaho Centennial ^By DAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visitors who visit Idaho during its 1990
Centennial have a unique opportunity to experience the theme that
runs through the state's history like a vein of gold _ man's love
affair with the land.
   The Gem State's 100th birthday party will feature a gamut of
``Wild West'' celebrations in virtually every town and county. And
there is the added reward of traveling through eye-catching Idaho.
   Idaho became the 43rd state on July 3, 1890.
   Settlers traveled to Idaho for its resources: gold and silver,
endless stands of timber, the rich volcanic soil.
   ``People who came here were looking for something to exploit,
but not in the bad sense,'' said Arthur Hart, a member of the Idaho
Centennial Commission who spent 17 years as director of the Idaho
Historical Society.
   One of the most involved projects in the celebration is the
creation of a Centennial Park. State officials insisted that
monument reflect industry's role in opening up the wild territory
to civilization.
   Mining attracted the first major influx of settlers, so it was
natural to locate the park around the old gold rush towns of Custer
and Bonanza in central Idaho.
   Those rustic ghost towns are a short jaunt off Idaho 75, nestled
in the pines along the Yankee Fork of the Salmon River. Ore wagons
rattled along the Motorway toll road to the ranching community of
Challis, where the park's interpretive center will be built.
   ``We had two Oregon Trail parks, but we didn't have any park for
mining, which brought them here in the first place,'' Hart said.
``The Oregon Trail people passed through Idaho, but didn't think
they could farm here.''
   Within two hour's drive from the Centennial Park are the granite
crags of the Sawtooth Mountains, the champagne whitewater of the
Middle and Main forks of the Salmon, or the world-class ski slopes
of Sun Valley. The resort retains the 1940s aura that attracted the
world's elite: Ernest Hemingway, Gary Cooper and Clark Gable, to
name a few.
   The Silver Valley in the Idaho Panhandle historically has ranked
as one of the top 10 mining districts in the world.
   Travelers intending to put in a busy day can visit the Coeur
d'Alene District Mining Museum in Wallace, Idaho's oldest standing
building in the Catholic Cataldo Mission built in 1853, or the
lakeside resort community of Coeur d'Alene.
   Cataldo was built by Jesuit priests and local Indians using
wooden pegs instead of nails.
   North America's longest gondola will soon stretch from the town
of Kellogg to the Silverhorn ski area in the Silver Valley.
   Northern Idaho remains a thick carpet of timber and once
featured the largest stand of white pine in the world. Lumberjacks
used to transport logs on the Clearwater River to the sawmills of
Lewiston in gigantic wooden flotillas complete with tents for
cooking and sleeping.
   Lumberjacks will chop, saw and climb trees as Lewiston showcases
its logging heritage with the grand finals of the World Association
of Timber Sports in May, 1990.
   People from all races came to Idaho to work the mines, farm or
build the railroads. The centennial honors them all with
celebrations or interpretive studies.
   In the midst of World War II in 1942, 9,400 Japanese-Americans
were relocated to the wind-swept Minidoka Relocation Center near
Twin Falls in south-central Idaho.
   The Japanese American Citizens League plans to build an
interpretive center at the camp.
   Basques from the Spanish Pyrenees migrated to the United States
from the 1800s on to tend sheep bands. Boise is the largest enclave
of Basques in North America. They plan their second Jaialdi
cultural festival in Boise in June, 1990, drawing Basques from the
West and Europe.
   When American explorers Meriwether Lewis and William Clark
passed into Idaho through Lolo Pass in 1805, they met friendly
Shoshone and Nez Perce Indian tribes who had roamed through
northern Idaho on spotted appaloosa horses for centuries.
   They are two of the state's six tribes that will meet for the
first time in Boise on July 9-15 for an ``All Idaho Indian Expo''
to present their histories, dreams and social issues.
   The Idaho Centennial calendar lists more than 500 events next
year, from an Idaho Cowboy Poetry Gathering to a whistle stop tour
of Union Pacific Railroad's steam engine No. 8444. Idaho's
Statehood Day celebration will run 43 hours from July 2 to
Independence Day with a dizzying schedule of fireworks and parades.
   ``Former Gov. John Evans said `I want a celebration of one
million,'' meaning he wanted every man, woman and child involved,''
Hart said. ``We're coming as close to that as we can.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
