<DOCNO> AP891204-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:SkiNotes     12-04 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Ski Notes,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Ski Notes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Frontier Visatours aims at the 55-plus winter traveler, known
affectionately as ``Sunshine Birds,'' counterparts of the ``Snow
Birds'' who go to Florida for the season.
   One of its trips is called the Snow Train, a four-hour Amtrak
journey through the Sierra Nevada Mountains at elevations 9,000
feet and higher. _
   The Budweiser Eagle Liner, the ski train between Denver and
Winter Park, Colo., begins its 1989-1990 season on Dec. 2. The
train makes a two-hour trip through the Rockies every Saturday in
December and Saturdays and Sundays from Jan. 6 through April 8,
with two holiday excursions Dec. 26 and 29.
   (The Hyatt Regency Denver downtown offers a discount on the ski
train fare for its guests.) _
   New air service to Colorado ski country begins Dec. 23, when
America West Airlines starts its operation of daily flights from
Phoenix to Vail and Beaver Creek and weekly service from Los
Angeles. _
   The new vertical rise gondola, The Silver Queen, will whisk
Aspen Mountain skiers from base to summit in less than 15 minutes,
a trip that used to take about 45 minutes. The vertical rise is the
world's longest and is at the heart of Colorado ski country,
incorporating Snowmass, Buttermilk, Aspen Mountain and Aspen
Highlands. The four-mountain area has more than 3,700 acres of
skiable terrain with 4l lifts, including four quad SuperChairs. _
   Improved amenities for East Coast skiers include new snowmaking
on the recently opened Timberline Peak at the Bolton Valley Resort
in Vermont. Night lighting, previously limited to the lower
mountain, now extends to the summit. Nine and one-half acres of ski
terrain on the connecting trail between Ricker Mountain and
Timberline Peak assures access to the Timberline quadruple
chairlift from Village lifts 3 and 4. _
   A new ski-in, ski-out resort at Beaver Creek, Colo., was opened
this fall by Hyatt Regency. The resort is adjacent to two lifts for
some of Colorado's best ski runs, including the crest of the 2
3@4-mile run laid out in a bid for the Winter Olympics in l976. The
Alpine-style resort has 300 rooms and is in a auto-free village
which also is home to the Vail@Beaver Creek ski school. _
</TEXT>
</DOC>
