<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Guides     12-04 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Guides,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Guides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Long an institution in Britain and Europe, bed and breakfast
accommodation on this side of the Atlantic has come into its own in
recent years. ``The Annual Directory of American Bed &amp; Breakfasts''
(Rutledge Hill Press) has comprehensive listings of almost 4,000
B&amp;B establishments in the U.S., Canada, Puerto Rico and the Virgin
Islands. _
   ``The Airline Passenger's Guerrilla Handbook'' by George Albert
Brown (Blakes Publishing Group) is a self-help guide for frequent
or occasional flyers. The book advises how to get the best fares,
how to deal with long lines at passport control, how to sleep
sitting up, how to deal with groups such as Hare Krishna at the
airport, and many of the other minutiae of air travel. _
   So your diet and nutrition regimen doesn't go by the boards when
you travel, Hope S. Warshaw has compiled ``The Retaurant Companion:
A Guide to Healthier Eating Out'' (Surrey Books). A registered
dietition and certified diabetes educator, Ms. Warshaw offers tips
to cut fat, sodium and calories from restaurant meals and how to
make nutritionally wise restaurant choices. _
   A gazetteer-format guide to road travel in the U.S., ``On the
Road USA'' (Reader's Digest) has maps, thumbnail sketches, and
camping and access keys to attractions in the country close to
exits on the interstate highway system. _
  e for the Disabled,'' published by the
non-profit charity, The Opening Door, contains information on
accommodations, travel and services for the disabled. The Virginia
guide has state, national, Canadian and British distribution and is
free to those with disabilities. Organizations are asked to
reimburse the publisher $5 per guide.
   (The Opening Door, Route 2 Box 1805, Woodford, Va. 22580.) _
   Warm-weather leisure destinations are the focus of a new group
of travel guides from Bantam publishers. Two soft-cover trade-size
entries cover Mexico and Hawaii and two pocket-size guides detail
the Bahamas and Miami. _
   A hefty guide to U.S. destinations is offered in ``Frommer's
Dollarwise USA,'' published by Simon and Schuster. It breaks up the
nation into seven regions and provides practical information on
restaurants, accommodations, sights and excursions. _
   Fodor's reflects the fitness mood with a guide to ``Health and
Fitness Vacations'' in North America and the Caribbean, listing
health clubs and jogging trails. _
   Business travelers to Europe are the market for a guide from
London's The Economist magazine. ``Europe's Business Cities''
focuses on 33 economic centers and provides information about local
business services as well as dining, entertainment and sightseeing.
_
   Among numerous guide books to the sunny, warm Caribbean area is
a new ``Caribbean Choice,'' published by Warner Books. It
concentrates on accommodations. _
   ``Kidding Around London: A Young Person's Guide to the City'' is
the latest in a new series of travel guides for youngsters (John
Muir Publications@W.W. Norton distribution). This title, by Sarah
Lovett, is aimed by the traveler eight years or older and surveys
the London sights most likely to appeal to children. It also
includes capsule explanations about such things as the history of
King Arthur, the ravens in the Tower of London, and British money.
Other titles cover San Francisco and Washington, D.C. _
</TEXT>
