<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Hideaway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boulders, in Carefree, Ariz., has been chosen the top U.S.
resort for the third consecutive year in a survey by Hideaway
Report, a monthly travel newsletter for affluent business travelers.
   New to the 1989 list of top resorts picked by the sampling of
2,500 subscribers to the newsletter was Halekulani in Hawaii, which
was 11th.
   Other top resorts in the survey, in order: The Greenbrier, West
Virginia; Ritz-Carlton Laguna Niguel, California; Ritz-Carlton
Naples, Florida; Manua Lani Bay, Hawaii; Mauna Kea, Hawaii; The
Cloisters, Georgia; Ventana, California; Auberge de Soleil,
California; and the Lodge at Pebble Beach, California.
   More than 70 percent of the subscribers to Hideaway Report,
which marks its 10th anniversary this year, are corporate
presidents or chief executive officers with a median annual income
of $280,000. Reader average age is 49.
</TEXT>
