<DOCNO> AP891204-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1006EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Briefs     12-04 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Briefs,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Briefs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY706</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Places to go, things to see and do, travel bargains to have:
   _ The sixth edition of ``Where to Find It, Buy It, Eat It in New
York'' by Gerry Frank has been updated to cover the latest in New
York City dining, shopping, sightseeing and hotels.
   The author, who lives in Washington but spends weekends in
Manhattan, lists 220 places in New York he considers best and also
includes a negative list of what he calls ``Don't Bother
Restaurants.'' He also tells how to get tickets to shows and which
are the best museums, where the bargains can be found in discount
and off-price stores, and where, if you need one, to find a chimney
sweep. Also included are instructions on how to find addresses and
read maps and how to get around the big town. _
   _ A new blues and gospel pavilion opens in December in New
Orleans, featuring two nightly performances of gospel, followed by
three blues sessions. Located between two Creole cottages at 227
Bourbon Street, the pavilion will spotlight local and national
artists, with sessions beginning at 8 p.m. and continuing until 2
a.m. every night, beginning in January. The pavilion will be open
weekends for the inaugural month of December. _
   Starting in March, rail buffs can make a Oakland-Los Angeles run
in the Princess' Super Dome rail cars which will be attached to
Amtrak's Coast Starlight trains No. 11 and 14.
   The trains will be called ``California Sun Express,'' with
passengers able to make the entire trip in one day or to choose an
overnight stopover at San Luis Obispo.
   The luxury dome cars, privately owned by Princess, already
operate through Alaska through the company's Tour Alaska
subsidiary. The cars will be outfitted in oak, brass, plush
carpeting and wool upholstery, topped by curved plate glass
windows. Chefs will prepare food on board, served in a dining salon
with linen, fine china and French stemware. _
   An ancient bayou, the great Chacahoula Swamp, is venue for day
trips operated by the Atchfalaya Basin Backwater Adventure in
Gibson, La.
   The tours explore areas with ancient cypress trees and exotic
wildlife in what was the main exit of the Mississippi into the Gulf
of Mexico 5,000 to 10,000 years ago. The tour boats travel through
rugged terrain on normally non-navigable waterways. _
   For a room with a really different view, try the Undersea Lodge
in Key Largo, Fla. It's billed as the world's only underwater
hotel, with views looking out on the water 30 feet below the lagoon
at the new Key Largo Undersea Park.
   The park enables visitors to accompany professionals exploring
the remains of a shipwreck, study and swim with more than 100
marine life species, and learn about marine conservation. _
   Five historic sites in New York's Hudson Valley are clustered
along the river north of New York City and can be taken in with day
drives or train trips from a Westchester County touring base.
   Washington Irving's home at Sunnyside and the Sleepy Hollow area
he wrote about, the water-powered grist mill and house at
Philipsburg Manor, the 18th century Van Cortlandt Manor, and the
Union Church of Pocantico Hills with stained glass windows by Henri
Matisse and Marc Chagall all are within minutes of each other along
Route 9 in the Tarrytown area.
   Montgomery Place, at Annandale-on-Hudson near Kingston, N.Y., is
a restoration in progress. The manor is the ancestral home of the
Hudson Valley's Livingston family and commands views of the river
and the Catskill Mountains.
   The properties are are managed by Historic Hudson Valley in
Tarrytown, N.Y. _
   Germany's Carnival, or ``Fasching,'' starts before Christmas and
goes on through Ash Wednesday, offering American travelers the
chance to take part in the public celebrations such as Rose Monday
in Cologne, Dusseldorf and Mainz, or the ``Munich Crazy''
celebration.
   Travel costs in Germany are lower during the winter, according
to the German National Tourist Office. At the same time, visitors
will find opera, ballet and theater at the height of their seasons.
_
   Birdwatchers traveling to the Rio Grande Valley in Texas will
find over 350 species of animals _ some found nowhere else on earth
_ at the Santa Ana National Wildlife Refuge. It's located where two
major flyways converge, and birders cam learn of current sightings
and flyovers of rare species by contacting a hotline directed by
Father Tom Pincelli, a Catholic priest whose major hobby is
birdwatching. The number is (512) 542-4823.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
