<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ChristmasGifts     12-04 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Christmas Gifts,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Planning To Spend $39 Billion on Christmas Gifts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. families plan to spend an estimated $39
billion on Christmas gifts this year, up 4 percent to 5 percent
from last year, according to a survey by the Conference Board.
   In its annual Christmas spending survey, released Sunday, the
business-research organization found that American families expect
to spend an average of $335 on Christmas gifts this season, with
about half of all families spending more and half spending less.
   The figures are based on a nationwide survey of 5,000 households.
   ``The prospects of a reasonably lively Christmas season should
put to rest the irrepressible warnings that we may be moving into
recession,'' said Fabian Linden, executive director of the
Conference Board's Consumer Research Center. ``As long as the
consumer maintains a good level of spending, the economy is not
likely to take a bad turn.''
   The survey again showed families in New England to be the
biggest Christmas spenders, with an average household expenditure
of $422, although that level is 11 percent lower than last year.
Families in the West South Central region _ Arkansas, Louisiana,
Oklahoma and Texas _ plan to spend the least on Christmas gifts, an
average $264.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891204-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0751EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     12-04 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in early European trading today.
Gold prices also fell as much as $5.25 an ounce.
   Foreign currency dealers said trading was calm, with most
attention on the West German mark following the weekend summit
meeting in Malta between President Bush and Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``The summit has given the mark another boost,'' said a trader
at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt, citing hopes the continuing thaw
between East and West will create new business opportunities for
West German industry.
   ``As long as the focus is on the mark, the dollar remains under
pressure,'' he said.
   A trader in Milan said the market was ``very lethargic with very
little activity ... The absence of factors to consider is
preoccupying.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.40 yen to a closing 143.48 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 143.30 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared, with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.7755 West German marks, down from 1.7825;
1.5920 Swiss francs, down from 1.5925; 6.0635 French francs, down
from 6.0875; 2.0038 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0150; 1,308.50
Italian lire, down from 1,313.25; and 1.1650 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1662.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5685 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5665 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $408.75 a troy ounce,
down from $414.00 bid late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $409.90.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $409.75, down from $415 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.79 to close at a bid $409.31.
   Silver fell in London to a bid price of $5.66 a troy ounce, down
from Friday's $5.70.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891204-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0753EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-04 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Rise in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index resumed its
rise to new highs today, while the dollar gained against the
Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which closed at
record highs for seven consecutive trading days before slipping
136.11 points on Friday, climbed 171.19 points, or 0.46 percent,
today to 37,303.87. The previous record of 37,268.79 was set
Thursday.
   Securities dealers said the market reacted favorably to amity
shown at the U.S.-Soviet summit, and investors actively bought
shares related to business with the Soviet Union and East bloc
countries.
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange, which lists
most major shares, was estimated at 1.2 billion shares, compared
with Friday's 1.1 billion.
   On the currency market, the dollar closed at 143.48 yen, up 0.40
yen from Friday's close of 143.08 yen. It opened at the day's low
of 143.37 and rose to 143.70 yen in midmorning trading, but eased
in the afternoon.
   Traders said the quiet mood should continue during a week that
promises little fresh economic news to trade on until Friday's
report on U.S. unemployment data for November.
   The market will watch Friday's report carefully for clues to
possible interest easing moves by the U.S. Federal Reserve, they
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
