<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Maxwell     12-04 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Maxwell,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maxwell Sets May as New Target Date for Start of European Paper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Robert Maxwell said Monday his new
newspaper, The European, will begin publishing on May 11, 1990, one
year later than originally planned.
   The newspaper, first planned as a daily, will be published
weekly, on Fridays, and will be printed in Britain, Germany,
Hungary and other unspecified countries, Maxwell said in a
statement.
   Maxwell, owner of Mirror Group Newspapers, said the broadsheet
English-language paper will be sold throughout Europe for the
equivalent of 78 cents and will include news, pictures, sports and
financial services.
   Maxwell said in March the paper would begin publishing this
autumn, instead of May as originally planned. He said at the time
research had convinced him the paper should begin as a weekly 'to
establish a base from which daily publication could begin.''
   He said then that differences between the French and British
executives of The European were part of the reason for postponing
its launch.
   Maxwell said Monday the newspaper's editor would be Ian Watson,
now deputy editor of London's Sunday Telegraph.
   Maxwell runs a publishing business in 28 countries with 40,000
employees, including Macmillan Inc., the U.S. publishing company.
</TEXT>
