<DOCNO> AP891204-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-Accountant     12-04 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Accountant,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Leaves Intact Award Accounting Firm Ordered to Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today left intact a $1.24
million award a leading accounting firm was ordered to pay to a
water heater manufacturer.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Ernst &amp;
Whinney, the accounting firm sued successfuly by Bradford-White
Corp., which makes water heaters at a Middleville, Mich., plant.
   Bradford-White, a Tennessee corporation, in 1981 bought out
another water heater manufacturer, W.L. Jackson of Chattanooga,
Tenn. In connection with that deal, Bradford-White accused Ernst &amp;
Whinney, the accountants for Jackson, of falsely reporting
Jackson's financial condition.
   The accounting firm had reported Jackson was in financial
trouble. But Bradford-White said Ernst &amp; Whinney concealed just how
bad matters were, and contended that Jackson was on the verge of
bankruptcy. The lawsuit alleged that Ernst &amp; Whinney violated
federal and Tennessee securities laws.
   Bradford-White was awarded $1.24 million by a federal jury in
Philadelphia. Bradford-White has offices in that city.
   A federal judge later overturned the award, ruling that the
verdict was inconsisent with some of the jury's own finding.
   But the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated the award
last April.
   The appeals court said there might have been some
inconsistencies, but there is no doubt the jury believed Ernst &amp;
Whinney misstated Jackson's net worth.
   The appeals court also rejected the accounting firm's claim that
Bradford-White waited too long to sue.
   Ernst &amp; Whinney waived any such claim at the trial and cannot
rely on it on appeal, the 3rd Circuit court said.
   The case is Ernst &amp; Whinney vs. Bradford-White Corp., 89-604.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
