<FIRST>r f BC-CoalProduction     12-04 0137</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Coal Production,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Reports Weekly Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic coal production totaled 16.1
million tons during the week ending Nov. 25, down 22 percent from
the 20.6 million tons produced in the previous week because of the
Thanksgiving holiday, the Department of Energy reported Monday.
   The U.S. coal industry produced 16.7 million tons in the same
week last year, according to the department's Energy Information
Administration.
   Wyoming ranked first among the 27 coal-producing states during
the week with 3.3 million tons produced. West Virginia was second
at 2.3 million tons and Kentucky was third at 2.25 million tons,
the department said.
   Domestic coal production so far this year is 878.1 million tons,
5.5 percent above last year's production at this time, the agency
said.
   The week's production accounts for bituminous and lignite coal.
</TEXT>
