<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   12-04 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Drift Lower in Moderate Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade as a lack of news over the
weekend reduced interest in the market.
   ``There was not a lot of news over the weekend,'' to stimulate
buying interest, said analyst Steve Freed of Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc. in Chicago
   A lack of export demand for U.S. soybeans and favorable weather
in South American crop areas put pressure on soybean futures, Freed
said.
   Corn prices were lower, despite Friday's announcement of a
purchase by the Soviet Union. Analysts say that news had been
factored into the market.
   Also, word that the Soviet Union has bid for 400,000 metric tons
of wheat under the export bonus program failed to lift wheat prices
today.
   Analysts said investors were awaiting the outcome of this week's
U.S.-Soviet grain talks to determine the level of Soviet buying
interest.
   In early trading, wheat was 2 cents to 3 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.06 a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 2\ cents lower with December at $2.32\ a bushel; oats were
a \ cent to 1 cent lower with December at $1.43{ a bushel; soybeans
were 3 cents to 4{ cents lower with January at $5.72\ a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were generally lower in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Pork prices were pressured by lower hog cash prices due to light
packer demand and profit taking by investors in frozen pork bellies.
   Live cattle futures were pushed lower by expectations of lower
cash prices for fed cattle this week, a traditional period of low
weak retail beef demand.
   Live cattle were .02 cent to .20 cent lower with December at 75
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .03 cent higher
with January at 82.77 cents a pound; hogs were .30 cent lower to
.10 cent higher with December at 50.45 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .22 cent lower to unchanged with February at 57.50
cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled higher and pork prices lower in
Friday's trading.
</TEXT>
