<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0345</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was higher in choppy trading
today.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 6.83 points at
2,754.48 at 2 pm EST.
   Advancing issues narrowly edged out declining ones on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 731 issues higher, 713 lower and 487
unchanged.
   Volume totaled 110.80 million shares on the NYSE.
   Some analysts, noting that trading volume was light, said they
didn't attach great significance to today's movements.
   ``There doesn't seem to be a tremendous interest on one side or
the other,'' said Bill Raftery, an analyst at Smith Barney, Harris
Upham &amp; Co.
   Wall Street mostly shrugged off today's report by the Commerce
Department that orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods
fell 0.2 percent in October to their lowest level since July.
   The report was the latest indicator showing the economy slowing
as the year draws to an end. The manufacturing sector has been
particularly weak, prompting concern of possible layoffs and a rise
in the unemployment rate.
   The Commerce Department also said sales of new homes edged down
0.5 percent in October, the sixth monthly decline of the year but a
major improvement over September.
   The NYSE's composite index was up 0.31 at 193.97.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had
fallen 1.13 to 374.45.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, IBM was up 2 at 99[,
Chevron had gained | at 71 and USX had jumped 2[ to 36~ amid
continued takeover speculation involving corporate raider Carl
Icahn.
   United Airlines' parent UAL had surged 6} to 180} following news
that investment group Condor Partners has raised its stake in UAL
to 11.8 percent and is holding talks with the company and its major
unions. The airline's pilots and top managers have been trying to
buy the company for several months.
   Occidental Petroleum was down [ at 30[ and Windmere had fallen |
to 8].
</TEXT>
