<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Machinists     12-04 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Machinists,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Enters 10th Month, Talks With Management</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the Eastern Airlines
Machinists, whose walkout entered its 10th month Monday, says there
is new dialogue with management but that his membership remains
committed to the strike.
   ``There's no way you can just blink away the trauma that people
have been through,'' said Charles E. Bryan, president of the
Machinists District 100. ``I believe that most everybody looks at
it that they've invested nine months and they don't want to lose
that. We've stayed solid so long.''
   Bryan disclosed that he had a three-hour meeting last Thursday
in Washington with Eastern officials and federal mediator Harry
Bickford.
   All agreed ``that nobody will put any spins on it,'' Bryan said.
``We met, and we'll have more meetings.''
   Company spokesman Robin Matell confirmed the meeting with Tom
Matthews, Eastern's senior vice president for human resources, and
Al Gibson, vice president for labor relations.
   ``They agreed to maintain a dialogue,'' Matell said.
   He wouldn't give any other details. He said the meeting was the
company's first with the Machinists union since Oct. 13.
   The latest session came the week after the Air Line Pilots
Association and the Transport Workers Union, representing flight
attendants, called off their sympathy strikes. They had joined the
8,500 mechanics and other Eastern ground workers represented by the
Machinists in walking out March 4 when 1{ years of federally
mediated talks.
   Matell said management met Monday with the flight attendants
union, will meet again Friday, and plans four days of negotiations
beginning Dec. 18. The company is waiting to hear from a federal
mediator on the next round of talks with the pilots, Matell said.
   The pilots and flight attendants are in negotiations on new
contracts and also on the return to work of their members.
   Bryan said the other unions' actions didn't affect his union's
strike. He noted that Eastern told the returning strikers they had
no jobs for them and they would have to go on a waiting list.
   ``I think it certainly was predictable that they are playing the
hardest of hardball, in the most arrogant way. (Eastern has been)
very condescending, saying: `We don't have any jobs but we might do
them a favor and take some of them back.' ''
   Bryan, who contends that Chairman Frank Lorenzo has been out to
break Eastern's unions and cannibalize the carrier since his Texas
Air Corp. bought it nearly four years ago, has portrayed the
unions' struggle in terms of good versus evil. He now draws
comparisons to Eastern Europe.
   Bryan denied that his union's talk of going underground implied
illegal activity. Eastern last week gained a preliminary injunction
ordering the Machinists to refrain from harassment, threats and
trespassing.
   Bryan said the union plans a range of activities that includes
an organized effort to urge anyone associated with the travel
industry to boycott Eastern and Texas Air.
   The company says it has 2,800 mechanics, including about 300
Machinists who have crossed picket lines, and rejects suggestions
of maintenance difficulties.
   There were some 4,500 Machinists mechanics who struck.
   Bryan was interviewed here Sunday after attending the Florida
Democratic Party's conference. He chatted with House Majority
Leader Richard Gephardt, who urged him to keep up his fight because
``it's important for this country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
