<FIRST>r f AM-EngineersUnion     12-04 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Engineers Union,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Union Veteran To Lead Operating Engineers Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Dugan Jr., president of the
330,000-member International Union of Operating Engineers the past
four years, announced Monday that he would step down effective Feb.
1.
   Dugan, 59, will be succeeded by Frank Hanley, also 59, a New
York City native who has been the union's No. 2 official, general
secretary treasurer, since 1979. From 1975-79 Hanley was a union
vice president.
   Dugan, president of the union since 1985, gave no reason for his
resignation. He informed the union's board of his decision at a
meeting Monday.
   Hanley had mounted an unusual protest in 1985 when Dugan was
hand-picked to succeed J.C. Turner as president, writing other
union leaders and requesting an open election. But he dropped the
request after meeting with Dugan.
   Dugan, of Phoenix, last month was re-elected to another two-year
term on the AFL-CIO's Executive Council, the labor federation's
governing body. It was unclear Monday whether he would complete
that term or ask that Hanley be allowed to take his place.
</TEXT>
