<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1630EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Deloitte-Touche     12-04 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Deloitte-Touche,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deloitte, Touch Ross Complete Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deloitte Haskins &amp; Sells and Touche Ross, two of
the country's biggest accounting firms, completed a merger of their
U.S. operations on Monday.
   A final agreement uniting the two accounting and professional
services firms was signed in New York.
   The combined company in the United States, called Deloitte &amp;
Touche, will have 19,700 partners and employees working at 100
offices around the country, the firms said in a news release.
   Deloitte &amp; Touche will rank third among the Big Six acccounting
firms based on projected 1989 revenue of $1.9 billion, they said.
   The new firm is part of a wider international partnership being
formed and to be known as Deloitte Ross Tohmatsu.
   J. Michael Cook, Deloitte &amp; Touche chief executive officer, said
the international merger is scheduled to be completed on Jan. 2.
   Efforts by Deloitte Haskins &amp; Sells and Touche Ross
International to create a worldwide link had suffered a setback
earlier in the autumn when the British arm of Deloitte decided to
join forces with a different accounting firm.
   The British partners of Deloitte Haskins and Coopers &amp; Lybrand
in October announced a plan to merge, creating Britain's largest
accounting firm with about 10,500 employees and fee income of about
$670 million a year.
   Deloitte &amp; Touche said Monday that international member firms of
Deloitte Ross Tohmatsu recently met in New York and approved
formation of the new company.
   The organization will have members in Australia, Canada, Hong
Kong, Japan, France, Italy, the Middle East, Latin America, the
Netherlands, Singapore, the United Kingdom, West Germany and
elsewhere.
</TEXT>
