<FIRST>u f AM-UAL 1stLd-Writethru   12-04 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL, 1st Ld-Writethru,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Revised UAL Buyout Bid Expected Near $5 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs to note $179.50 is closing stock price, SUBS
16th graf pvs with Machinists saying no talks scheduled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A revised employee buyout proposal being readied
by UAL Corp. executives could value the parent of United Airlines
at between $4.75 billion and $5.42 billion, sharply lower than an
earlier, aborted proposal, analysts said Monday.
   Analysts said a new bid, the successor to the failed $6.75
billion buyout led by United's pilots union and management, might
be unveiled in time for consideration at a scheduled Dec. 13
meeting of UAL's board of directors.
   UAL representatives are expected to present details of a new
buyout plan to United's flight attendants' union on Wednesday.
   The company has met recently with U.S. and Japanese bankers,
representatives of the United pilots' union and Coniston Partners,
an investor group that is pushing for a sale or restructuring of
UAL.
   UAL stock rose $5.50 a share to $179.50 in composite New York
Stock Exchange trading, adding to Friday's $12.50 a share gain.
   Patricia Friend, outgoing president of the United chapter of the
Association of Flight Attendants, said Monday that a revised buyout
plan may be presented at this week's meeting.
   But she added: ``We're a long way away from an agreement that
would require a vote.''
   Nevertheless, airline industry analysts and stock-market
investors speculated that the pieces of a new bid were falling
rapidly into place. Chicago-based UAL told its employees on Friday
that executives were working on a revised proposal for employee
purchase of the airline company.
   ``It looks like they're really trying to put together a takeover
deal here,'' said Stephen Dexter, an analyst in Chicago with Kemper
Financial Services Inc.
   The $300 a share offer from the pilots, UAL senior management
and British Airways PLC fell through after the group failed to get
the necessary financing. Since then, UAL stock has traded sharply
lower.
   Dexter figured the new deal would be for $210 to $240 a share.
Another analyst said he had spoken with a United pilot who ``threw
out a $220 number.''
   Analyst Samuel Buttrick of Kidder Peabody &amp; Co., said lenders
who balked at and doomed the $300-a-share offer probably would
agree to finance a deal at $225.
   UAL management is believed to be seeking strong commitments from
lenders and the company's three major unions before announcing a
revised buyout effort.
   The earlier pilot-management bid failed in October when lenders
refused to finance it, citing the strong opposition of the
Machinists union. The Machinists represent about 25,000 of UAL's
70,000 employees.
   United pilots long have sought ownership of the carrier, the
nation's second-largest, and are believed to be working with
management on the new proposal. Spokesman Hank Krakowski of the
United chapter of the Air Line Pilots Association, declined comment
Monday.
   Brian Freeman, an adviser to the Machinists union, said no
meetings between representatives of his union and UAL had been held
recently and he knew of none scheduled.
   Officials of the Machinists union in Washington and California
did not return telephone calls.
   UAL spokesman Russell Mack said the company's financial advisers
already had met with the pilots and were planning to meet with the
flight attendants, who also had not joined the earlier
pilots-management buyout group. He said he did not know whether the
advisers had met with the Machinists.
   The company is being pressed toward a sale or restructuring by
Coniston, the New York-based investor group that is threatening to
launch a drive for shareholder consent to oust 13 of the company's
15 directors and create a five-member board.
   Coniston has boosted its UAL stake to 11.8 percent of the
company's outstanding common shares from 9.7 percent, general
partner Keith Gollust said Monday. Gollust declined comment on the
buyout situation.
   He said Coniston had been in contact with UAL and the unions and
was holding back on launching its consent solicitation.
   ``We are monitoring the situation closely,'' Gollust said in a
telephone interview. ``We will commence our consent solicitation if
and when we conclude it would be advantageous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
