<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-04 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>RESENDING FOR ALL NEEDING</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed against major foreign
currencies Monday as traders renewed their interest in the West
German mark.
   Gold prices tumbled more than $12 an ounce, retreating after a
strong advance recently. Traders said last week that bullion was
getting overvalued and that such a drop was possible.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
dropped $12.50 a troy ounce to $401.10. Republic National Bank in
New York quoted a troy ounce of gold bullion at $401.20 as of 4
p.m. EST, $12.30 lower than Friday's late bid.
   Marc Chandler of Money Market Services International in Chicago
said currency dealers directed attention mainly to the West German
mark and bought on speculation that the country will have to raise
interest rates to stem a possible surge in economic growth.
   The Swiss franc was weighed down by heavy selling pressure
related to Switzerland's lower interest rates compared with its
European neighbors, particularly West Germany, Chandler said.
   Trading in dollars is expected to be light this week ahead of
Friday's potentially market-moving report on U.S. unemployment.
   A government report that said U.S. factory orders fell 0.2
percent in October evoked little reaction among dollar traders
although it reinforced the notion that economic growth is sluggish.
   Currency dealers overseas, meanwhile, were said to be closing
out positions before the year end. Market volume tends to dry up
toward the end of the year, when dealers are hesitant to risk
profits or add to losses.
   Dealers also were expected to remain reluctant to trade heavily
while they assess the outcome of the weekend's superpower summit
and what it will mean for the future of the dollar and the world
economy.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing 143.48 Japanese yen from
143.08 yen at Friday's close. Later, in London, it rose further to
143.57 yen and, in New York, the dollar rose to 143.65 from 143.40
late Friday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.5638 from $1.5665 late
Friday. In New York, the pound fell to $1.56225 from $1.5625 late
Friday.
   Other dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday's late
quotes included: 1.78425 West German marks, down from 1.7865;
1.6065 Swiss francs, up from 1.5995; 6.0915 French francs, down
from 6.1020; 1,314.50 Italian lire, down from 1,316.50; and 1.16365
Canadian dollars, down from 1.6505.
   Selected late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Friday were: 1.7808 West German marks, down from 1.7825; 1.5995
Swiss francs, up from 1.5925; 6.0800 French francs, down from
6.0875; 2.0095 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0150; 1,312.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,313.25; and 1.1640 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1662.
   Precious metals prices declined in what dealers described as a
technically motivated correction to a powerful runup.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $406.25 a troy ounce
from $414 bid late Friday. In Zurich, the metal fell to a closing
bid of $408 from $415 bid late Friday. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold
fell $2.79 to close at $409.31.
   Silver for current delivery slid to $5.509 a troy ounce from
$5.663 on New York's Comex. Silver bullion fell in London to a late
bid price of $5.60 a troy ounce from $5.70 bid late Friday.
</TEXT>
