<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-NYNEX     12-04 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYNEX,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Return to Jobs, Telephone Company Tackles Backlog</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 40,000 NYNEX Corp. workers returned to work
Monday, 116 days after they began a bitter strike, and began
tackling a tremendous backlog on phone installations.
   ``Everybody's now back to work. We are delighted to see them
all. The priority is attacking this backlog,'' said NYNEX spokesman
John Bonomo.
   Members of the Communication Workers of America at NYNEX and its
subsidiary New York Telephone and 20,000 members of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers at New England
Telephone struck the regional telephone company on Aug. 6. The
strike affected 10 million customers.
   Officials of the Communications Workers of America had predicted
widespread animosity when their members returned, but that
apparently was not the case Monday.
   ``People are reporting back to work with a few minor incidents
that have not led to anything serious,'' said Ron Woods, CWA area
director for downstate New York.
   That week other strikes began in 20 states and all were resolved
by September except for the one at NYNEX.
   The IBEW returned to work Nov. 20 after its members and the CWA
reached agreement with NYNEX on regional issues. Local issues
continued to hang up the CWA negotiations until Nov. 23.
   A ratification vote ended Friday with 85 percent of the members
approving the contract.
   New York Telephone said it was trying to fill more than 100,000
service orders and a potential backlog of another 150,000
installations with customers who withheld orders during the work
stoppage.
   Filling those orders will take until May, the company said.
Repair work, it said, is up to date.
   To clear the backlog, New York Telephone initiated a five-point
program that includes increasing its installation workforce by
nearly 50 percent.
</TEXT>
