<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     12-04 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures End Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold weather in parts of the nation helped boost
heating oil futures prices Monday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   Prices of other energy futures, including crude oil and unleaded
gasoline, closed mixed.
   No. 2 home heating oil for January delivery advanced 0.88 cent
to 63.79 cents a gallon. Contracts for delivery through June posted
gains of between 0.09 cent and 0.65 cent.
   Energy analysts said strength in London's gasoil market spilled
over into U.S. markets as low water levels on the Rhine River
continued to disrupt shipments. Gasoil is the British equivalent of
heating oil.
   ``It creates logistical problems and gives our market a higher
call,'' said Jack Unger, energy broker with Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures.
   Icy temperatures in some parts of the country also gave the
heating oil market a lift, he said.
   Profit-taking, meanwhile, erased the gains in the crude oil
pits. The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, slipped 5 cents to $20.25 a
barrel after trading as high as $20.62 during the session.
   Contracts for later delivery closed narrowly mixed.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for January delivery closed 0.41
cent higher at 52.52 cents a gallon, while later contracts posted
slightly smaller gains.
</TEXT>
