<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 1903EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WallResigns-Texas     12-04 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Resigns-Texas,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall's Departure Unfair, But Not Surprising, Say Some Texans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   M. Danny Wall's resignation Monday as the nation's
chief thrift regulator came as no surprise in Texas, where much of
the industry's problems have been centered.
   Politicians and industry officials said they believed Wall had
become a symbol of the industry's failings and, as such, had to be
replaced as head of the Office of Thrift Supervision.
   Rep. Steve Bartlett, a Texas Republican who also serves on the
Banking Committee, said, ``Danny Wall was part of the solution, not
part of the problem.'' But Bartlett added, ``I think (the
resignation) was inevitable. That's not to say it was fair.''
   Although it was Wall's slowness in closing down Lincoln Savings
&amp; Loan Association that was the catalyst for the current wave of
criticism, Bartlett said, ``I think Danny Wall would have been,
even without Lincoln, a controversial person because he was solving
problems.
   ``He left the savings and loan industry stronger than when he
came in,'' Bartlett said.
   Wall was chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board from July
1987 until last August, when its function as the federal regulator
of the savings and loan industry was transferred to the new Office
of Thrift Supervision.
   The Texas thrift landscape is much changed from Wall's Southwest
Plan, devised last year to bring new capital into the industry.
   The mergers, designed to take advantage of tax laws before they
expired on Dec. 31, 1988, have been criticized by some who complain
the deals were too expensive.
   Under the plan, steel companies, home builders, investors and
other non-traditional thrift owners bought up groups of insolvent
institutions and packaged them into new entities.
   Four of the five largest Texas thrifts were created under the
Southwest Plan.
   ``In the final accounting, which won't be done for several
years, these Southwest Plan deals might look better than they do
today, based on the cost of resolutions that the RTC (Resolution
Trust Corp.) is experiencing,'' said Bill Ferguson, an industry
consultant in Dallas.
   ``I guess he had just taken about all the flak he could take,''
said H.R. ``Bum'' Bright, whose Bright Banc Savings Association was
seized by regulators earlier this year.
   ``We thought he had fundamentally a reasonable program on his
original Southwest Plan, one that would work out that would be less
cost to the taxpayers than the subsequent plans appear to be from
our standpoint.''
   James L. Pledger, commissioner of the Savings and Loan
Department of Texas, said, ``Danny Wall had the toughest job in
government because of the magnitude of the problems.''
   He praised Wall's attempts to focus public attention on the
healthy portion of the industry.
   ``He has been able to ... maintain a approach that recognizes
that a large portion of the thrift industry is profitable and is
doing well.''
</TEXT>
