<FIRST>r f BC-NuclearFine     12-04 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nuclear Fine,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Power Corp. Nuclear Plant Fined $50,000 by NRC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRYSTAL RIVER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida Power Corp. has been fined
$50,000 for allegedly failing to make sure safety equipment was up
to standards at its Crystal River nuclear plant, the U.S. Nuclear
Regulatory Commission said Monday.
   The alleged violations involved water pumps and valves that were
of commercial quality and didn't meet federal specifications for
nuclear safety equipment, said NRC spokesman Ken Clark in Atlanta.
   In one case, the impeller of a backup pump used to bring in sea
water for cooling had only five vanes instead of the required
seven. ``For seven weeks, that pump was not capable of fulfilling
its safety function,'' Clark said.
   The St. Petersburg-based utility, which has 30 days to either
pay the fine or appeal it, has corrected all of the violations
listed in the NRC fine, Clark said.
   He said the alleged violations came as the utility was in the
process of trying to upgrade its safety equipment to meet new, more
stringent guidelines imposed by the NRC last March.
   ``We were making an honest effort to meet federal guidelines
within the window of direction we had from the NRC,'' Jacobs said.
   The utility was fined $100,000 by the NRC in September for the
alleged inability of some safety equipment to operate under
post-accident conditions, Jacobs said.
</TEXT>
