<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-GamingPatents     12-04 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gaming Patents,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gaming Device Maker Sues Japanese Company for Patent Infringement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The No. 1 gaming device maker in the world
filed a federal lawsuit Monday against a Japanese company, claiming
the foreign firm is using three of the larger company's patents to
make slot machines.
   International Game Technology filed the U.S. District Court
lawsuit against Tokyo-based Sigma Inc. and Sigma Game Inc., a
Sparks, Nev., subsidiary that makes the slot machines.
   ``We believe that most if not all of Sigma's slot machines on
the market infringe on our patents,'' said San Francisco attorney
John Hughes, representing Reno-based IGT.
   Mike Stefanik, director of operations for Sigma Game, said the
company was unaware of the suit, which claims its slot machines are
copies of patented IGT slot machines.
   ``Everybody uses these types of slot machines,'' Stefanik said.
``So their reasoning behind the lawsuit is beyond me.''
   Hughes said IGT wants to force Sigma to change its slot machines
so they don't use patented IGT slot devices.
   IGT also seeks unspecified damages to compensate for any
business the company might have lost because of the alleged patent
infringement, Hughes said.
   ``These devices were patented for a reason _ because they have
unique elements,'' Hughes said.
   IGT, which had revenue of $140 million last year, has a similar
lawsuit pending against a different Japanese company, Universal Co.
Ltd., and its Nevada-based subsidiary company, Universal
Distributing of Nevada.
   In that lawsuit, patent infringement isn't claimed, but IGT
alleges Universal used IGT's trade secrets in manufacturing a video
poker game named ``Player's Edge.''
</TEXT>
