<FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 2304EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-DeLorean-AppealsCourt     12-04 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-DeLorean-Appeals Court,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Appeals Court Upholds Judgment Against DeLorean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ruled Monday that a
British court's award of a $54 million default judgment against
former automaker John Z. DeLorean can be enforced against him.
   A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
upheld a lower court's ruling against DeLorean, who tried to
prevent enforcement of the British court's award.
   Last month in London, however, English High Court Judge Peter
Gibson overturned a lower court order that allowed legal documents
in the case to be served on DeLorean at his home in New Jersey,
outside the jurisdiction of the English courts.
   ``It follows that all subsequent orders made against Mr.
DeLorean will fall away,'' Gibson said in his Nov. 24 ruling.
   In October 1987, the High Court of Justice, Chancery Court
division in London awarded the default judgment against DeLorean to
DSQ Property Co. Ltd.
   DSQ Property, formerly DeLorean Motor Cars Ltd. of Belfast,
Northern Ireland, then sued in January 1989 in federal court in New
York City to enforce the British court's judgment against DeLorean,
who had produced cars through DeLorean Motor Cars Ltd.
   The cars were distributed in the United States by DeLorean Motor
Co., which owned 75 percent of DeLorean Motor Cars Ltd.
   The New York federal court transferred the case to U.S. District
Court in Detroit, where Judge Richard Suhrheinrich ruled that the
British court's judgment could be enforced against DeLorean.
DeLorean appealed, but the 6th Circuit appeals court ruled against
him Monday.
   In last month's ruling in England, Gibson said that in DSQ's
application to serve documents on DeLorean outside British
jurisdiction, there had been ``serious non-disclosures'' of
matters, including the existence of proceedings against DeLorean in
the U.S. unrelated to DSQ.
   Mike Morganroth, a lawyer for DeLorean, said Monday night that
the 6th Circuit Court ruling was moot since the British High Court
had set aside the judgment against DeLorean.
   DSQ Property Co. Ltd. was created as the corporate successor to
DeLorean Motor Cars Ltd., which went into financial receivership.
   The British court's judgment and DeLorean's settlement with the
bankruptcy trustee of DeLorean Motor Co., which filed for
bankruptcy in October 1982, resulted from claims involving the
design of the DeLorean automobile.
   The 6th Circuit appellate court rejected DeLorean's arguments
that his settlement with the bankruptcy trustee prevented
recognition or enforcement of the British court's award in the
United States. The court also rejected DeLorean's arguments that he
had not been properly served with documents to inform him of the
British court's award.
   Morganroth said he expects DSQ Property to appeal the British
court's ruling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
